rt.com>{{cite web|url=http://au.eurosport.com/football/gianluca-pagliuca_prs4743/person.shtml|title=Gianluca Pagliuca|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Serie A]]: [[1990\u201391 Serie A|1990\u201391]]\n* [[Coppa Italia]]: [[1987\u201388 Coppa Italia|1987\u201388]], [[1988\u201389 Coppa Italia|1988\u201389]], [[1993\u201394 Coppa Italia|1993\u201394]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]]: 1991\n* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]: [[1989-90 European Cup Winners' Cup|1989\u201390]]\n\n;F.C. Internazionale Milano<ref name=eurosport.com/>\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup|1997\u201398]]\n\n===International===\n;[[Italy national football team|Italy]]<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/gianluca-pagliuca/4436/|title=G. Pagliuca|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[FIFA World Cup]]: Runner-up [[FIFA World Cup|1994]]\n\n===Individual===\n;F.C. Internazionale Milano<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/italpoy.html |title=Italy - Footballer of the Year |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121013030/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/italpoy.html |archivedate=21 January 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n*Pirata d'Oro (Internazionale Player Of The Year): 1995<ref>{{cite web|author=Inter.it staff, inter(a t)inter.it |url=http://inter.it/aas/news/reader?L=en&N=24665&stringa=%22player%20of%20the%20year%22 |title=F.C. Internazionale Milano |publisher=Inter.it |date=17 November 2006 |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* [[Guerin d'Oro]]: [[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397]]\n\n;[[Bologna F.C.]]<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\"/>\n* Guerin d'Oro: 2004\u201305\n\n===Orders===\n:[[File:Cavaliere OMRI BAR.svg|left|50px]] 5th Class/Knight: ''[[Italian orders of merit|Cavaliere Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana]]'': 1991<ref name=\"5th class\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Onorificenze.aspx?pag=3045&qIdOnorificenza=&cognome=&nome=&daAnno=1800&aAnno=2014&luogoNascita=&testo=&ordinamento=2 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150320014016/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Onorificenze.aspx?pag=3045&qIdOnorificenza=&cognome=&nome=&daAnno=1800&aAnno=2014&luogoNascita=&testo=&ordinamento=2 |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 March 2015 |title=Onoreficenze |website=quirinale.it |language=Italian |date=30 September 1991 |accessdate=19 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{FIFA player|77257|Gianluca Pagliuca}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=10705}}\n\n{{Pirata d'Oro}}\n{{navboxes colour\n|title=Italy squads\n|bg= #0066bc\n|fg= #FFFFFF\n|list1=\n{{Italy football squad 1988 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Italy squad 1990 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Italy squad 1994 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Italy men's football squad 1996 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Italy squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pagliuca, Gianluca}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Bologna F.C. 1909 players]]\n[[Category:Ascoli Calcio 1898 F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:1990 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Italy B international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer statistics:Fix overlinking.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gianluca_Pagliuca"}
{"title_page": "Crossmakelagher", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:R205 national secondary road \u2013 Crossmakellagher.jpg|thumb|R205 road in Crossmakellagher townland]]\n'''Crossmakelagher''', also written Crossmakellagher or Crossmakellegher, ({{Irish derived place name|Cros Mhic Ch\u00e9ileachair, meaning 'McKelleher's Crossroad; Locals abbreviate it as 'Cross'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nCrossmakelagher is bounded on the north by [[Cavanaquill]] and [[Killynaff]] townlands, on the west by [[Tonyhallagh]] and [[Tonyrevan]] townlands, on the south by [[Bellaheady]] and [[Killarah]] townlands in [[Kildallan]] parish and on the east by [[Cormeen]] townland in [[Kildallan]] parish and [[Lecharrownahone]] townland. Its chief geographical features are the [[Shannon-Erne Waterway]], a small plantation, a pond, a quarry, a spring well and several dug wells. Crossmakelagher is traversed by the regional [[R205 road (Ireland)|R205 road]], minor roads and rural lanes and the disused [[Cavan and Leitrim Railway]]. The townland covers 197 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nUp until the 18th century it was divided into two different townlands, the part north of the present R205 main road was Crossmakelagher and the part between the R205 and the Shannon-Erne Waterway was called Drumcon (Irish derived place name|Druim Con, meaning 'The Ridge of the Greyhounds'). Crossmakelagher was also called ''Barne'' at the time (Irish derived place name Bearn, meaning 'A Gap').\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Cross''.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf National Archives Dublin]</ref><ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref>\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''CrossmcKelagher'' and the other subdivisions as ''Barne'' and ''Drumgoone''.\n\nThe 1665 Down Survey map depicts the north part as ''Crosmckellagher'' and the south part as ''Drumcone''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref> \n\n[[William Petty]]'s 1685 map depicts them as ''Crossemckelaher'' and ''Drumcon''.<ref>[http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#c=Cavan]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 4 June 1611, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted ''one poll of Barne to Hugh McManus Oge Magauran''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA211&dq=boely+Killmuriertagh&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBzuSOzbjfAhWjQxUIHZeBAogQ6AEINTAC#v=onepage&q=boely%20Killmuriertagh&f=false]</ref> He was the great-grandson of a previous Magauran chief, [[Tom\u00e1s mac Maghnus M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]] who ruled from 1512 to 1532. His father Manus Og lived in [[Cor, Templeport|Cor]] and received a pardon in 1586.\n\nIn the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 23 June 1610, along with other lands forming the Manor of Calva, King [[James VI and I]] granted ''two polls of Crosse to Hugh Culme''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA194&lpg=PA194&dq=Kilclogen&source=bl&ots=sGT6qXkfxh&sig=9RJ9eMs-ATQuJW4vgmqxm_501_Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjrp7WOoqzfAhUIDuwKHYsRAHMQ6AEwB3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Kilclogen&f=false]</ref>  In the same year Culme surrendered his interest to Walter Talbot of Ballyconnell. Walter Talbot died on 26 June 1625 at Ballyconnell and his son James Talbot succeeded to the Ballyconnell estate aged just 10 years. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 20 September 1630 found that James Talbot was seized of ''two polls of Crosse'', along with other lands.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PA11-IA1&dq=Derrogeny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52JidpKzfAhVCyaQKHb4_BlgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=Derrogeny&f=false}]</ref> James Talbot married Helen Calvert, the daughter of [[George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore]] of Maryland, USA, in 1635. In the aftermath of the Irish Rebellion of 1641 James Talbot's estate was confiscated because he was a Catholic and he was granted an estate in 1655 at Castle Rubey, County Roscommon instead. He died in 1687. Talbot's land in Crossmakelagher was distributed as follows-\n\nIn the Hearth Money Rolls compiled on 29 September 1663<ref>''The Hearth Money Rolls for the Baronies of Tullyhunco and Tullyhaw, County Cavan'', edited by Rev. Francis J. McKiernan, in Breifne Journal. Vol. I, No. 3 (1960), pp. 247-263</ref> there were two Hearth Tax payers in  ''Liosmackelagher- Cormucke McKelacher and Patricke McKelacher''.\t\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the townland as belonging to Captain Gwilliams (i.e. the landlord of Ballyconnell, Captain Thomas Gwyllym) and the tenants as ''Edward Rely & Others''. The same survey also lists ''Barne'' and ''Drumgoone'' as belonging to Captain Gwilliams. A further confirming  grant dated 11 August 1666 was made from King [[Charles II of England]] to Thomas Guyllym of Ballyconnell included ''52 acres 1 rood and 24 perches in Crossmackillagher, alias Crosse, alias Barne and part of the same 10 acres and 16 perches''. The grant also included ''47 acres 2 roods in Dromcowen, alias Drumgoney.''<ref>[https://archive.org/details/op1244157-1001/page/n45]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]] Eleanor Reynolds of ''Lissanore'' made a deposition about the rebellion in Lissanover which included-\n''Ellenor Reinolds of Late of Lissanore in the County of Cauan widow aged 46 yeares or thereabouts duly sworne etc. .. She further saith that in May 1642 this deponents mother not being able (because of age & weaknes) to goe to Croghan Castle was left behind with some of the tenants at Lissanore aforesaid, where she was about the tyme aforesaid barbarously murthered by one '''ffarell Groome mc Kellogher of CrossemacKellogher''' who confessed the said barbarous fact to divers persons that voluntarily did depose the same to be true.''<ref>[http://1641.tcd.ie/deposition.php?depID=832167r164]</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the name as ''Crossmakellagher''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list twelve tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Cross&search=Search], in the ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Crossmakelagher Valuation Office Field books are available for 1839-1841.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00400.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=&townland=crossmakeelagher&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=&townland=crossmakelagher&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists ten landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=190620&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=Crossmakelagher]</ref>\n\n==Census==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Males\n! Females\n! Total Houses\n! Uninhabited\n|-\n| 1841 || 34 || 19 || 15 || 8 || 0\n|-\n| 1851 || 63 || 33 || 30 || 11 || 2\n|-\n| 1861 || 49 || 25 || 24 || 11 || 1\n|-\n| 1871 || 35 || 18 || 17 || 8 || 1\n|-\n| 1881 || 31 || 18 || 13 || 7 || 1\n|-\n| 1891 || 27 || 16 || 11 || 8 || 2\n\n|}\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are eleven families listed in the townland<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Ballyconnell/Crossmakillagher/ ''Census of Ireland 1901'']</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are thirteen families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Ballyconnell/Crossmakellagher/ ''Census of Ireland 1911'']</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThere seem to be no structures of historical interest in the townland apart from the disused [[Cavan and Leitrim Railway]]. In 1739 Dean John Richardson referred to two megaliths in ''Crossmaclaght'' but there is no trace today. He may have mistaken the location.<ref>''Dean Richardson's Further Account of Com. Cavan'' by Patterson, T.G.F., Gaffikin, M. and Davies, O.,  in 1938 Ulster Journal of Archaeology 1, 142-151.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.098|-7.626|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:R205 national secondary road \u2013 Crossmakellagher.jpg|thumb|R205 road in Crossmakellagher townland]]\n'''Crossmakelagher''', also written Crossmakellagher or Crossmakellegher, ({{Irish derived place name|Cros Mhic Ch\u00e9ileachair, meaning 'McKelleher's Crossroad; Locals abbreviate it as 'Cross'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nCrossmakelagher is bounded on the north by [[Cavanaquill]] and [[Killynaff]] townlands, on the west by [[Tonyhallagh]] and [[Tonyrevan]] townlands, on the south by [[Bellaheady]] and [[Killarah]] townlands in [[Kildallan]] parish and on the east by [[Cormeen]] townland in [[Kildallan]] parish and [[Lecharrownahone]] townland. Its chief geographical features are the [[Shannon-Erne Waterway]], a small plantation, a pond, a quarry, a spring well and several dug wells. Crossmakelagher is traversed by the regional [[R205 road (Ireland)|R205 road]], minor roads and rural lanes and the disused [[Cavan and Leitrim Railway]]. The townland covers 197 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nUp until the 18th century it was divided into two different townlands, the part north of the present R205 main road was Crossmakelagher and the part between the R205 and the Shannon-Erne Waterway was called Drumcon (Irish derived place name|Druim Con, meaning 'The Ridge of the Greyhounds'). Crossmakelagher was also called ''Barne'' at the time (Irish derived place name Bearn, meaning 'A Gap').\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Cross''.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf National Archives Dublin]</ref><ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref>\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''CrossmcKelagher'' and the other subdivisions as ''Barne'' and ''Drumgoone''.\n\nThe 1665 Down Survey map depicts the north part as ''Crosmckellagher'' and the south part as ''Drumcone''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref> \n\n[[William Petty]]'s 1685 map depicts them as ''Crossemckelaher'' and ''Drumcon''.<ref>[http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#c=Cavan]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 4 June 1611, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted ''one poll of Barne to Hugh McManus Oge Magauran''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA211&dq=boely+Killmuriertagh&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBzuSOzbjfAhWjQxUIHZeBAogQ6AEINTAC#v=onepage&q=boely%20Killmuriertagh&f=false]</ref> He was the great-grandson of a previous Magauran chief, [[Tom\u00e1s mac Maghnus M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]] who ruled from 1512 to 1532. His father Manus Og lived in [[Cor, Templeport|Cor]] and received a pardon in 1586.\n\nIn the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 23 June 1610, along with other lands forming the Manor of Calva, King [[James VI and I]] granted ''two polls of Crosse to Hugh Culme''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA194&lpg=PA194&dq=Kilclogen&source=bl&ots=sGT6qXkfxh&sig=9RJ9eMs-ATQuJW4vgmqxm_501_Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjrp7WOoqzfAhUIDuwKHYsRAHMQ6AEwB3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Kilclogen&f=false]</ref>  In the same year Culme surrendered his interest to Walter Talbot of Ballyconnell. Walter Talbot died on 26 June 1625 at Ballyconnell and his son James Talbot succeeded to the Ballyconnell estate aged just 10 years. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 20 September 1630 found that James Talbot was seized of ''two polls of Crosse'', along with other lands.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PA11-IA1&dq=Derrogeny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52JidpKzfAhVCyaQKHb4_BlgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=Derrogeny&f=false}]</ref> James Talbot married Helen Calvert, the daughter of [[George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore]] of Maryland, USA, in 1635. In the aftermath of the Irish Rebellion of 1641 James Talbot's estate was confiscated because he was a Catholic and he was granted an estate in 1655 at Castle Rubey, County Roscommon instead. He died in 1687. Talbot's land in Crossmakelagher was distributed as follows-\n\nIn the Hearth Money Rolls compiled on 29 September 1663<ref>''The Hearth Money Rolls for the Baronies of Tullyhunco and Tullyhaw, County Cavan'', edited by Rev. Francis J. McKiernan, in Breifne Journal. Vol. I, No. 3 (1960), pp. 247-263</ref> there were two Hearth Tax payers in  ''Liosmackelagher- Cormucke McKelacher and Patricke McKelacher''.\t\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the townland as belonging to Captain Gwilliams (i.e. the landlord of Ballyconnell, Captain Thomas Gwyllym) and the tenants as ''Edward Rely & Others''. The same survey also lists ''Barne'' and ''Drumgoone'' as belonging to Captain Gwilliams. A further confirming  grant dated 11 August 1666 was made from King [[Charles II of England]] to Thomas Guyllym of Ballyconnell included ''52 acres 1 rood and 24 perches in Crossmackillagher, alias Crosse, alias Barne and part of the same 10 acres and 16 perches''. The grant also included ''47 acres 2 roods in Dromcowen, alias Drumgoney.''<ref>[https://archive.org/details/op1244157-1001/page/n45]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]] Eleanor Reynolds of ''Lissanore'' made a deposition about the rebellion in Lissanover which included-\n''Ellenor Reinolds of Late of Lissanore in the County of Cauan widow aged 46 yeares or thereabouts duly sworne etc. .. She further saith that in May 1642 this deponents mother not being able (because of age & weaknes) to goe to Croghan Castle was left behind with some of the tenants at Lissanore aforesaid, where she was about the tyme aforesaid barbarously murthered by one '''ffarell Groome mc Kellogher of CrossemacKellogher''' who confessed the said barbarous fact to divers persons that voluntarily did depose the same to be true.''<ref>[http://1641.tcd.ie/deposition.php?depID=832167r164]</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the name as ''Crossmakellagher''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list twelve tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Cross&search=Search], in the ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Crossmakelagher Valuation Office Field books are available for 1839-1841.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00400.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=&townland=crossmakeelagher&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=&townland=crossmakelagher&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists ten landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=190620&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=Crossmakelagher]</ref>\n\n==Census==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Males\n! Females\n! Total Houses\n! Uninhabited\n|-\n| 1841 || 34 || 19 || 15 || 8 || 0\n|-\n| 1851 || 63 || 33 || 30 || 11 || 2\n|-\n| 1861 || 49 || 25 || 24 || 11 || 1\n|-\n| 1871 || 35 || 18 || 17 || 8 || 1\n|-\n| 1881 || 31 || 18 || 13 || 7 || 1\n|-\n| 1891 || 27 || 16 || 11 || 8 || 2\n\n|}\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are eleven families listed in the townland,<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Ballyconnell/Crossmakillagher/ ''Census of Ireland 1901'']</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are thirteen families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Ballyconnell/Crossmakellagher/ ''Census of Ireland 1911'']</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThere seem to be no structures of historical interest in the townland apart from the disused [[Cavan and Leitrim Railway]]. In 1739 Dean John Richardson referred to two megaliths in ''Crossmaclaght'' but there is no trace today. He may have mistaken the location.<ref>''Dean Richardson's Further Account of Com. Cavan'' by Patterson, T.G.F., Gaffikin, M. and Davies, O.,  in 1938 Ulster Journal of Archaeology 1, 142-151.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.098|-7.626|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCensus", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossmakelagher"}
{"title_page": "Nobuhiko Obayashi", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese film director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Nobuhiko Obayashi\n| image        = Nobuhiko Obayashi cropped 2 Nobuhiko Obayashi 201911.jpg\n| caption      = Nobuhiko Obayashi\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1938|1|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Onomichi, Hiroshima]], [[Empire of Japan]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|4|10|1938|1|9|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| occupation   = [[Film director]], [[screenwriter]], [[Film editing|editor]], [[film producer]]\n| years_active = 1960\u20132020\n| spouse       = Kyoko Obayashi<ref name=haring>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/nobuhiko-obayashi-dies-influential-japanese-filmmaker-was-82-obituary-1202906225/|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi Dies: Influential Japanese Filmmaker Succumbs To Cancer At Age 82.|last=Haring|first=Bruce|date=10 April 2020|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=throbit>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/nobuhiko-obayashi-dead-japanese-filmmaker-was-82-1289895|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi, Prolific Japanese Film Director, Dies at 82|date=10 April 2020|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| children     = Chigumi<ref name=haring /><ref name=throbit />\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Nobuhiko Obayashi'''|\u5927\u6797 \u5ba3\u5f66|\u014cbayashi Nobuhiko|9 January 1938 \u2013 10 April 2020}} was a Japanese [[film director|director]], [[screenwriter]] and [[film editing|editor]] of films and television advertisements. He began his filmmaking career as a pioneer of Japanese [[experimental film]]s<ref name=dargis>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/15/movies/15house.html|title=7 Frightened Teenagers in Nobuhiko Obayashi's First Feature|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=14 January 2010|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/10/31/films/life-spent-working-among-japans-movie-greats/#.XpD2XfhKhPY|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi: A life spent working among Japan's movie greats|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=31 October 2019|work=[[The Japan Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> before transitioning to directing more mainstream media, and his resulting filmography as a director spanned almost 60 years. He is best known as the director of the 1977 [[horror film]] ''[[House (1977 film)|House]]'', which has garnered a [[Cult film|cult following]]. He was notable for his distinct surreal filmmaking style, as well as the [[Anti war film|anti-war]] themes commonly embedded in his films.<ref name=kageyama>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/obayashis-40-year-career-defined-warning-wars-horror-66559049|title=Obayashi's 40-film career defined by warning of war's horror|last=Kageyama|first=Yuri|date=27 October 2019|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Honolulu Festival Parade - Grand Marshals (6869570396).jpg|thumb|200px|Obayashi (right) with [[:ja:\u68ee\u6c11\u592b|Tamio Mori]] (left) at the Honolulu Festival in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]] in 2012]]\n[[File:Obayashi Nobuhiko from \"HANAGATAMI\" at Opening Ceremony of the Tokyo International Film Festival 2017 (28423832079).jpg|thumb|200px|Obayashi at the 2017 [[Tokyo International Film Festival]]]]\nObayashi was born on 9 January 1938 in the city of [[Onomichi, Hiroshima|Onomichi]], Japan.<ref>{{harvnb|Federation of Motion Picture Producers in Asia|1989|p=}}: \"Nobuhiko Obayashi was born January 9, 1983, the so {{sic}} of a doctor, in Onomichi, Hiroshima Prefecture, Japan.\"</ref> After his father, a doctor,<ref name=kageyama /> was called to the battlefront during [[World War II]], he was raised in his early infancy by his maternal grandparents. Through his childhood and adolescence Obayashi followed many artistic pursuits including drawing, writing, playing the piano, and a growing interest in animation and film.\n\n==Career==\n===1955\u20131977: Early career and ''House''===\nIn 1955 Obayashi, at the urging of his father, began procedures to enter medical school and become a doctor. However, he abandoned the prospect of a career in medicine in favor of following his artistic interests at [[Seijo University]].<ref name=blair>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/japanese-auteur-nobuhiko-obayashi-be-showcased-at-tokyo-film-fest-1224810|title=Auteur Nobuhiko Obayashi to Be Showcased at Tokyo Film Fest|last=Blair|first=Gavin J.|date=17 July 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In 1956 he was accepted to the university's liberal arts department, where he began to work with [[8 mm film|8]] and [[16 mm film]].<ref>{{harvnb|Federation of Motion Picture Producers in Asia|1989|p=}}: \"After moving to Tokyo and entering Seijo University, he started making 8 mm films as 'art.' After filming a number of documentaries and dramas, he switched to 16 mm.\"</ref> Toward the end of his stay at the university Obayashi began working on a series of [[Short film|short]] experimental films. Along with works by other filmmakers such as [[Shuji Terayama]] and [[Donald Richie]], Obayashi's films would develop the tone of Japanese experimental cinema through the 1960s. In these early experimental films Obayashi employed a number of avant-garde techniques that he would carry into his later mainstream work. Though these films tended to be of a personal nature, they received public viewership due to distribution by the [[Art Theatre Guild]].\n\nFollowing his departure from university, Obayashi continued to work on his experimental films while earning a living as a director in the new field of television advertisements. Obayashi's TV commercials had a visual appeal similar to that of his experimental works. In the 1970s he began a series of Japanese ads featuring well-known American stars such as [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Charles Bronson]] and [[Catherine Deneuve]].<ref name=schillingvariety>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/asia/tokyo-festival-nobuhiko-obayashi-labyrinth-cinema-1203381807/|title=Tokyo Film Festival: Nobuhiko Obayashi Re-enters 'Labyrinth of Cinema'|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=27 October 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Throughout his career, Obayashi directed around 3,000 television commercials.<ref name=varietyrip>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/nobuhiko-obayashi-dies-dead-japanese-director-1234577784/|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi Japanese Director Dead at 82|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=10 April 2020|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> He made his feature film [[directorial debut]] with the horror film ''[[House (1977 film)|House]]'', released in 1977.<ref name=dargis /><ref name=atkinson>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2010/01/12/rediscovering-the-japanese-horror-flick-house/|title=Rediscovering the Japanese Horror Flick House|last=Atkinson|first=Michael|date=12 January 2010|work=[[The Village Voice]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The film employed a mixture of trick photography and avant-garde techniques to achieve its distinctive, surreal visuals, and has gone on to be considered a [[Cult film|cult classic]]. It earned Obayashi the [[Blue Ribbon Awards|Blue Ribbon Award]] for Best New Director.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv6tMUEJ?url=http://www.kinejun.jp/special/90alltimebest/index.html|title=WebCite query result|website=Webcitation.org|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1980s\u20132010s: Further mainstream success===\nThrough the 1980s and onwards he continued to make feature films and broadened his mainstream appeal. He directed a number of [[coming-of-age]] films such as ''[[Tenk\u014dsei]]'' (1982), ''[[Toki o Kakeru Sh\u014djo (1983 film)|The Girl Who Leapt Through Time]]'' (1983), and ''[[Lonely Heart (film)|Lonely Heart]]'' (1985)\u2014which together form his \"Onomichi trilogy\", named after the town where he was born<ref name=blair /><ref name=smithtjt>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/10/03/films/tokyo-international-film-festival-celebrate-homegrown-talent/#.XpELlvhKhPY|title=Tokyo International Film Festival to celebrate homegrown talent|last=Smith|first=Alyssa I.|date=3 October 2019|work=[[The Japan Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\u2014as well as ''[[Chizuko's Younger Sister]]'' (1991).\n\nHis 1988 film ''[[The Discarnates]]'' was entered into the [[16th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1989\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1989 |title=16th Moscow International Film Festival (1989)|publisher=[[Moscow International Film Festival]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316085017/http://moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1989|archive-date=16 March 2013|access-date=24 February 2013}}</ref> His 1998 film ''[[Sada (film)|Sada]],'' based on the true story of [[Sada Abe]], was entered into the [[48th Berlin International Film Festival]], where it won the [[FIPRESCI Prize|FIRESCI Prize]] for \"its unique combination of innovative style and human observation.\"<ref name=atkinson /><ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1998/02_programm_1998/02_Programm_1998.html|title=Berlinale: 1998 Programme|website=Berlinale.de|access-date=1 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Obayashi was diagnosed with stage-four terminal [[cancer]]<ref name=haring /><ref name=schillingvariety /> and was only given a few months to live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/10/29/tokyo-film-festivalnobuhiko-obayashis-hanagatami-like-nothing/|title=Tokyo Film Festival \u2013 Hanagatami, review: Nobuhiko Obayashi's latest is like nothing else around|last=Collin|first=Robbie|date=29 October 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Despite this, he started production on ''[[Hanagatami]]'', a passion project of his which had been over 40 years in the making.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mubi.com/notebook/posts/working-for-tomorrow-an-interview-with-nobuhiko-obayashi|title=Working for Tomorrow: An Interview with Nobuhiko Obayashi on Notebook|last=Masubuchi|first=Aiko|date=24 January 2019|publisher=[[Mubi (streaming service)|MUBI]]|language=en|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> The film was released in 2017 and was met with acclaim, winning prizes such as the [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Film|Best Film Award]] at the 72nd [[Mainichi Film Awards]].<ref name=mainichi>{{cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20180118/p2a/00m/0et/019000c|title='Hanagatami' wins top prize at 72nd Mainichi Film Awards|date=18 January 2018|work=[[Mainichi Daily News]]|language=en|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> It is the third installment in a thematic trilogy of modern anti-war films by Obayashi, along with ''[[Casting Blossoms to the Sky]]'' (2012) and ''[[Seven Weeks]]'' (2014).\n\nHe shot and edited his final film, titled ''[[Labyrinth of Cinema]]'', while receiving cancer treatment.<ref name=schillingvariety /> ''Labyrinth of Cinema'' premiered at the 2019 [[Tokyo International Film Festival]].<ref name=young>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/labyrinth-cinema-1252406|title='Labyrinth of Cinema': Film Review {{!}} Tokyo 2019|last=Young|first=Deborah|date=5 November 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nObayashi died on 10 April 2020 at the age of 82,<ref name=throbit /><ref name=varietyrip /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20200411-04100252-sph-ent|title=\u6620\u753b\u76e3\u7763\u306e\u5927\u6797\u5ba3\u5f66\u6c0f\u3001\uff18\uff12\u6b73\u3067\u6b7b\u53bb\u3000\u80ba\u304c\u3093\u3067\u4f59\u547d\uff13\u304b\u6708\u306e\u5ba3\u544a\u304b\u3089\uff13\u5e74\uff18\u304b\u6708|date=11 April 2020|website=[[Yahoo! Japan]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=squires>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3612601/r-p-hausu-filmmaker-nobuhiko-obayashi-passed-away-82/|title=[R.I.P.] 'Hausu' Filmmaker Nobuhiko \u00d4bayashi Has Passed Away at 82|last=Squires|first=John|date=10 April 2020|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=rife>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-nobuhiko-obayashi-director-of-hausu-and-the-gir-1842796621|title=R.I.P. Nobuhiko Obayashi, director of ''Hausu'', ''Sada'', and ''School In The Crosshairs''|last=Rife|first=Katie|date=10 April 2020|work=[[The A. V. Club]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> from lung cancer in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13290076|title=Film director Obayashi dies in Tokyo of lung cancer at 82|date=11 April 2020|work=[[The Asahi Shimbun]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=haring />\n\n==Honors==\n* [[Medals of Honor (Japan)|Medal with Purple Ribbon]] (2004)\n* [[Order of the Rising Sun|Order of the Rising Sun, 4th Class, Gold Rays with Rosette]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20091103-OYT1T00037.htm|title=\u79cb\u306e\u53d9\u52f2\u3001\u68ee\u5c71\u5143\u6cd5\u76f8\u3089\uff14\uff10\uff12\uff14\u4eba\u306b|date=3 November 2009|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Person of Cultural Merit]] (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/29/tech/shigeru-miyamoto-nintendo-trnd/index.html|title='Mario Bros.' creator Shigeru Miyamoto to be given one of Japan's highest honors|last=Kim|first=Allen|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! width=\"65\"| [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=\"65\"| [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=\"65\"| [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! width=\"65\"| [[Film editing|Editor]]\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n! class=unsortable | {{Tooltip|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1977\n| ''[[House (1977 film)|House]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also special effects director\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=219}}\n|-\n| ''The Visitor in the Eye''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| \n| Also appears as an actor\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Furimukeba Ai]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=312}}\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''School in the Crosshairs''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| <ref name=rife />\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Tenk\u014dsei]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n| Also known as ''Exchange Students'' and ''I Are You, You Am Me''\n| <ref name=blair /><ref name=smithtjt />\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Toki o Kakeru Sh\u014djo (1983 film)|The Girl Who Leapt Through Time]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n| <ref name=squires />{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=397}}\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''The Deserted City''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1985\n| ''[[Lonely Heart (film)|Lonely Heart]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=blair /><ref name=smithtjt /><ref name=squires />\n|-\n| ''Four Sisters''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=346}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1986\n| ''[[His Motorbike, Her Island]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=349}}\n|-\n| ''Bound for the Fields, the Mountains, and the Seacoast''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{sfn|Sharp|2008|p=44}}\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[The Drifting Classroom]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| \n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Discarnates]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Beijing Watermelon''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref>{{cite book|year=1991|title=Variety's Film Reviews 1989-1990|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Variety_Film_Reviews/wHRZAAAAMAAJ|volume=|publisher=[[R.R. Bowker]]|isbn=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Chizuko's Younger Sister]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref>{{cite magazine|last=O'Hara|first=Kate (compiler)|editor-last=Kosner|editor-first=Edward|editor-link=Edward Kosner|date=21 October 1991|title=Movies: Theater Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ugCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA128|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media, LLC|volume=24|issue=41|page=128|issn=0028-7369|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=135}}\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Samurai Kids]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=383}}\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Turning Point''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref name=squires /><ref>{{cite book|last=Sloan|first=Jane|year=2007|title=Reel Women: An International Directory of Contemporary Feature Films about Women|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|page=146|isbn=978-0810857384}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Goodbye for Tomorrow''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=391}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1998\n| ''[[Sada (film)|Sada]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=rife />{{sfn|Sharp|2008|p=190}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Bowyer|first=Justin|year=2004|title=The Cinema of Japan and Korea|publisher=[[Wallflower Press]]|page=103|isbn=978-1904764120}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''I Want to Hear the Wind's Song''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''The Last Snow''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''The Reason''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Casting Blossoms to the Sky]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=blair /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/08/16/films/filmmaker-nobuhiko-obayashi-devotes-message-peace-via-big-screen/#.XpEXJ_hKhPY|title=Filmmaker Nobuhiko Obayashi devotes himself to a message of peace via the big screen|last=Masangkay|first=May|date=16 August 2017|work=[[The Japan Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Seven Weeks]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/seven-weeks-review-nobuhiko-obayashi-1201511929/|title=Film Review: 'Seven Weeks'|last=Lee|first=Maggie|date=9 June 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Hanagatami]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref name=mainichi /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/hanagatami-1122609|title='Hanagatami': Film Review|last=Young|first=Deborah|date=22 June 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Labyrinth of Cinema]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref name=young /><ref name=squires />\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|author=Federation of Motion Picture Producers in Asia|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/34th_Asia_Pacific_Film_Festival_18_21_De/15AyAAAAIAAJ|title=34th Asia-Pacific Film Festival, 18-21 December 1989, Jakarta, Indonesia|date=1989|publisher=[[Asia-Pacific Film Festival]]|access-date=10 April 2020|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Galbraith IV|first=Stuart|year=1996|title=The Japanese Filmography: A Complete Reference to 209 Filmmakers and the Over 1250 Films Released in the United States, 1900 through 1994|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-0786400324|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Galbraith IV|first=Stuart|year=2008|title=The Toho Studios Story: A History and Complete Filmography|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|isbn=978-0810860049|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sharp|first=Jasper|year=2008|title=Behind the Pink Curtain: The Complete History of Japanese Sex Cinema|publisher=FAB Press|isbn=978-1903254547|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0643171}}\n* [http://www.ubu.com/film/obayashi.html Ubuweb] entry for Obayashi showcasing his experimental works\n\n{{Nobuhiko Obayashi}}\n{{Blue Ribbon Award for Best Newcomer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obayashi, Nobuhiko}}\n[[Category:Japanese film directors]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hiroshima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal with Purple Ribbon]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rising Sun, 4th class]]\n[[Category:Horror film directors]]\n[[Category:Persons of Cultural Merit]]\n[[Category:People from Onomichi, Hiroshima]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese film director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Nobuhiko Obayashi\n| image        = Nobuhiko Obayashi cropped 2 Nobuhiko Obayashi 201911.jpg\n| caption      = Nobuhiko Obayashi\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1938|1|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Onomichi, Hiroshima]], [[Empire of Japan]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|4|10|1938|1|9|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| occupation   = [[Film director]], [[screenwriter]], [[Film editing|editor]], [[film producer]]\n| years_active = 1960\u20132020\n| spouse       = Kyoko Obayashi<ref name=haring>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/nobuhiko-obayashi-dies-influential-japanese-filmmaker-was-82-obituary-1202906225/|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi Dies: Influential Japanese Filmmaker Succumbs To Cancer At Age 82.|last=Haring|first=Bruce|date=10 April 2020|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=throbit>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/nobuhiko-obayashi-dead-japanese-filmmaker-was-82-1289895|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi, Prolific Japanese Film Director, Dies at 82|date=10 April 2020|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| children     = Chigumi<ref name=haring /><ref name=throbit />\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Nobuhiko Obayashi'''|\u5927\u6797 \u5ba3\u5f66|\u014cbayashi Nobuhiko|9 January 1938 \u2013 10 April 2020}} was a Japanese [[film director|director]], [[screenwriter]] and [[film editing|editor]] of films and television advertisements. He began his filmmaking career as a pioneer of Japanese [[experimental film]]s<ref name=dargis>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/15/movies/15house.html|title=7 Frightened Teenagers in Nobuhiko Obayashi's First Feature|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=14 January 2010|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/10/31/films/life-spent-working-among-japans-movie-greats/#.XpD2XfhKhPY|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi: A life spent working among Japan's movie greats|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=31 October 2019|work=[[The Japan Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> before transitioning to directing more mainstream media, and his resulting filmography as a director spanned almost 60 years. He is best known as the director of the 1977 [[horror film]] ''[[House (1977 film)|House]]'', which has garnered a [[Cult film|cult following]]. He was notable for his distinct surreal filmmaking style, as well as the [[Anti war film|anti-war]] themes commonly embedded in his films.<ref name=kageyama>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/obayashis-40-year-career-defined-warning-wars-horror-66559049|title=Obayashi's 40-film career defined by warning of war's horror|last=Kageyama|first=Yuri|date=27 October 2019|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Honolulu Festival Parade - Grand Marshals (6869570396).jpg|thumb|200px|Obayashi (right) with [[:ja:\u68ee\u6c11\u592b|Tamio Mori]] (left) at the Honolulu Festival in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]] in 2012]]\n[[File:Obayashi Nobuhiko from \"HANAGATAMI\" at Opening Ceremony of the Tokyo International Film Festival 2017 (28423832079).jpg|thumb|200px|Obayashi at the 2017 [[Tokyo International Film Festival]]]]\nObayashi was born on 9 January 1938 in the city of [[Onomichi, Hiroshima|Onomichi]], Japan.<ref>{{harvnb|Federation of Motion Picture Producers in Asia|1989|p=}}: \"Nobuhiko Obayashi was born January 9, 1983, the so {{sic}} of a doctor, in Onomichi, Hiroshima Prefecture, Japan.\"</ref> After his father, a doctor,<ref name=kageyama /> was called to the battlefront during [[World War II]], he was raised in his early infancy by his maternal grandparents. Through his childhood and adolescence Obayashi followed many artistic pursuits including drawing, writing, playing the piano, and a growing interest in animation and film.\n\n==Career==\n===1955\u20131977: Early career and ''House''===\nIn 1955 Obayashi, at the urging of his father, began procedures to enter medical school and become a doctor. However, he abandoned the prospect of a career in medicine in favor of following his artistic interests at [[Seijo University]].<ref name=blair>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/japanese-auteur-nobuhiko-obayashi-be-showcased-at-tokyo-film-fest-1224810|title=Auteur Nobuhiko Obayashi to Be Showcased at Tokyo Film Fest|last=Blair|first=Gavin J.|date=17 July 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In 1956 he was accepted to the university's liberal arts department, where he began to work with [[8 mm film|8]] and [[16 mm film]].<ref>{{harvnb|Federation of Motion Picture Producers in Asia|1989|p=}}: \"After moving to Tokyo and entering Seijo University, he started making 8 mm films as 'art.' After filming a number of documentaries and dramas, he switched to 16 mm.\"</ref> Toward the end of his stay at the university Obayashi began working on a series of [[Short film|short]] experimental films. Along with works by other filmmakers such as [[Shuji Terayama]] and [[Donald Richie]], Obayashi's films would develop the tone of Japanese experimental cinema through the 1960s. In these early experimental films Obayashi employed a number of avant-garde techniques that he would carry into his later mainstream work. Though these films tended to be of a personal nature, they received public viewership due to distribution by the [[Art Theatre Guild]].\n\nFollowing his departure from university, Obayashi continued to work on his experimental films while earning a living as a director in the new field of television advertisements. Obayashi's TV commercials had a visual appeal similar to that of his experimental works. In the 1970s he began a series of Japanese ads featuring well-known American stars such as [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Charles Bronson]] and [[Catherine Deneuve]].<ref name=schillingvariety>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/asia/tokyo-festival-nobuhiko-obayashi-labyrinth-cinema-1203381807/|title=Tokyo Film Festival: Nobuhiko Obayashi Re-enters 'Labyrinth of Cinema'|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=27 October 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Throughout his career, Obayashi directed around 3,000 television commercials.<ref name=varietyrip>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/nobuhiko-obayashi-dies-dead-japanese-director-1234577784/|title=Nobuhiko Obayashi Japanese Director Dead at 82|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=10 April 2020|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> He made his feature film [[directorial debut]] with the horror film ''[[House (1977 film)|House]]'', released in 1977.<ref name=dargis /><ref name=atkinson>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2010/01/12/rediscovering-the-japanese-horror-flick-house/|title=Rediscovering the Japanese Horror Flick House|last=Atkinson|first=Michael|date=12 January 2010|work=[[The Village Voice]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The film employed a mixture of trick photography and avant-garde techniques to achieve its distinctive, surreal visuals, and has gone on to be considered a [[Cult film|cult classic]]. It earned Obayashi the [[Blue Ribbon Awards|Blue Ribbon Award]] for Best New Director.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv6tMUEJ?url=http://www.kinejun.jp/special/90alltimebest/index.html|title=WebCite query result|website=Webcitation.org|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1980s\u20132010s: Further mainstream success===\nThrough the 1980s and onwards he continued to make feature films and broadened his mainstream appeal. He directed a number of [[coming-of-age]] films such as ''[[Tenk\u014dsei]]'' (1982), ''[[Toki o Kakeru Sh\u014djo (1983 film)|The Girl Who Leapt Through Time]]'' (1983), and ''[[Lonely Heart (film)|Lonely Heart]]'' (1985)\u2014which together form his \"Onomichi trilogy\", named after the town where he was born<ref name=blair /><ref name=smithtjt>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/10/03/films/tokyo-international-film-festival-celebrate-homegrown-talent/#.XpELlvhKhPY|title=Tokyo International Film Festival to celebrate homegrown talent|last=Smith|first=Alyssa I.|date=3 October 2019|work=[[The Japan Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\u2014as well as ''[[Chizuko's Younger Sister]]'' (1991).\n\nHis 1988 film ''[[The Discarnates]]'' was entered into the [[16th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1989\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1989 |title=16th Moscow International Film Festival (1989)|publisher=[[Moscow International Film Festival]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316085017/http://moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1989|archive-date=16 March 2013|access-date=24 February 2013}}</ref> His 1998 film ''[[Sada (film)|Sada]],'' based on the true story of [[Sada Abe]], was entered into the [[48th Berlin International Film Festival]], where it won the [[FIPRESCI Prize|FIRESCI Prize]] for \"its unique combination of innovative style and human observation.\"<ref name=atkinson /><ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1998/02_programm_1998/02_Programm_1998.html|title=Berlinale: 1998 Programme|website=Berlinale.de|access-date=1 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Obayashi was diagnosed with stage-four terminal [[cancer]]<ref name=haring /><ref name=schillingvariety /> and was only given a few months to live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/10/29/tokyo-film-festivalnobuhiko-obayashis-hanagatami-like-nothing/|title=Tokyo Film Festival \u2013 Hanagatami, review: Nobuhiko Obayashi's latest is like nothing else around|last=Collin|first=Robbie|date=29 October 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Despite this, he started production on ''[[Hanagatami]]'', a passion project of his which had been over 40 years in the making.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mubi.com/notebook/posts/working-for-tomorrow-an-interview-with-nobuhiko-obayashi|title=Working for Tomorrow: An Interview with Nobuhiko Obayashi on Notebook|last=Masubuchi|first=Aiko|date=24 January 2019|publisher=[[Mubi (streaming service)|MUBI]]|language=en|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> The film was released in 2017 and was met with acclaim, winning prizes such as the [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Film|Best Film Award]] at the 72nd [[Mainichi Film Awards]].<ref name=mainichi>{{cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20180118/p2a/00m/0et/019000c|title='Hanagatami' wins top prize at 72nd Mainichi Film Awards|date=18 January 2018|work=[[Mainichi Daily News]]|language=en|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> It is the third installment in a thematic trilogy of modern anti-war films by Obayashi, along with ''[[Casting Blossoms to the Sky]]'' (2012) and ''[[Seven Weeks]]'' (2014).\n\nHe shot and edited his final film, titled ''[[Labyrinth of Cinema]]'', while receiving cancer treatment.<ref name=schillingvariety /> ''Labyrinth of Cinema'' premiered at the 2019 [[Tokyo International Film Festival]].<ref name=young>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/labyrinth-cinema-1252406|title='Labyrinth of Cinema': Film Review {{!}} Tokyo 2019|last=Young|first=Deborah|date=5 November 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nObayashi died on 10 April 2020 at the age of 82,<ref name=throbit /><ref name=varietyrip /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20200411-04100252-sph-ent|title=\u6620\u753b\u76e3\u7763\u306e\u5927\u6797\u5ba3\u5f66\u6c0f\u3001\uff18\uff12\u6b73\u3067\u6b7b\u53bb\u3000\u80ba\u304c\u3093\u3067\u4f59\u547d\uff13\u304b\u6708\u306e\u5ba3\u544a\u304b\u3089\uff13\u5e74\uff18\u304b\u6708|date=11 April 2020|website=[[Yahoo! Japan]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=squires>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3612601/r-p-hausu-filmmaker-nobuhiko-obayashi-passed-away-82/|title=[R.I.P.] 'Hausu' Filmmaker Nobuhiko \u00d4bayashi Has Passed Away at 82|last=Squires|first=John|date=10 April 2020|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=rife>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-nobuhiko-obayashi-director-of-hausu-and-the-gir-1842796621|title=R.I.P. Nobuhiko Obayashi, director of ''Hausu'', ''Sada'', and ''School In The Crosshairs''|last=Rife|first=Katie|date=10 April 2020|work=[[The A. V. Club]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> from lung cancer in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Asahi Shimbun]]|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13290076|title=Film director Obayashi dies in Tokyo of lung cancer at 82|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=haring />\n\n==Honors==\n* [[Medals of Honor (Japan)|Medal with Purple Ribbon]] (2004)\n* [[Order of the Rising Sun|Order of the Rising Sun, 4th Class, Gold Rays with Rosette]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20091103-OYT1T00037.htm|title=\u79cb\u306e\u53d9\u52f2\u3001\u68ee\u5c71\u5143\u6cd5\u76f8\u3089\uff14\uff10\uff12\uff14\u4eba\u306b|date=3 November 2009|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Person of Cultural Merit]] (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/29/tech/shigeru-miyamoto-nintendo-trnd/index.html|title='Mario Bros.' creator Shigeru Miyamoto to be given one of Japan's highest honors|last=Kim|first=Allen|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! width=\"65\"| [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=\"65\"| [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=\"65\"| [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! width=\"65\"| [[Film editing|Editor]]\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n! class=unsortable | {{Tooltip|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1977\n| ''[[House (1977 film)|House]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also special effects director\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=219}}\n|-\n| ''The Visitor in the Eye''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| \n| Also appears as an actor\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Furimukeba Ai]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=312}}\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''School in the Crosshairs''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| <ref name=rife />\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Tenk\u014dsei]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n| Also known as ''Exchange Students'' and ''I Are You, You Am Me''\n| <ref name=blair /><ref name=smithtjt />\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Toki o Kakeru Sh\u014djo (1983 film)|The Girl Who Leapt Through Time]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n| <ref name=squires />{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=397}}\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''The Deserted City''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1985\n| ''[[Lonely Heart (film)|Lonely Heart]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=blair /><ref name=smithtjt /><ref name=squires />\n|-\n| ''Four Sisters''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=346}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1986\n| ''[[His Motorbike, Her Island]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=349}}\n|-\n| ''Bound for the Fields, the Mountains, and the Seacoast''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{sfn|Sharp|2008|p=44}}\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[The Drifting Classroom]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| \n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Discarnates]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Beijing Watermelon''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref>{{cite book|year=1991|title=Variety's Film Reviews 1989-1990|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Variety_Film_Reviews/wHRZAAAAMAAJ|volume=|publisher=[[R.R. Bowker]]|isbn=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Chizuko's Younger Sister]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref>{{cite magazine|last=O'Hara|first=Kate (compiler)|editor-last=Kosner|editor-first=Edward|editor-link=Edward Kosner|date=21 October 1991|title=Movies: Theater Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ugCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA128|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media, LLC|volume=24|issue=41|page=128|issn=0028-7369|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=135}}\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Samurai Kids]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=383}}\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Turning Point''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref name=squires /><ref>{{cite book|last=Sloan|first=Jane|year=2007|title=Reel Women: An International Directory of Contemporary Feature Films about Women|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|page=146|isbn=978-0810857384}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Goodbye for Tomorrow''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=391}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1998\n| ''[[Sada (film)|Sada]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=rife />{{sfn|Sharp|2008|p=190}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Bowyer|first=Justin|year=2004|title=The Cinema of Japan and Korea|publisher=[[Wallflower Press]]|page=103|isbn=978-1904764120}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''I Want to Hear the Wind's Song''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''The Last Snow''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''The Reason''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires />\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Casting Blossoms to the Sky]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=blair /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/08/16/films/filmmaker-nobuhiko-obayashi-devotes-message-peace-via-big-screen/#.XpEXJ_hKhPY|title=Filmmaker Nobuhiko Obayashi devotes himself to a message of peace via the big screen|last=Masangkay|first=May|date=16 August 2017|work=[[The Japan Times]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Seven Weeks]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| <ref name=squires /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/seven-weeks-review-nobuhiko-obayashi-1201511929/|title=Film Review: 'Seven Weeks'|last=Lee|first=Maggie|date=9 June 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Hanagatami]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref name=mainichi /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/hanagatami-1122609|title='Hanagatami': Film Review|last=Young|first=Deborah|date=22 June 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Labyrinth of Cinema]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| <ref name=schillingvariety /><ref name=young /><ref name=squires />\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|author=Federation of Motion Picture Producers in Asia|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/34th_Asia_Pacific_Film_Festival_18_21_De/15AyAAAAIAAJ|title=34th Asia-Pacific Film Festival, 18-21 December 1989, Jakarta, Indonesia|date=1989|publisher=[[Asia-Pacific Film Festival]]|access-date=10 April 2020|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Galbraith IV|first=Stuart|year=1996|title=The Japanese Filmography: A Complete Reference to 209 Filmmakers and the Over 1250 Films Released in the United States, 1900 through 1994|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-0786400324|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Galbraith IV|first=Stuart|year=2008|title=The Toho Studios Story: A History and Complete Filmography|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|isbn=978-0810860049|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sharp|firs