{"title_page": "Hibana (Rainbow Six Siege)", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game character}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Hibana (''Rainbow Six Siege'')}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name = Yumiko \"Hibana\" Imagawa\n| image = File:Hibana_Rainbow6_artwork.png\n| alt = Artwork of the article subject, a Special operations personnel wearing heavy, dark clothing. She rests a large firearm on her right shoulder.\n| caption = Hibana as she appears in ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege#Downloadable content and expansion packs|Operation Red Crow]]'' (2016)\n| creator = [[Ubisoft Montreal]]\n| series = [[Tom Clancy's]]\n| first = ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege#Downloadable content and expansion packs|Operation Red Crow]]'' (2016)\n| gender = Female\n| significant_other = Jack Estrada\n| nationality = Japanese\n| voice = Laura Miyata\n}}\n{{Rainbow Six Siege series}}\n{{nihongo|'''Yumiko \"Hibana\" Imagawa'''|\u4eca\u5ddd \u7531\u7f8e\u5b50|Imagawa Yumiko|lead=yes}}, is a fictional [[player character]] who appears in the 2015 video game ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege]]''\u2014a [[Tactical shooter|tactical]] [[Online game|online]] [[first-person shooter]] developed by [[Ubisoft Montreal]]\u2014and other video games published by French video game publisher [[Ubisoft]]. She was introduced in the fourth expansion ''Operation Red Crow'', released on November 17, 2016.Ryan Whittworth sexually slaps his brothers arse \n\nIn ''Rainbow Six Siege'' lore, Hibana was born and raised in [[Nagoya]], [[Japan]] and is a skilled martial artist who joined the [[National Police Agency (Japan)|National Police Academy]] at age 18. Nicknamed \"Hibana\" because of her style of leadership, she developed tactical versatility while training with elite [[police tactical unit]]s [[FBI Special Weapons and Tactics Teams|FBI SWAT]] and [[GIGN]] and was known as an expert in gaining entry in high-risk areas and onrush tactics. After training, she was recruited by the [[Aichi Prefectural Police|Aichi Prefectural Police Department]]'s Special Unit.\n\nWithin the game, Hibana has access to her \"X-Kairos\", a specialised [[40 mm grenade|9 mm]] calibre launcher used to project six explosive pellets that can be remotely detonated. It can be used in various ways, such as creating [[sightlines]], entry points, crawlspaces, or destroying [[Trap door|hatches]].\n\n==Development and release==\nBefore release, Ubisoft announced that the fourth free expansion for ''Rainbow Six Siege'' as ''Operation Red Crow'', with fans speculating that it would be set in Japan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-red-crow-adds-a-pair-of-japanese-operators/|title=Rainbow Six Siege: Operation Red Crow adds a pair of Japanese operators|last=Chalk|first=Andy|date=November 2, 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026213638/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-red-crow-adds-a-pair-of-japanese-operators/|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> with Reddit user Cheesetoaster13 soon leaking images of the two Japanese operators to the official ''Rainbow Six Siege'' [[subreddit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/02/rainbow-six-siege-japan-dlc-is-called-operation-red-crow-new-operators-leak/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Japan DLC is called Operation Red Crow, new operators leak|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=November 2, 2016|website=[[VG247]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508223803/http://www.vg247.com/2016/11/02/rainbow-six-siege-japan-dlc-is-called-operation-red-crow-new-operators-leak/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> On November 17, 2016, Ubisoft released the expansion for Season Pass owners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/news/13129-rainbow-six-siege-continues-postlaunch-support-with-tomorrows-operation-red-crow|title=Rainbow Six Siege Continues Post-Launch Support With Tomorrow's Operation Red Crow|last=Leack|first=Jonathan|date=November 16, 2016|website=[[GameRevolution]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-red-crow-update-gets-a-release-/1100-6445329/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Red Crow Update Gets a Release Date|last=Pereira|first=Chris|date=November 10, 2016|website=[[GameSpot]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724020530/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-red-crow-update-gets-a-release-/1100-6445329/|archive-date=July 24, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Alongside Skyscraper, a map available to the public for free, two operators from Japan's special police force [[Special Assault Team]] (SAT) were released as part of the expansion, including Hibana, a stealth-focused operator.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-fourth-season-content-featured-in-new-videos/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's season four content featured in two new videos|last=Prescott|first=Shaun|date=November 8, 2016|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026213623/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-fourth-season-content-featured-in-new-videos/|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom September 25, 2018, Ubisoft announced that all Year One operators, including Hibana, would be put up for sale for 40% less than their usual selling price.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neowin.net/news/the-eight-year-one-operators-of-rainbow-six-siege-gets-discounted-by-ubisoft|title=The eight Year One operators of Rainbow Six Siege gets discounted by Ubisoft|last=Ariyasinghe|first=Pulasthi|date=September 25, 2018|website=[[Neowin]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925190848/https://www.neowin.net/news/the-eight-year-one-operators-of-rainbow-six-siege-gets-discounted-by-ubisoft|archive-date=September 25, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-6-siege-year-1-operators-price-has-been-dropped-until-next-year/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Year 1 operators price has been dropped until next year|last=James|first=Sarah|date=September 25, 2018|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701074202/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-6-siege-year-1-operators-price-has-been-dropped-until-next-year/|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/25/rainbow-six-siege-year-1-operators-temporary-price-cut/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Year 1 operators price cut by 40% for a limited time|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=September 25, 2018|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926115001/https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/25/rainbow-six-siege-year-1-operators-temporary-price-cut/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Post-release===\nUpon release, it was discovered that if playing on the [[PlayStation 4]] version of the game, a [[Software bug|bug]] could occur that could cause the game to drop it's [[frame rate]] (FPS) to 0 when using her gadget. Ubisoft quickly pulled her from rotation, making her inaccessible, until a [[Patch (computing)|patch]] was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-disables-clash-other-gadgets-causing-game-breaking-exploits/|title=Rainbow Six Siege disables Clash, other gadgets causing game-breaking exploits|last=Park|first=Morgan|date=May 17, 2019|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603174453/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-disables-clash-other-gadgets-causing-game-breaking-exploits/|archive-date=June 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/21/rainbow-six-siege-ubisoft-re-added-bugged-operator-hibana-to-prevent-a-worse-bug-from-happening/|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Ubisoft re-added bugged operator Hibana to prevent a worse bug from happening|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=November 21, 2019|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124095527/http://www.vg247.com/2016/11/21/rainbow-six-siege-ubisoft-re-added-bugged-operator-hibana-to-prevent-a-worse-bug-from-happening/|archive-date=November 24, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> The bug was fixed in the game's 5.1 update, released the week after the launch of Operation Red Crow, alongside other issues concerning the X-Kairos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/97811/rainbow-six-siege-51-patch-fixes-hibana-glitch-changes-vote-kicks|title=Rainbow Six Siege 5.1 patch fixes Hibana glitch, changes vote kicks|last=Keefer|first=John|date=November 22, 2016|website=[[Shacknews]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123172241/http://www.shacknews.com/article/97811/rainbow-six-siege-51-patch-fixes-hibana-glitch-changes-vote-kicks|archive-date=November 23, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Rainbow Six Siege''<nowiki/>'s Update 2.1.1 brought various fixes to the X-Kairos, with Ubisoft noting various issues, including times when some of the pellets won't explode, a bug where pellets aren't displayed properly when shot between two reinforced walls, and a Lingering visual effect after detonation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/827403/Rainbow-Six-Siege-title-update-2-1-1-servers-down-LIVE-patch-notes-release-time|title=Rainbow Six Siege update 2.1.1 - Alpha Packs coming, release date reveal next week?|last=Dassanayake|first=Dion|date=July 13, 2017|website=[[Daily Express]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709063423/https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/827403/Rainbow-Six-Siege-title-update-2-1-1-servers-down-LIVE-patch-notes-release-time|archive-date=July 9, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-introduces-loot-boxes-bal/1100-6451582/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Update Introduces Loot Boxes, Balance Changes, More|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=July 11, 2017|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019194140/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-introduces-loot-boxes-bal/1100-6451582/|archive-date=October 19, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-sieges-loot-box-system-is-rolling-out-today/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's loot box system is rolling out today|last=Prescott|first=Shaun|date=July 12, 2017|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208210734/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-sieges-loot-box-system-is-rolling-out-today/|archive-date=February 8, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Unfortunately for players, the update failed to fix the issue concerning pellets not exploding when detonated. In the patch notes of Update 2.1.3, Ubisoft stated that they planned to fix the bug by the second season of the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-coming-today-changes-lots/1100-6449453/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Update Coming Today, Changes Lots Of Operators|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=April 19, 2017|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020234947/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-coming-today-changes-lots/1100-6449453/|archive-date=October 20, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/19/rainbow-six-siege-update-2-1-3-out-on-all-platforms-hibanas-x-kairos-bug-wont-be-fixed-until-y2s2/|title=Rainbow Six Siege update 2.1.3 out on all platforms, Hibana\u2019s X-KAIROS bug won't be fixed until Y2S2|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=April 19, 2017|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704174938/https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/19/rainbow-six-siege-update-2-1-3-out-on-all-platforms-hibanas-x-kairos-bug-wont-be-fixed-until-y2s2/|archive-date=July 4, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/793873/Rainbow-Six-Siege-update-Ubisoft-patch-notes-new-operator-PS4-Xbox-One|title=Rainbow Six Siege update: Ubisoft patch notes confirm new operator changes on PS4 and Xbox|last=Jones|first=Gary|date=April 19, 2017|website=Daily Express|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924105722/https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/793873/Rainbow-Six-Siege-update-Ubisoft-patch-notes-new-operator-PS4-Xbox-One|archive-date=September 24, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Operation Grim Sky'' expansion, released to the ''Technical Test Server'' (TTS) in August 2018, buffed the X-Kairos to be able to destroy a hatch with only four pellets rather than six to partially fix a bug where the latter would not hit it's intended target.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/08/24/rainbow-six-sieges-grim-sky-test-server-rebalances-more-operators-glaz-hibana-zofia-and-maverick/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Grim Sky Test Server Rebalances More Operators: Glaz, Hibana, Zofia and Maverick|last=Parlock|first=Joe|date=August 24, 2018|website=[[Forbes]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827174311/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/08/24/rainbow-six-sieges-grim-sky-test-server-rebalances-more-operators-glaz-hibana-zofia-and-maverick/|archive-date=August 27, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/new-nerfs-coming-to-maverick-zofia-glaz-in-rainbow-six-siege/|title=New nerfs coming to Maverick, Zofia, Glaz in Rainbow Six Siege|last=Park|first=Morgan|date=August 23, 2018|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416193750/https://www.pcgamer.com/new-nerfs-coming-to-maverick-zofia-glaz-in-rainbow-six-siege/|archive-date=April 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> An additional fix was added to the update where, in some instances, reinforced wall debris will remain floating even though the wall was destroyed by the X-Kairos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sieges-grim-sky-update-is-live-here-are-the-full-p/1100-6461547/|title=Siege's Grim Sky Update Is Live; Here Are The Full Patch Notes|last=Ram\u00e9e|first=Jordan|date=September 10, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911034304/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sieges-grim-sky-update-is-live-here-are-the-full-p/1100-6461547/|archive-date=September 11, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Story and character===\n====Biography====\nHibana was born the daughter of a butcher and was inspired by her family to start practising [[Ky\u016bd\u014d]] at a young age. The [[ranged weapon]] training obtained from the practice was followed by her entering martial arts and perfecting multiple assessments while carrying precise, controlled, and fluid motions.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Background:''' The daughter of a local butcher, Imagawa was inspired by her family to practice Ky\u016bd\u014d from a young age. This long range weapon marked her entry in martial arts by perfecting her assessment of multiple factors a once while carrying precise, controlled, and fluid motions.}}</ref>\n\nWhile studying at the National Police Academy, she was the nickname \"Hibana\" because of her [[improvised explosive device]]s and leadership skills while on the field. She was recruited by the Ichi Prefectural Police Department Special Unit because of her lethality and fluency in seven languages. The recruitment allowed her charisma and various techniques and to quickly move up in the ranks.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Background:''' Her area of expertise is to gain entry in high-risk areas. During her studies at the National Police Academy, she gained the nickname Hibana due to her improvised explosive devices and brilliant leadership skills on the field. Fluent in seven languages and lethal with any weapon, Imagawa was recruited by the Aichi Prefectural Police Department Special Unit, where her diverse techniques and charisma allowed her to move up the ranks quickly.}}</ref>\n\nOriginally from Nagoya, Hibana travelled the world to perfect her technique and skills. She specialises in paramilitary techniques, gained by training with the Special Air Service, FBI SWAT, GIGN, and various other special forces units. She acquired tactical versatility from her diverse training, including proficiency in performing [[Offensive (military)|assaults]] in [[Tube (structure)|tubular spaces]] such as [[bus]]es, [[train]]s and [[Airplane|aeroplanes]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Background:''' A Nagoya native, Imagawa traveled the world to perfect her skills and technique. She is specialized in paramilitary techniques gained by training with the SAS, FBI SWAT, and GIGN, to name a few. From her diverse training, she acquired a rare tactical versatility, which includes a proficiency in tubular (bus, train, and airplane) assaults.}}</ref>\n\n====Personality====\nConsidered a natural team builder, Hibana is passionate and adaptive in her fields. She has inspired experts from diverse backgrounds to work alongside each other to reach a common goal.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Psychological Profile:''' Imagawa is a natural team builder. Passionate and adaptive, she inspires experts from diverse backgrounds to work together and reach a common goal..}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n[[File:Hibana_Kairos_gameplay_example.jpg|thumb|right|A gameplay screenshot showcasing Hibana using her X-Kairos gadget to blow a hole in a wall.]]\nIn ''Rainbow Six Siege,'' Hibana is a light-armoured attacking operator who is equipped with the \"X-Kairos\", a 40&nbsp;mm calibre launcher that fires six explosive pellets simultaneously that can be remotely detonated from a safe distance.<ref name=\":2\" /> The launcher can be used to blow open holes in walls, creating either [[sightline]]s or entry points depending on how the player uses it.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFor firearms, she possesses either a [[Benelli Supernova]] pump-action shotgun or a [[Howa Type 89]] assault rifle as primary weapons and either a [[SIG Sauer P226|SIG Sauer P229]] semi-automatic pistol or a [[Minebea PM-9]] machine pistol as secondary weapons.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> She also has access to either [[stun grenade]]s or a [[M18 Claymore mine|claymore]] as gadgets, though the claymore was later replaced with a [[Door breaching#Explosive|breaching charge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/rainbow-six-siege-balance-changes-lion-blitz-virgil-nerf/|title=Meta-shifting balance changes coming to Rainbow Six Siege with nerfs to Lion, Blitz and Vigil|last=Billcliffe|first=James|date=April 25, 2018|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615082612/https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/rainbow-six-siege-balance-changes-lion-blitz-virgil-nerf/|archive-date=June 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/07/18/rainbow-six-siege-hibana-what-she-can-do-and-how-to-use-her/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Hibana: what she can do and how to use her|last=Irwin|first=Dave|date=July 18, 2018|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720165431/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/07/18/rainbow-six-siege-hibana-what-she-can-do-and-how-to-use-her/|archive-date=July 20, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom October 25 to October 31, 2018, Hibana, alongside various other operators, were made playable in the in-game Halloween-themed event ''Mad House'' and were each given event-exclusive uniforms which could be unlocked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/25/rainbow-six-sieges-halloween-event-is-finally-underway-but-not-for-long/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Halloween Event Is Finally Underway, But Not For Long|last=Parlock|first=Joe|date=October 25, 2018|website=Forbes|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620025045/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/25/rainbow-six-sieges-halloween-event-is-finally-underway-but-not-for-long/|archive-date=June 20, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.co.uk/2018/10/26/rainbow-6-siege-halloween-event-is-now-live|title=Rainbow 6: Siege's Spooks Get a Mad House for Halloween|last=James|first=Sarah|date=October 26, 2019|website=[[Kotaku UK]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHibana has received various unique cosmetic skins for her uniform and armoury, including cosmetics exclusive to the limited time ''Outbreak'' event,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-outbreak-event-detailed-features/1100-6456343/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Outbreak Event Detailed, Features Premium Cosmetic Loot Boxes|last=Pereira|first=Chris|date=January 29, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228214331/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-outbreak-event-detailed-features/1100-6456343/|archive-date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> an outfit supporting American [[Esports]] team [[FaZe Clan|Faze Clan]] as part of the game's ''Pilot Program'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-pilot-program-skins|title=Rainbow Six Siege\u2019s profit-sharing Pilot Program skins are available now|last=Boudreau|first=Ian|date=December 5, 2018|website=PCGamesN|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206040737/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-pilot-program-skins|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-6-siege-esports-weapon-skins|title=Rainbow Six Siege to roll out esports team weapon skins and charms with Grim Sky|last=Boudreau|first=Ian|date=August 18, 2018|website=PCGamesN|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622093150/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-6-siege-esports-weapon-skins|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> and exclusive outfit and weapon skins if the player linked their [[Twitch Prime]] accounts to their [[Uplay|UPlay]] account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/twitch-prime-rainbow-six-siege-packs-how-get-free-loot-ubisoft-club-1109915|title=Twitch Prime users can get eight free Twitch Prime packs this month|last=Asarch|first=Steven|date=September 6, 2018|website=[[Newsweek]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009183016/https://www.newsweek.com/twitch-prime-rainbow-six-siege-packs-how-get-free-loot-ubisoft-club-1109915|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> In February 2019, Ubisoft unveiled an Elite skin set for Hibana, which contained the 'Onkochishin' uniform that draws inspiration from her Japanese heritage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/hibana-elite-skin-release-date|title=Rainbow Six Siege Hibana Elite skin release date: when you can get the Onkochishin bundle|last=Forward|first=Jordan|date=February 20, 2019|website=PCGamesN|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218030152/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/hibana-elite-skin-release-date|archive-date=February 18, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/videos/rainbow-six-siege-hibana-elite-set-official-traile/2300-6448408/|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Hibana Elite Set Official Trailer|last=Kulasingha|first=Gajan|date=February 18, 2019|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> The uniforms unique victory animation shows her using a traditional Japanese [[longbow]] known as a [[Yumi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/ubisoft-shows-off-sieges-new-hibana-elite-skin/|title=Ubisoft shows off Siege's new Hibana Elite skin|last=Dahlgren|first=Lisa|date=February 19, 2019|website=[[Gamereactor|Gamereactor UK]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSeveral video game magazines have included her in lists detailing the best operators in ''Rainbow Six Siege'',<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/rainbow-six-siege-guide-best-attacker-operators/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Guide: Best Attacker Operators For Y4S1|last=Keyes|first=Rob|date=March 5, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306133719/https://screenrant.com/rainbow-six-siege-guide-best-attacker-operators/|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-operators|title=Best Rainbow Six Siege operators|last=|first=|date=July 15, 2019|website=[[PCGamesN]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701171753/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-operators|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operators/|title=The best Rainbow Six Siege operators: Who to pick in 2019|last=Park|first=Morgan|date=June 20, 2019|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722045953/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operators/|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> with ''[[VG247]]''<nowiki/>'s Mitch Lineham listing her as the 7th best attacker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/07/23/rainbow-six-siege-operator-tier-best-attacker-defenders/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Operator tier ranks - the best and worst Attackers and Defenders|last=Lineham|first=Mitch|date=July 23, 2018|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724110551/https://www.vg247.com/2018/07/23/rainbow-six-siege-operator-tier-best-attacker-defenders/|archive-date=July 24, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> and writers for ''[[GameSpot]]'' including her in articles about the best operators to choose for beginners and experts at the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/best-rainbow-six-siege-operators-for-beginners/2900-1848/5/|title=Best Rainbow Six Siege Operators For Beginners|last=|first=|date=April 3, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/best-rainbow-six-siege-operators-for-experts-opera/2900-1866/5/|title=Best Rainbow Six Siege Operators For Experts (Operation Chimera Update)|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=April 6, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Hibana was also mentioned by Sam Greer of ''[[Eurogamer]]'' as her favourite operator when talking about diversity within the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-13-how-rainbow-six-siege-brings-diversity-to-the-military-shooter|title=How Rainbow Six Siege brings diversity to the military shooter|last=Greer|first=Sam|date=May 13, 2019|website=[[Eurogamer]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512172224/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-13-how-rainbow-six-siege-brings-diversity-to-the-military-shooter|archive-date=May 12, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHibana is also one of the most popular operators to play as, at an 86.4% operator usage rate\u2014the rate in which an operator has to appear in a round\u2014calculated near the end of ''Rainbow Six Siege''<nowiki/>'s third season, compared to operator usage rates of Ash at 65.1%, Thermite at 47.6%, Thatcher at 46.5%, and Buck at 41.1%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/hibana-and-ela-are-hugely-popular-siege-operators/|title=Hibana and Ela are hugely popular Siege Operators|last=Bishop|first=Sam|date=November 18, 2017|website=Gamereactor UK|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> While talking to fans in an Ask Me Anything on Reddit, The balancing team for the game stated that Hibana was considered to be well-balanced and was in a \"good place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/24/ubisoft-calls-rainbow-six-sieges-lion-its-biggest-mistake-in-reddit-qa-more-reworks-on-the-way/|title=Ubisoft Calls Lion Rainbow Six Siege's \"Biggest Mistake\" In Reddit Q&A, More Reworks On The Way|last=Parlock|first=Joe|date=October 24, 2018|website=Forbes|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106221357/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/24/ubisoft-calls-rainbow-six-sieges-lion-its-biggest-mistake-in-reddit-qa-more-reworks-on-the-way/|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-us/game-info/operators/hibana/ Hibana's profile] at publisher's homepage\n\n{{Tom Clancy games}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional special forces personnel]]\n[[Category:Female characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional military personnel in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Fictional Japanese people in video games]]\n[[Category:Tom Clancy characters]]\n[[Category:Ubisoft characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game character}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Hibana (''Rainbow Six Siege'')}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name = Yumiko \"Hibana\" Imagawa\n| image = File:Hibana_Rainbow6_artwork.png\n| alt = Artwork of the article subject, a Special operations personnel wearing heavy, dark clothing. She rests a large firearm on her right shoulder.\n| caption = Hibana as she appears in ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege#Downloadable content and expansion packs|Operation Red Crow]]'' (2016)\n| creator = [[Ubisoft Montreal]]\n| series = [[Tom Clancy's]]\n| first = ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege#Downloadable content and expansion packs|Operation Red Crow]]'' (2016)\n| gender = Female\n| significant_other = Jack Estrada\n| nationality = Japanese\n| voice = Laura Miyata\n}}\n{{Rainbow Six Siege series}}\n{{nihongo|'''Yumiko \"Hibana\" Imagawa'''|\u4eca\u5ddd \u7531\u7f8e\u5b50|Imagawa Yumiko|lead=yes}}, is a fictional [[player character]] who appears in the 2015 video game ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege]]''\u2014a [[Tactical shooter|tactical]] [[Online game|online]] [[first-person shooter]] developed by [[Ubisoft Montreal]]\u2014and other video games published by French video game publisher [[Ubisoft]]. She was introduced in the fourth expansion ''Operation Red Crow'', released on November 17, 2016.\n\nIn ''Rainbow Six Siege'' lore, Hibana was born and raised in [[Nagoya]], [[Japan]] and is a skilled martial artist who joined the [[National Police Agency (Japan)|National Police Academy]] at age 18. Nicknamed \"Hibana\" because of her style of leadership, she developed tactical versatility while training with elite [[police tactical unit]]s [[FBI Special Weapons and Tactics Teams|FBI SWAT]] and [[GIGN]] and was known as an expert in gaining entry in high-risk areas and onrush tactics. After training, she was recruited by the [[Aichi Prefectural Police|Aichi Prefectural Police Department]]'s Special Unit.\n\nWithin the game, Hibana has access to her \"X-Kairos\", a specialised [[40 mm grenade|40 mm]] calibre launcher used to project six explosive pellets that can be remotely detonated. It can be used in various ways, such as creating [[sightlines]], entry points, crawlspaces, or destroying [[Trap door|hatches]].\n\n==Development and release==\nBefore release, Ubisoft announced that the fourth free expansion for ''Rainbow Six Siege'' as ''Operation Red Crow'', with fans speculating that it would be set in Japan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-red-crow-adds-a-pair-of-japanese-operators/|title=Rainbow Six Siege: Operation Red Crow adds a pair of Japanese operators|last=Chalk|first=Andy|date=November 2, 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026213638/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-red-crow-adds-a-pair-of-japanese-operators/|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> with Reddit user Cheesetoaster13 soon leaking images of the two Japanese operators to the official ''Rainbow Six Siege'' [[subreddit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/02/rainbow-six-siege-japan-dlc-is-called-operation-red-crow-new-operators-leak/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Japan DLC is called Operation Red Crow, new operators leak|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=November 2, 2016|website=[[VG247]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508223803/http://www.vg247.com/2016/11/02/rainbow-six-siege-japan-dlc-is-called-operation-red-crow-new-operators-leak/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> On November 17, 2016, Ubisoft released the expansion for Season Pass owners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/news/13129-rainbow-six-siege-continues-postlaunch-support-with-tomorrows-operation-red-crow|title=Rainbow Six Siege Continues Post-Launch Support With Tomorrow's Operation Red Crow|last=Leack|first=Jonathan|date=November 16, 2016|website=[[GameRevolution]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-red-crow-update-gets-a-release-/1100-6445329/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Red Crow Update Gets a Release Date|last=Pereira|first=Chris|date=November 10, 2016|website=[[GameSpot]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724020530/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-red-crow-update-gets-a-release-/1100-6445329/|archive-date=July 24, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Alongside Skyscraper, a map available to the public for free, two operators from Japan's special police force [[Special Assault Team]] (SAT) were released as part of the expansion, including Hibana, a stealth-focused operator.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-fourth-season-content-featured-in-new-videos/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's season four content featured in two new videos|last=Prescott|first=Shaun|date=November 8, 2016|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026213623/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-fourth-season-content-featured-in-new-videos/|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom September 25, 2018, Ubisoft announced that all Year One operators, including Hibana, would be put up for sale for 40% less than their usual selling price.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neowin.net/news/the-eight-year-one-operators-of-rainbow-six-siege-gets-discounted-by-ubisoft|title=The eight Year One operators of Rainbow Six Siege gets discounted by Ubisoft|last=Ariyasinghe|first=Pulasthi|date=September 25, 2018|website=[[Neowin]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925190848/https://www.neowin.net/news/the-eight-year-one-operators-of-rainbow-six-siege-gets-discounted-by-ubisoft|archive-date=September 25, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-6-siege-year-1-operators-price-has-been-dropped-until-next-year/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Year 1 operators price has been dropped until next year|last=James|first=Sarah|date=September 25, 2018|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701074202/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-6-siege-year-1-operators-price-has-been-dropped-until-next-year/|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/25/rainbow-six-siege-year-1-operators-temporary-price-cut/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Year 1 operators price cut by 40% for a limited time|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=September 25, 2018|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926115001/https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/25/rainbow-six-siege-year-1-operators-temporary-price-cut/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Post-release===\nUpon release, it was discovered that if playing on the [[PlayStation 4]] version of the game, a [[Software bug|bug]] could occur that could cause the game to drop it's [[frame rate]] (FPS) to 0 when using her gadget. Ubisoft quickly pulled her from rotation, making her inaccessible, until a [[Patch (computing)|patch]] was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-disables-clash-other-gadgets-causing-game-breaking-exploits/|title=Rainbow Six Siege disables Clash, other gadgets causing game-breaking exploits|last=Park|first=Morgan|date=May 17, 2019|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603174453/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-disables-clash-other-gadgets-causing-game-breaking-exploits/|archive-date=June 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/21/rainbow-six-siege-ubisoft-re-added-bugged-operator-hibana-to-prevent-a-worse-bug-from-happening/|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Ubisoft re-added bugged operator Hibana to prevent a worse bug from happening|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=November 21, 2019|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124095527/http://www.vg247.com/2016/11/21/rainbow-six-siege-ubisoft-re-added-bugged-operator-hibana-to-prevent-a-worse-bug-from-happening/|archive-date=November 24, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> The bug was fixed in the game's 5.1 update, released the week after the launch of Operation Red Crow, alongside other issues concerning the X-Kairos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/97811/rainbow-six-siege-51-patch-fixes-hibana-glitch-changes-vote-kicks|title=Rainbow Six Siege 5.1 patch fixes Hibana glitch, changes vote kicks|last=Keefer|first=John|date=November 22, 2016|website=[[Shacknews]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123172241/http://www.shacknews.com/article/97811/rainbow-six-siege-51-patch-fixes-hibana-glitch-changes-vote-kicks|archive-date=November 23, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Rainbow Six Siege''<nowiki/>'s Update 2.1.1 brought various fixes to the X-Kairos, with Ubisoft noting various issues, including times when some of the pellets won't explode, a bug where pellets aren't displayed properly when shot between two reinforced walls, and a Lingering visual effect after detonation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/827403/Rainbow-Six-Siege-title-update-2-1-1-servers-down-LIVE-patch-notes-release-time|title=Rainbow Six Siege update 2.1.1 - Alpha Packs coming, release date reveal next week?|last=Dassanayake|first=Dion|date=July 13, 2017|website=[[Daily Express]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709063423/https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/827403/Rainbow-Six-Siege-title-update-2-1-1-servers-down-LIVE-patch-notes-release-time|archive-date=July 9, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-introduces-loot-boxes-bal/1100-6451582/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Update Introduces Loot Boxes, Balance Changes, More|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=July 11, 2017|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019194140/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-introduces-loot-boxes-bal/1100-6451582/|archive-date=October 19, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-sieges-loot-box-system-is-rolling-out-today/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's loot box system is rolling out today|last=Prescott|first=Shaun|date=July 12, 2017|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208210734/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-sieges-loot-box-system-is-rolling-out-today/|archive-date=February 8, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Unfortunately for players, the update failed to fix the issue concerning pellets not exploding when detonated. In the patch notes of Update 2.1.3, Ubisoft stated that they planned to fix the bug by the second season of the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-coming-today-changes-lots/1100-6449453/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Update Coming Today, Changes Lots Of Operators|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=April 19, 2017|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020234947/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-update-coming-today-changes-lots/1100-6449453/|archive-date=October 20, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/19/rainbow-six-siege-update-2-1-3-out-on-all-platforms-hibanas-x-kairos-bug-wont-be-fixed-until-y2s2/|title=Rainbow Six Siege update 2.1.3 out on all platforms, Hibana\u2019s X-KAIROS bug won't be fixed until Y2S2|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=April 19, 2017|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704174938/https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/19/rainbow-six-siege-update-2-1-3-out-on-all-platforms-hibanas-x-kairos-bug-wont-be-fixed-until-y2s2/|archive-date=July 4, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/793873/Rainbow-Six-Siege-update-Ubisoft-patch-notes-new-operator-PS4-Xbox-One|title=Rainbow Six Siege update: Ubisoft patch notes confirm new operator changes on PS4 and Xbox|last=Jones|first=Gary|date=April 19, 2017|website=Daily Express|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924105722/https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/793873/Rainbow-Six-Siege-update-Ubisoft-patch-notes-new-operator-PS4-Xbox-One|archive-date=September 24, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Operation Grim Sky'' expansion, released to the ''Technical Test Server'' (TTS) in August 2018, buffed the X-Kairos to be able to destroy a hatch with only four pellets rather than six to partially fix a bug where the latter would not hit it's intended target.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/08/24/rainbow-six-sieges-grim-sky-test-server-rebalances-more-operators-glaz-hibana-zofia-and-maverick/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Grim Sky Test Server Rebalances More Operators: Glaz, Hibana, Zofia and Maverick|last=Parlock|first=Joe|date=August 24, 2018|website=[[Forbes]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827174311/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/08/24/rainbow-six-sieges-grim-sky-test-server-rebalances-more-operators-glaz-hibana-zofia-and-maverick/|archive-date=August 27, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/new-nerfs-coming-to-maverick-zofia-glaz-in-rainbow-six-siege/|title=New nerfs coming to Maverick, Zofia, Glaz in Rainbow Six Siege|last=Park|first=Morgan|date=August 23, 2018|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416193750/https://www.pcgamer.com/new-nerfs-coming-to-maverick-zofia-glaz-in-rainbow-six-siege/|archive-date=April 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> An additional fix was added to the update where, in some instances, reinforced wall debris will remain floating even though the wall was destroyed by the X-Kairos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sieges-grim-sky-update-is-live-here-are-the-full-p/1100-6461547/|title=Siege's Grim Sky Update Is Live; Here Are The Full Patch Notes|last=Ram\u00e9e|first=Jordan|date=September 10, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911034304/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sieges-grim-sky-update-is-live-here-are-the-full-p/1100-6461547/|archive-date=September 11, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Story and character===\n====Biography====\nHibana was born the daughter of a butcher and was inspired by her family to start practising [[Ky\u016bd\u014d]] at a young age. The [[ranged weapon]] training obtained from the practice was followed by her entering martial arts and perfecting multiple assessments while carrying precise, controlled, and fluid motions.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Background:''' The daughter of a local butcher, Imagawa was inspired by her family to practice Ky\u016bd\u014d from a young age. This long range weapon marked her entry in martial arts by perfecting her assessment of multiple factors a once while carrying precise, controlled, and fluid motions.}}</ref>\n\nWhile studying at the National Police Academy, she was the nickname \"Hibana\" because of her [[improvised explosive device]]s and leadership skills while on the field. She was recruited by the Ichi Prefectural Police Department Special Unit because of her lethality and fluency in seven languages. The recruitment allowed her charisma and various techniques and to quickly move up in the ranks.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Background:''' Her area of expertise is to gain entry in high-risk areas. During her studies at the National Police Academy, she gained the nickname Hibana due to her improvised explosive devices and brilliant leadership skills on the field. Fluent in seven languages and lethal with any weapon, Imagawa was recruited by the Aichi Prefectural Police Department Special Unit, where her diverse techniques and charisma allowed her to move up the ranks quickly.}}</ref>\n\nOriginally from Nagoya, Hibana travelled the world to perfect her technique and skills. She specialises in paramilitary techniques, gained by training with the Special Air Service, FBI SWAT, GIGN, and various other special forces units. She acquired tactical versatility from her diverse training, including proficiency in performing [[Offensive (military)|assaults]] in [[Tube (structure)|tubular spaces]] such as [[bus]]es, [[train]]s and [[Airplane|aeroplanes]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Background:''' A Nagoya native, Imagawa traveled the world to perfect her skills and technique. She is specialized in paramilitary techniques gained by training with the SAS, FBI SWAT, and GIGN, to name a few. From her diverse training, she acquired a rare tactical versatility, which includes a proficiency in tubular (bus, train, and airplane) assaults.}}</ref>\n\n====Personality====\nConsidered a natural team builder, Hibana is passionate and adaptive in her fields. She has inspired experts from diverse backgrounds to work alongside each other to reach a common goal.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|developer=Ubisoft Montreal|publisher=Ubisoft|date=November 17, 2016|platform=PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Windows|level=Hibana's bio|quote='''Psychological Profile:''' Imagawa is a natural team builder. Passionate and adaptive, she inspires experts from diverse backgrounds to work together and reach a common goal..}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n[[File:Hibana_Kairos_gameplay_example.jpg|thumb|right|A gameplay screenshot showcasing Hibana using her X-Kairos gadget to blow a hole in a wall.]]\nIn ''Rainbow Six Siege,'' Hibana is a light-armoured attacking operator who is equipped with the \"X-Kairos\", a 40&nbsp;mm calibre launcher that fires six explosive pellets simultaneously that can be remotely detonated from a safe distance.<ref name=\":2\" /> The launcher can be used to blow open holes in walls, creating either [[sightline]]s or entry points depending on how the player uses it.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFor firearms, she possesses either a [[Benelli Supernova]] pump-action shotgun or a [[Howa Type 89]] assault rifle as primary weapons and either a [[SIG Sauer P226|SIG Sauer P229]] semi-automatic pistol or a [[Minebea PM-9]] machine pistol as secondary weapons.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> She also has access to either [[stun grenade]]s or a [[M18 Claymore mine|claymore]] as gadgets, though the claymore was later replaced with a [[Door breaching#Explosive|breaching charge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/rainbow-six-siege-balance-changes-lion-blitz-virgil-nerf/|title=Meta-shifting balance changes coming to Rainbow Six Siege with nerfs to Lion, Blitz and Vigil|last=Billcliffe|first=James|date=April 25, 2018|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615082612/https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/rainbow-six-siege-balance-changes-lion-blitz-virgil-nerf/|archive-date=June 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/07/18/rainbow-six-siege-hibana-what-she-can-do-and-how-to-use-her/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Hibana: what she can do and how to use her|last=Irwin|first=Dave|date=July 18, 2018|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720165431/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/07/18/rainbow-six-siege-hibana-what-she-can-do-and-how-to-use-her/|archive-date=July 20, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom October 25 to October 31, 2018, Hibana, alongside various other operators, were made playable in the in-game Halloween-themed event ''Mad House'' and were each given event-exclusive uniforms which could be unlocked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/25/rainbow-six-sieges-halloween-event-is-finally-underway-but-not-for-long/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Halloween Event Is Finally Underway, But Not For Long|last=Parlock|first=Joe|date=October 25, 2018|website=Forbes|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620025045/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/25/rainbow-six-sieges-halloween-event-is-finally-underway-but-not-for-long/|archive-date=June 20, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.co.uk/2018/10/26/rainbow-6-siege-halloween-event-is-now-live|title=Rainbow 6: Siege's Spooks Get a Mad House for Halloween|last=James|first=Sarah|date=October 26, 2019|website=[[Kotaku UK]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHibana has received various unique cosmetic skins for her uniform and armoury, including cosmetics exclusive to the limited time ''Outbreak'' event,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-outbreak-event-detailed-features/1100-6456343/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Outbreak Event Detailed, Features Premium Cosmetic Loot Boxes|last=Pereira|first=Chris|date=January 29, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228214331/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-outbreak-event-detailed-features/1100-6456343/|archive-date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> an outfit supporting American [[Esports]] team [[FaZe Clan|Faze Clan]] as part of the game's ''Pilot Program'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-pilot-program-skins|title=Rainbow Six Siege\u2019s profit-sharing Pilot Program skins are available now|last=Boudreau|first=Ian|date=December 5, 2018|website=PCGamesN|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206040737/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-pilot-program-skins|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-6-siege-esports-weapon-skins|title=Rainbow Six Siege to roll out esports team weapon skins and charms with Grim Sky|last=Boudreau|first=Ian|date=August 18, 2018|website=PCGamesN|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622093150/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-6-siege-esports-weapon-skins|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> and exclusive outfit and weapon skins if the player linked their [[Twitch Prime]] accounts to their [[Uplay|UPlay]] account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/twitch-prime-rainbow-six-siege-packs-how-get-free-loot-ubisoft-club-1109915|title=Twitch Prime users can get eight free Twitch Prime packs this month|last=Asarch|first=Steven|date=September 6, 2018|website=[[Newsweek]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009183016/https://www.newsweek.com/twitch-prime-rainbow-six-siege-packs-how-get-free-loot-ubisoft-club-1109915|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> In February 2019, Ubisoft unveiled an Elite skin set for Hibana, which contained the 'Onkochishin' uniform that draws inspiration from her Japanese heritage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/hibana-elite-skin-release-date|title=Rainbow Six Siege Hibana Elite skin release date: when you can get the Onkochishin bundle|last=Forward|first=Jordan|date=February 20, 2019|website=PCGamesN|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218030152/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/hibana-elite-skin-release-date|archive-date=February 18, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/videos/rainbow-six-siege-hibana-elite-set-official-traile/2300-6448408/|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Hibana Elite Set Official Trailer|last=Kulasingha|first=Gajan|date=February 18, 2019|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> The uniforms unique victory animation shows her using a traditional Japanese [[longbow]] known as a [[Yumi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/ubisoft-shows-off-sieges-new-hibana-elite-skin/|title=Ubisoft shows off Siege's new Hibana Elite skin|last=Dahlgren|first=Lisa|date=February 19, 2019|website=[[Gamereactor|Gamereactor UK]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSeveral video game magazines have included her in lists detailing the best operators in ''Rainbow Six Siege'',<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/rainbow-six-siege-guide-best-attacker-operators/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Guide: Best Attacker Operators For Y4S1|last=Keyes|first=Rob|date=March 5, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306133719/https://screenrant.com/rainbow-six-siege-guide-best-attacker-operators/|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-operators|title=Best Rainbow Six Siege operators|last=|first=|date=July 15, 2019|website=[[PCGamesN]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701171753/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-operators|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operators/|title=The best Rainbow Six Siege operators: Who to pick in 2019|last=Park|first=Morgan|date=June 20, 2019|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722045953/https://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operators/|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> with ''[[VG247]]''<nowiki/>'s Mitch Lineham listing her as the 7th best attacker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/07/23/rainbow-six-siege-operator-tier-best-attacker-defenders/|title=Rainbow Six Siege Operator tier ranks - the best and worst Attackers and Defenders|last=Lineham|first=Mitch|date=July 23, 2018|website=VG247|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724110551/https://www.vg247.com/2018/07/23/rainbow-six-siege-operator-tier-best-attacker-defenders/|archive-date=July 24, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> and writers for ''[[GameSpot]]'' including her in articles about the best operators to choose for beginners and experts at the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/best-rainbow-six-siege-operators-for-beginners/2900-1848/5/|title=Best Rainbow Six Siege Operators For Beginners|last=|first=|date=April 3, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/best-rainbow-six-siege-operators-for-experts-opera/2900-1866/5/|title=Best Rainbow Six Siege Operators For Experts (Operation Chimera Update)|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=April 6, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Hibana was also mentioned by Sam Greer of ''[[Eurogamer]]'' as her favourite operator when talking about diversity within the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-13-how-rainbow-six-siege-brings-diversity-to-the-military-shooter|title=How Rainbow Six Siege brings diversity to the military shooter|last=Greer|first=Sam|date=May 13, 2019|website=[[Eurogamer]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512172224/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-13-how-rainbow-six-siege-brings-diversity-to-the-military-shooter|archive-date=May 12, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHibana is also one of the most popular operators to play as, at an 86.4% operator usage rate\u2014the rate in which an operator has to appear in a round\u2014calculated near the end of ''Rainbow Six Siege''<nowiki/>'s third season, compared to operator usage rates of Ash at 65.1%, Thermite at 47.6%, Thatcher at 46.5%, and Buck at 41.1%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/hibana-and-ela-are-hugely-popular-siege-operators/|title=Hibana and Ela are hugely popular Siege Operators|last=Bishop|first=Sam|date=November 18, 2017|website=Gamereactor UK|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> While talking to fans in an Ask Me Anything on Reddit, The balancing team for the game stated that Hibana was considered to be well-balanced and was in a \"good place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/24/ubisoft-calls-rainbow-six-sieges-lion-its-biggest-mistake-in-reddit-qa-more-reworks-on-the-way/|title=Ubisoft Calls Lion Rainbow Six Siege's \"Biggest Mistake\" In Reddit Q&A, More Reworks On The Way|last=Parlock|first=Joe|date=October 24, 2018|website=Forbes|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106221357/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/10/24/ubisoft-calls-rainbow-six-sieges-lion-its-biggest-mistake-in-reddit-qa-more-reworks-on-the-way/|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-us/game-info/operators/hibana/ Hibana's profile] at publisher's homepage\n\n{{Tom Clancy games}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional special forces personnel]]\n[[Category:Female characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional military personnel in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Fictional Japanese people in video games]]\n[[Category:Tom Clancy characters]]\n[[Category:Ubisoft characters]]\n", "name_user": "Bwills155244", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor grammatical errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hibana_(Rainbow_Six_Siege)"}
{"title_page": "Recording studio as an instrument", "text_new": "[[File:Studer J37 4-track tape recorder (1964-1972), Abbey Road Studios.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A Studer four-track tape recorder used at [[EMI Studios]] from 1965 to the 1970s]]\n\nIn [[music production]], the [[recording studio]] is often treated as a [[musical instrument]] when it plays a significant role in the [[music composition|composition of music]]. Sometimes called \"playing the studio\", the approach is typically embodied by artists or producers who place less emphasis on simply capturing live performances in studio and instead favor the creative use of studio technology in completing finished works.{{sfn|Greene|2016|p=179}} Techniques include the incorporation of [[noise in music|non-musical sounds]], [[overdub]]bing, [[magnetic tape|tape]] edits, [[sound synthesis]], [[Audio_signal_processing#Audio_effects|audio signal processing]], and combining segmented performances ([[Take#Music_recording|takes]]) into a unified whole.\n\nComposers have been exploiting the potentials of [[multitrack recording]] since the technology was made available to them. Before the late 1940s, musical recordings were typically created with the idea of presenting a faithful rendition of a real-life performance. Following the advent of three-track tape in the mid 1950s, recording spaces became more accustomed for in-studio composition. By the late 1960s, in-studio composition had become standard practice, and remained so into the 2010s. Despite the widespread changes that have led to more compact recording set-ups, individual components such as [[digital audio workstation]]s are still referred to as \"the studio\".\n\n==Definitions==\n{{Quote box|quote= There is no single instance in which the studio suddenly became recognized as an instrument, and even at present [2018] it may not have wide recognition as such. Nevertheless, there is a historical precedent of the studio\u2014broadly defined\u2014consciously being used to perform music.\n|source = \u2014Adam Bell, ''Dawn of the DAW: The Studio As Musical Instrument''{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=37}}\n|align = right\n|width = 25%}}\n\n\"Playing the studio\" is critical shorthand for in-studio composition.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Seymour|first1=Corey|title=Love & Mercy Does Justice to the Brilliance of Brian Wilson|journal=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=June 5, 2015|url=http://www.vogue.com/13266664/love-and-mercy-brian-wilson/|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}</ref> Definitions of the specific criterion of a \"musical instrument\" vary,{{sfn|Bell|2018|pp=34\u201335}} and it is unclear whether the \"studio as instrument\" concept extends to using multi-track recording simply to facilitate the basic music writing process.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=38}}  According to academic Adam Bell, some proposed definitions may be consistent with music produced in a recording studio, but not with music that relies heavily on [[digital audio workstation]]s (DAW).{{sfn|Bell|2018|pp=34\u201335}} Various music educators alluded to \"using the studio as a musical instrument\" in books published as early as the late 1960s.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=xvi}}\n\n[[Rock music|Rock]] historian Doyle Greene defines \"studio as compositional tool\" as a process in which music is produced around studio constructions rather than the more traditional method of capturing a live performance as is.{{sfn|Greene|2016|p=179}} Techniques include the incorporation of [[noise in music|non-musical sounds]], [[overdub]]bing, [[magnetic tape|tape]] edits, [[sound synthesis]], [[Audio_signal_processing#Audio_effects|audio signal processing]], and combining segmented performances ([[Take#Music_recording|takes]]) into a unified whole.{{sfn|Greene|2016|p=179}} Despite the widespread changes that have led to more compact recording set-ups, individual components such as DAWs are still referred to as \"the studio\".{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=34}}\n\n==Evolution of recording processes==\n[[File:MFQ with Phil Spector.jpg|thumb|right|[[Phil Spector]] (center) at [[Gold Star Studios]], where he developed his [[Wall of Sound]] methods, 1965]]\n\nComposers have been exploiting the potentials of [[multitrack recording]] since the technology was made available to them.{{sfn|Eno|2004|p=127}} Before the late 1940s, musical recordings were typically created with the idea of presenting a faithful rendition of a real-life performance.{{sfn|Eno|2004|p=128}} Writing in 1937, the American composer [[John Cage]] called for the development of \"centers of experimental music\" places where \"the new materials, oscillators, turntables, generators, means for amplifying small sounds, film phonographs, etc.\" would allow composers to \"work using twentieth-century means for making music.\"<ref>Cage, J.(2004),'The Future of Music Credo,'in Cox, Christoph; Warner, Daniel. Audio Culture: Readings in Modern Music. A&C Black. {{ISBN|978-0-8264-1615-5}}.</ref>\n\nIn the early 1950s, electronic equipment was expensive to own, and for most people, was only accessible through large organizations or institutions. However, virtually every young composer was interested in the potential of tape-based recording.<ref name=\"HolmesHolmes2002\">{{cite book|last1=Holmes|first1=Thomas B.|last2=Holmes|first2=Thom|title=Electronic and Experimental Music: Pioneers in Technology and Composition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILkquoGXEq0C|year=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-93644-6|pages=81\u201385}}</ref> According to [[Brian Eno]], \"the move to tape was very important\", because unlike [[gramophone records]], tape was \"malleable and mutable and cuttable and reversible in ways that discs aren't. It's very hard to do anything interesting with a disc\".{{sfn|Eno|2004|p=128}} In the mid 1950s, popular recording conventions changed profoundly with the advent of three-track tape,{{sfn|Eno|2004|pp=128\u2013129}} and by the early 1960s, it was common for producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with [[musical form]], [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].{{sfn|Blake|2009|p=45}}\n\nIn-studio composition became standard practice by the late 1960s and early 1970s, and remained so into the 2010s. During the 1970s, the \"studio as instrument\" concept shifted from the studio's recording space to the studio's control room, where electronic instruments could be plugged directly into the mixing console.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=49}} As of the 2010s, the \"studio as instrument\" idea remains ubiquitous in genres such as [[pop music|pop]], [[hip-hop music|hip-hop]], and electronic music.<ref name=\"Ableton1\">{{cite web|title=A Brief History of The Studio As An Instrument: Part 1 - Early Reflections|url=https://www.ableton.com/en/blog/studio-as-an-instrument-part-1/|website=Ableton.com|date=October 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable artists and works==\n===1940s\u20131950s===\n* Pioneers from the 1940s include [[Bill Putnam]], [[Les Paul]], and [[Tom Dowd]], who each contributed to the development of common recording practices like reverb, [[Delay (audio effect)|tape delay]], and [[overdubbing]]. Putnam was one of the first to recognize echo and reverb as elements to enhance a recording, rather than as natural byproducts of the recording space. He engineered [[the Harmonicats]]' 1947 novelty song \"[[Peg o' My Heart]]\", which was a significant chart hit and became the first popular recording to use artificial reverb for artistic effect.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/> Although Les Paul was not the first to use overdubs, he popularized the technique in the 1950s.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=12, 39}}\n\n* Around the same time, French composers [[Pierre Schaeffer]] and [[Pierre Henry]] were developing ''[[musique concrete]]'', a method of composition in which pieces of tape are rearranged and spliced together, and thus originated [[sampling (music)|sampling]]. Meanwhile in England, [[Daphne Oram]] experimented heavily with [[electronic instrument]]s during her tenure as a balancing engineer for the [[BBC]], however, her tape experiments were mostly unheard at the time.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/>\n\n===1950s\u20131960s===\n{{Listen\n|filename=Telstar.ogg\n|title=The Tornadoes \u2013 \"Telstar\" (1962)\n|pos=right\n|description  = Meek's best-known production, \"[[Telstar (song)|Telstar]]\", features a sped-up piano, a [[clavioline]] overdubbed three times, and a guitar that fades in and out of the recording.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/> The piece won an [[Ivor Novello Award]] and sold over five million copies worldwide.\n}}\n\n* English producer [[Joe Meek]] is considered one of the most influential engineers of all time,{{by whom?|date=October 2018}} being one of the first to exploit the use of recording studios as instruments, and one of the first producers to assert an [[auteur|individual identity as an artist]].<ref name=\"tmtpat2013\">{{cite web|last1=Patrick|first1=Jonathan|title=Joe Meek's pop masterpiece ''I Hear a New World'' gets the chance to haunt a whole new generation of audiophile geeks|url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/joe-meeks-pop-masterpiece-i-hear-a-new-world-gets-the-chance-to-haunt-a-whole-new-generation-of|website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date=March 8, 2013}}</ref> He got his start in 1955 at [[IBC Studios]] in London. One of Meek's signature techniques was to overload a signal with [[dynamic range compression]], which was unorthodox at the time. He was antagonized by his employers for his \"radical\" techniques. Some of these methods, such as close-miking instruments, later became part of normal recording practice.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/>\n\n* Discussing [[Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller]], Adam Bell describes the songwriting duo's productions for [[the Coasters]] as \"an excellent example of their pioneering practices in the emerging field of production\", citing an account from Stoller in which he recalls \"cutting esses off words, sticking the tape back together so you didn't notice. And sometimes if the first refrain on a take was good and the second one lousy, we'd tape another recording of the first one and stick it in place of the second one.\"{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=39}}\n\n* Phil Spector, sometimes regarded as Joe Meek's American counterpart,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gritten|first1=David|title=Joe Meek and the tragic demise of the maverick who revolutionised British pop|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/joe-meek-and-the-tragic-demise-of-the-maverick-who-revolutionise/|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=October 1, 2016}}</ref> is also considered \"important as the first star producer of popular music and its first 'auteur' ... Spector changed pop music from a performing art ... to an art which could sometimes exist only in the recording studio\".{{sfn|Bannister|2007|p=38}} His original production formula (dubbed the \"Wall of Sound\") called for large ensembles (including some instruments not generally used for ensemble playing, such as [[electric guitar|electric]] and [[acoustic guitar]]s), with multiple instruments doubling and even tripling many of the parts to create a fuller, richer sound.{{sfn|Zak|2001|p=77}}{{refn|group=nb|For example, Spector would often duplicate a part played by an [[acoustic piano]] with an [[electric piano]] and a [[harpsichord]].{{sfn|Ribowsky|1989|pp=185-186}} Session guitarist [[Barney Kessel]] notes: \"Musically, it was terribly simple, but the way he recorded and miked it, they\u2019d diffuse it so that you couldn't pick out any one instrument. Techniques like distortion and echo were not new, but Phil came along and took these to make sounds that had not been used in the past. I thought it was ingenious.\"{{sfn|Ribowsky|1989|pp=185-186}} }} It evolved from his mid-1950s work with Leiber and Stoller during the period in which they sought a fuller sound through excessive instrumentation.{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=10}}{{refn|group=nb|Leiber and Stoller considered Spector's methods to be very distinct from what they were doing, stating: \"Phil was the first one to use multiple [[drum kit]]s, three pianos and so on. We went for much more clarity in terms of instrumental colors, and he deliberately blended everything into a kind of mulch. He definitely had a different point of view.\"{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=10}}}} His 1963 production of \"[[Be My Baby]]\", according to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, was a \"[[Rosetta Stone|Rosetta stone]] for studio pioneers such as [[the Beatles]] and [[Brian Wilson]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11028260/the_rs_500_greatest_songs_of_all_time/1|title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|publisher=RollingStone.com|accessdate=2007-06-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516110704/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11028260/the_rs_500_greatest_songs_of_all_time/1|archivedate=16 May 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Beatles and George Martin in studio 1966.JPG|thumb|right|Martin working with the Beatles, 1964]]\n\n* The Beatles' producer [[George Martin]] and [[the Beach Boys]]' producer-songwriter Brian Wilson are generally credited with helping to popularize the idea of the studio as an instrument used for in-studio composition, and music producers after the mid 1960s increasingly drew from their work.{{sfn|Edmondson|2013|p=890}}{{refn|group=nb|Academic [[Bill Martin (philosophy)|Bill Martin]] writes that the advancing technology of multitrack recording and [[mixing board]]s were more influential to [[experimental rock]] than [[electronic instruments]] such as the [[synthesizer]], allowing the Beatles and the Beach Boys to become the first crop of non-[[classically trained]] musicians to create extended and complex compositions.{{sfn|Martin|2015|p=75}}}} Although Martin was nominally the Beatles' producer, from 1964 he ceded control to the band, allowing them to use the studio as a workshop for their ideas and later as a sound laboratory.{{sfn|Millard|2012|pp=178\u201379}} Musicologist Olivier Julien writes that the Beatles' \"gradual integration of arranging and recording into one and the same process\" began as early as 1963, but developed in earnest during the sessions for ''[[Rubber Soul]]'' (1965) and ''[[Revolver (Beatles album)|Revolver]]'' (1966) and \"ultimately blossomed\" during the sessions for ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' (1967).{{sfn|Julien|2008|p=162}} Wilson, who was mentored by Spector,{{sfn|Cogan|Clark|2003|pp=32\u201333}} was another early auteur of popular music.{{sfn|Edmondson|2013|p=890}} Authors Jim Cogan and William Clark credit him as the first rock producer to use the studio as a discrete instrument.{{sfn|Cogan|Clark|2003|pp=32\u201333}}\n\n{{Listen\n|filename=Tomorrow Never Knows (Beatles song - sample).ogg\n|title=The Beatles \u2013 \"Tomorrow Never Knows\" (1966)\n|pos=right\n|description  = Author Mark Brend writes that, with ''Revolver'', the Beatles advanced on Meek's approach, and employed the studio as \"an environment for wide-ranging sonic research\" that included experimentation with [[tape loop]]s, reversed and speed-manipulated tape sounds, and backwards-recorded lead guitar parts.{{sfn|Brend|2005|pp=55\u201356}} \n}}\n\n: According to author David Howard, Martin's work on the Beatles' \"[[Tomorrow Never Knows]]\", from  ''Revolver'', and Spector's production  of \"[[River Deep \u2013 Mountain High]]\" from the same year were the two recordings that ensured that the studio \"was now its own instrument\".{{sfn|Howard|2004|pp=2\u20133}} Citing composer and producer [[Virgil Moorefield]]'s book ''The Producer as Composer'', author Jay Hodgson highlights ''Revolver'' as representing a \"dramatic turning point\" in recording history through its dedication to studio exploration over the \"performability\" of the songs, as this and subsequent Beatles albums reshaped listeners' preconceptions of a pop recording.{{sfn|Hodgson|2010|pp=viii\u2013ix}} According to Julien, the follow-up LP ''Sgt. Pepper'' represents the \"epitome of the transformation of the recording studio into a compositional tool\", marking the moment when \"popular music entered the era of phonographic composition.\"{{sfn|Julien|2008|pp=166\u2013167}} Composer and musicologist [[Michael Hannan (composer)|Michael Hannan]] attributes the album's impact to Martin and his engineers, in response to the Beatles' demands, making increasingly creative use of studio equipment and originating new processes.{{sfn|Hannan|2008|p=46}}\n\n: Like ''Revolver'', \"[[Good Vibrations]]\", which Wilson produced for the Beach Boys in 1966, was a prime proponent in revolutionizing rock from live concert performances into studio productions that could only exist on record.{{sfn|Ashby|2004|p=282}} For the first time, Wilson limited himself to recording short interchangeable fragments (or \"modules\") rather than a complete song. Through the method of [[tape splicing]], each fragment could then be assembled into a linear sequence \u2013 as Wilson explored on subsequent recordings from this period \u2013 allowing any number of larger structures and divergent moods to be produced at a later time.<ref name=\"ARP\">{{cite journal|last1=Heiser|first1=Marshall|title=SMiLE: Brian Wilson\u2019s Musical Mosaic|journal=The Journal on the Art of Record Production|date=November 2012|issue=7|url=http://arpjournal.com/smile-brian-wilson%E2%80%99s-musical-mosaic/}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Academic Marshall Heiser saw the resultant style of jumpcuts as a \"striking characteristic\", and that they \"must be acknowledged as compositional statements in themselves, giving the music a sonic signature every bit as noticeable as the performances themselves. There was no way this music could be 'real.' Wilson was therefore echoing the techniques of ''musique concr\u00e8te'' and seemed to be breaking the audio '[[fourth wall]]'\u2014if there can said to be such a thing.\"<ref name=\"ARP\">{{cite journal|last1=Heiser|first1=Marshall|title=SMiLE: Brian Wilson\u2019s Musical Mosaic|journal=The Journal on the Art of Record Production|date=November 2012|issue=7|url=http://arpjournal.com/smile-brian-wilson%E2%80%99s-musical-mosaic/}}</ref>}} Musicologist [[Charlie Gillett]] called \"Good Vibrations\" \"one of the first records to flaunt studio production as a quality in its own right, rather than as a means of presenting a performance\",{{sfn|Gillett|1984|p=329}} while rock critic [[Gene Sculatti]] called it the \"ultimate in-studio production trip\", adding that its influence was apparent in songs such as \"[[A Day in the Life]]\" from ''Sgt. Pepper''.<ref name=\"Scalluti1968\">{{cite magazine|last=Sculatti |first=Gene |authorlink=Gene Sculatti|url=http://www.teachrock.org/resources/article/villains-and-heroes-in-defense-of-the-beach-boys/ |title=Villains and Heroes: In Defense of the Beach Boys |magazine=Jazz & Pop |date=September 1968 |accessdate=10 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714191639/http://www.teachrock.org/resources/article/villains-and-heroes-in-defense-of-the-beach-boys/ |archivedate=14 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===1970s\u20132010s===\n[[File:Brian Eno live remix at Punkt 2012 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Brian Eno]] at a live remix in 2012]]\n\n* Adam Bell credits [[Brian Eno]] with popularizing the concept of the studio as instrument, particularly that it \"did not require previous experience, and in some ways, a lack of know-how might even be advantageous to creativity\", and that \"such an approach was typified\" by [[Kraftwerk]], whose members proclaimed \"we play the studio\".{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=49}} He goes on to say:\n\n: {{quote|While those of the ilk of Brian Wilson used the studio as an instrument by orchestrating everyone that worked within it, the turn to technology in the cases of [[Sly Stone]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], and Brian Eno signify a conceptual shift in which an alternative approach that might make using the studio as an instrument cheaper, easier, more convenient, or more creative, was increasingly sought after. Compared to the 1960s, using the studio as an instrument became less about working ''the system'' as it were, and working the ''systems''.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=49}} }}\n\n* Jamaican producer [[Lee \"Scratch\" Perry]] is noted for his 70s [[reggae]] and [[Dub music|dub]] productions, recorded at his [[Black Ark Studios|Black Ark]] studio.{{sfn|Toop|2018|p=115}} [[David Toop]] commented that \"at its heights, Perry's genius has transformed the recording studio\" into \"virtual space, an imaginary chamber over which presided the electronic wizard, evangelist, gossip columnist and Dr. Frankenstein that he became.\"{{sfn|Toop|2018|pp=114\u2014115}}\n\n* From the late 1970s onward, [[hip hop production]] has been strongly linked to the lineage and technique of earlier artists who used the studio as an instrument. Jazz critic [[Francis Davis]] identified early hip-hop [[Disc jockey|DJs]], including [[Afrika Bambaataa]] and [[Grandmaster Flash]], as \"grassroots successors to Phil Spector, Brian Wilson, and George Martin, the 1960s producers who pioneered the use of the recording studio as an instrument in its own right.\"{{sfn|Davis|2004|p=259}}\n\n[[File:MBV 2008.jpg|thumb|[[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]] performing in 2008]]\n\n* Beginning in the 1980s, musicians associated with the genres [[dream pop]] and [[shoegazing]] made innovative use of [[effects pedal]]s and recording techniques to create ethereal, \"dreamy\" musical atmospheres.{{sfn|Edmondson|2013|p=1205}} The English-Irish shoegazing band [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]], helmed by guitarist-producer [[Kevin Shields]], are often celebrated for their studio albums ''[[Isn't Anything]]'' (1988) and ''[[Loveless (My Bloody Valentine album)|Loveless]]'' (1991). Writing for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', [[Paul Lester]] said Shields is \"widely accepted as shoegazing's genius\", with \"his astonishing wall of sound, use of the studio as instrument and dazzling reinvention of the guitar making him a sort of hydra-headed Spector-[[Jimi Hendrix|Hendrix]]-Eno figure\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lester|first1=Paul|author-link=Paul Lester|title=Sonic Cathedral spark shoegazing music revival|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article6066716.ece|website=[[The Times|Times Online]]|date=April 12, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919185133/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article6066716.ece|archive-date=September 19, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Record production}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[Acousmatic music]]\n* [[Art pop]]\n* [[Click track]]\n* [[Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center]]\n* [[Electroacoustic music]]\n* [[Experimental pop]]\n* [[Groupe de Recherches Musicales]]\n* [[Lo-fi music|Lo-fi/DIY music]]\n* [[Post-punk]]\n* [[Psychedelic music]]\n* [[Recording consciousness]]\n* [[Recording practices of the Beatles]]\n* ''[[Soundbreaking]]'' documentary series\n* [[Xenochrony]]\n* [[Studio di fonologia musicale di Radio Milano]]\n* [[Studio for Electronic Music (WDR)]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb|30em}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Ashby|editor-first=Arved Mark|title=The Pleasure of Modernist Music: Listening, Meaning, Intention, Ideology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pit6yL_Few4C|year=2004|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-1-58046-143-6}}\n* {{cite book|first=Matthew|last=Bannister|title=White Boys, White Noise: Masculinities and 1980s Indie Guitar Rock|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ckLKGTXRwQC&pg=PA38|year=2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8803-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Bell|first=Adam Patrick|title=Dawn of the DAW: The Studio As Musical Instrument|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZD9FDwAAQBAJ|year=2018|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-029660-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Brend|first=Mark|title=Strange Sounds: Offbeat Instruments and Sonic Experiments in Pop|publisher=Backbeat Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2005|isbn=978-0-879308551|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cogan|first1=Jim|last2=Clark|first2=William|title=Temples of Sound: Inside the Great Recording Studios|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hO-KQ4o_B2MC|year=2003|publisher=Chronicle Books|isbn=978-0-8118-3394-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Francis |authorlink=Francis Davis |year=2004 |title=Jazz and Its Discontents: A Francis Davis Reader |publisher=Da Capo |isbn=0-306-81055-7 |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=QVr_AgAAQBAJ}} |ref={{SfnRef|Davis|2004}}}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Eno|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Eno|editor-last1=Cox|editor-first1=Christoph|editor-last2=Warner|editor-first2=Daniel|title=Audio Culture: Readings in Modern Music|chapter=The Studio as Compositional Tool|chapter-url=http://golancourses.net/2009ems1/pdf/sound_eno-the-studio-as-a-compositional-tool.pdf|year=2004|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-0-8264-1615-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Gillett|first=Charlie|authorlink=Charlie Gillett|title=The Sound of the City: The Rise of Rock and Roll|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzmhhXUwyt4C&pg=PA329|year=1984|publisher=Perseus Books Group|isbn=978-0-306-80683-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Greene|first=Doyle|title=Rock, Counterculture and the Avant-Garde, 1966\u20131970: How the Beatles, Frank Zappa and the Velvet Underground Defined an Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ELeaCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-2403-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hannan|first=Michael |year=2008|chapter= The sound design of ''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band''|title= Sgt. Pepper and the Beatles: It Was Forty Years Ago Today|editor-last=Julien |editor-first=Olivier|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-0-7546-6708-7|ref=harv|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=vZ-SB57WBo8C}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hodgson|first=Jay|year=2010|title=Understanding Records: A Field Guide to Recording Practice|publisher=Continuum|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-1-4411-5607-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Howard|first=David N.|year=2004|title=Sonic Alchemy: Visionary Music Producers and Their Maverick Recordings |publisher=Hal Leonard |location=Milwaukee, WI|isbn=0-634-05560-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Julien|first=Oliver |year=2008|chapter= 'A lucky man who made the grade': ''Sgt. Pepper'' and the rise of a phonographic tradition in twentieth-century popular music |title= Sgt. Pepper and the Beatles: It Was Forty Years Ago Today|editor-last=Julien |editor-first=Olivier|location=|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-0-7546-6708-7|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=vZ-SB57WBo8C}}|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Martin|first=Bill|title=Avant Rock: Experimental Music from the Beatles to Bjork|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CCLyCgAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=Open Court Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-8126-9939-5}}\n* {{cite book|last=Millard|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Beatlemania: Technology, Business, and Teen Culture in Cold War America|year=2012|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore, MD|isbn=978-1-4214-0525-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moorefield |first=Virgil |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Producer_as_Composer.html?id=PZ0R4_Oxr-4C&pg=PA18|title=The Producer as Composer: Shaping the Sounds of Popular Music|publisher=MIT Press |date=2010 |isbn=0-262-13457-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ribowsky|first=Mark|title=He's a Rebel|url=https://archive.org/details/hesrebel00ribo|url-access=registration|year=1989|publisher=Dutton|isbn=978-0-525-24727-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Toop|first=David|author-link=David Toop|title=Ocean of Sound: Ambient Sound and Radical Listening in the Age of Communication|year=2018|orig-year=First published 1995|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]]|isbn=978-1-78816-030-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zak|first=Albin|title=Poetics of Rock: Cutting Tracks, Making Records|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DJM6FgvlWw0C|year=2001|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92815-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|last=Eller|first=Dylan|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/03/28/revisiting-brian-enos-the-studio-as-a-compositional-tool/|title=Revisiting Brian Eno\u2019s \u2018The Studio as a Compositional Tool\u2019|date=March 28, 2016|website=[[TechCrunch]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schmidt Horning|first=Susan|year=2016 |orig-year=1st pub. 2012 by Ashgate|chapter=The Sounds of Space: Studio as Instrument in the Era of High Fidelity |title=The Art of Record Production: An Introductory Reader for a New Academic Field |editor1-last=Frith |editor1-first=Simon |editor1-link=Simon Frith |editor2-last=Zagorski-Thomas |editor2-first=Simon |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-4094-0562-7}}\n\n{{Music production}}\n[[Category:Recording studios| ]]\n[[Category:Musical instruments| Recording studio]]\n[[Category:Electronic music| ]]\n[[Category:Popular music]]\n[[Category:New media]]\n[[Category:20th century in music]]\n[[Category:21st century in music]]\n[[Category:Audio engineering]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Studer J37 4-track tape recorder (1964-1972), Abbey Road Studios.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A Studer four-track tape recorder used at [[EMI Studios]] from 1965 to the 1970s]]\n\nIn [[music production]], the [[recording studio]] is often treated as a [[musical instrument]] when it plays a significant role in the [[music composition|composition of music]]. Sometimes called \"playing the studio\", the approach is typically embodied by artists or producers who place less emphasis on simply capturing live performances in studio and instead favor the creative use of studio technology in completing finished works.{{sfn|Greene|2016|p=179}} Techniques include the incorporation of [[noise in music|non-musical sounds]], [[overdub]]bing, [[magnetic tape|tape]] edits, [[sound synthesis]], [[Audio_signal_processing#Audio_effects|audio signal processing]], and combining segmented performances ([[Take#Music_recording|takes]]) into a unified whole.\n\nComposers have been exploiting the potentials of [[multitrack recording]] since the technology was made available to them. Before the late 1940s, musical recordings were typically created with the idea of presenting a faithful rendition of a real-life performance. Following the advent of three-track tape in the mid 1950s, recording spaces became more accustomed for in-studio composition. By the late 1960s, in-studio composition had become standard practice, and remained so into the 2010s. Despite the widespread changes that have led to more compact recording set-ups, individual components such as [[digital audio workstation]]s are still referred to as \"the studio\".\n\n==Definitions==\n{{Quote box|quote= There is no single instance in which the studio suddenly became recognized as an instrument, and even at present [2018] it may not have wide recognition as such. Nevertheless, there is a historical precedent of the studio\u2014broadly defined\u2014consciously being used to perform music.\n|source = \u2014Adam Bell, ''Dawn of the DAW: The Studio As Musical Instrument''{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=37}}\n|align = right\n|width = 25%}}\n\n\"Playing the studio\" is critical shorthand for in-studio composition.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Seymour|first1=Corey|title=Love & Mercy Does Justice to the Brilliance of Brian Wilson|journal=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=June 5, 2015|url=http://www.vogue.com/13266664/love-and-mercy-brian-wilson/|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}</ref> Definitions of the specific criterion of a \"musical instrument\" vary,{{sfn|Bell|2018|pp=34\u201335}} and it is unclear whether the \"studio as instrument\" concept extends to using multi-track recording simply to facilitate the basic music writing process.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=38}}  According to academic Adam Bell, some proposed definitions may be consistent with music produced in a recording studio, but not with music that relies heavily on [[digital audio workstation]]s (DAW).{{sfn|Bell|2018|pp=34\u201335}} Various music educators alluded to \"using the studio as a musical instrument\" in books published as early as the late 1960s.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=xvi}}\n\n[[Rock music|Rock]] historian Doyle Greene defines \"studio as compositional tool\" as a process in which music is produced around studio constructions rather than the more traditional method of capturing a live performance as is.{{sfn|Greene|2016|p=179}} Techniques include the incorporation of [[noise in music|non-musical sounds]], [[overdub]]bing, [[magnetic tape|tape]] edits, [[sound synthesis]], [[Audio_signal_processing#Audio_effects|audio signal processing]], and combining segmented performances ([[Take#Music_recording|takes]]) into a unified whole.{{sfn|Greene|2016|p=179}} Despite the widespread changes that have led to more compact recording set-ups, individual components such as DAWs are still referred to as \"the studio\".{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=34}}\n\n==Evolution of recording processes==\n[[File:MFQ with Phil Spector.jpg|thumb|right|[[Phil Spector]] (center) at [[Gold Star Studios]], where he developed his [[Wall of Sound]] methods, 1965]]\n\nComposers have been exploiting the potentials of [[multitrack recording]] since the technology was made available to them.{{sfn|Eno|2004|p=127}} Before the late 1940s, musical recordings were typically created with the idea of presenting a faithful rendition of a real-life performance.{{sfn|Eno|2004|p=128}} Writing in 1937, the American composer [[John Cage]] called for the development of \"centers of experimental music\" places where \"the new materials, oscillators, turntables, generators, means for amplifying small sounds, film phonographs, etc.\" would allow composers to \"work using twentieth-century means for making music.\"<ref>Cage, J.(2004),'The Future of Music Credo,'in Cox, Christoph; Warner, Daniel. Audio Culture: Readings in Modern Music. A&C Black. {{ISBN|978-0-8264-1615-5}}.</ref>\n\nIn the early 1950s, electronic equipment was expensive to own, and for most people, was only accessible through large organizations or institutions. However, virtually every young composer was interested in the potential of tape-based recording.<ref name=\"HolmesHolmes2002\">{{cite book|last1=Holmes|first1=Thomas B.|last2=Holmes|first2=Thom|title=Electronic and Experimental Music: Pioneers in Technology and Composition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILkquoGXEq0C|year=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-93644-6|pages=81\u201385}}</ref> According to [[Brian Eno]], \"the move to tape was very important\", because unlike [[gramophone records]], tape was \"malleable and mutable and cuttable and reversible in ways that discs aren't. It's very hard to do anything interesting with a disc\".{{sfn|Eno|2004|p=128}} In the mid 1950s, popular recording conventions changed profoundly with the advent of three-track tape,{{sfn|Eno|2004|pp=128\u2013129}} and by the early 1960s, it was common for producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with [[musical form]], [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].{{sfn|Blake|2009|p=45}}\n\nIn-studio composition became standard practice by the late 1960s and early 1970s, and remained so into the 2010s. During the 1970s, the \"studio as instrument\" concept shifted from the studio's recording space to the studio's control room, where electronic instruments could be plugged directly into the mixing console.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=49}} As of the 2010s, the \"studio as instrument\" idea remains ubiquitous in genres such as [[pop music|pop]], [[hip-hop music|hip-hop]], and electronic music.<ref name=\"Ableton1\">{{cite web|title=A Brief History of The Studio As An Instrument: Part 1 - Early Reflections|url=https://www.ableton.com/en/blog/studio-as-an-instrument-part-1/|website=Ableton.com|date=October 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable artists and works==\n===1940s\u20131950s===\n* Pioneers from the 1940s include [[Bill Putnam]], [[Les Paul]], and [[Tom Dowd]], who each contributed to the development of common recording practices like reverb, [[Delay (audio effect)|tape delay]], and [[overdubbing]]. Putnam was one of the first to recognize echo and reverb as elements to enhance a recording, rather than as natural byproducts of the recording space. He engineered [[the Harmonicats]]' 1947 novelty song \"[[Peg o' My Heart]]\", which was a significant chart hit and became the first popular recording to use artificial reverb for artistic effect.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/> Although Les Paul was not the first to use overdubs, he popularized the technique in the 1950s.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=12, 39}}\n\n* Around the same time, French composers [[Pierre Schaeffer]] and [[Pierre Henry]] were developing ''[[musique concrete]]'', a method of composition in which pieces of tape are rearranged and spliced together, and thus originated [[sampling (music)|sampling]]. Meanwhile in England, [[Daphne Oram]] experimented heavily with [[electronic instrument]]s during her tenure as a balancing engineer for the [[BBC]], however, her tape experiments were mostly unheard at the time.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/>\n\n===1950s\u20131960s===\n{{Listen\n|filename=Telstar.ogg\n|title=The Tornadoes \u2013 \"Telstar\" (1962)\n|pos=right\n|description  = Meek's best-known production, \"[[Telstar (song)|Telstar]]\", features a sped-up piano, a [[clavioline]] overdubbed three times, and a guitar that fades in and out of the recording.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/> The piece won an [[Ivor Novello Award]] and sold over five million copies worldwide.\n}}\n\n* English producer [[Joe Meek]] is considered one of the most influential engineers of all time,{{by whom?|date=October 2018}} being one of the first to exploit the use of recording studios as instruments, and one of the first producers to assert an [[auteur|individual identity as an artist]].<ref name=\"tmtpat2013\">{{cite web|last1=Patrick|first1=Jonathan|title=Joe Meek's pop masterpiece ''I Hear a New World'' gets the chance to haunt a whole new generation of audiophile geeks|url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/joe-meeks-pop-masterpiece-i-hear-a-new-world-gets-the-chance-to-haunt-a-whole-new-generation-of|website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date=March 8, 2013}}</ref> He got his start in 1955 at [[IBC Studios]] in London. One of Meek's signature techniques was to overload a signal with [[dynamic range compression]], which was unorthodox at the time. He was antagonized by his employers for his \"radical\" techniques. Some of these methods, such as close-miking instruments, later became part of normal recording practice.<ref name=\"Ableton1\"/>\n\n* Discussing [[Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller]], Adam Bell describes the songwriting duo's productions for [[the Coasters]] as \"an excellent example of their pioneering practices in the emerging field of production\", citing an account from Stoller in which he recalls \"cutting esses off words, sticking the tape back together so you didn't notice. And sometimes if the first refrain on a take was good and the second one lousy, we'd tape another recording of the first one and stick it in place of the second one.\"{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=39}}\n\n* Phil Spector, sometimes regarded as Joe Meek's American counterpart,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gritten|first1=David|title=Joe Meek and the tragic demise of the maverick who revolutionised British pop|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/joe-meek-and-the-tragic-demise-of-the-maverick-who-revolutionise/|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=October 1, 2016}}</ref> is also considered \"important as the first star producer of popular music and its first 'auteur' ... Spector changed pop music from a performing art ... to an art which could sometimes exist only in the recording studio\".{{sfn|Bannister|2007|p=38}} His original production formula (dubbed the \"Wall of Sound\") called for large ensembles (including some instruments not generally used for ensemble playing, such as [[electric guitar|electric]] and [[acoustic guitars]]), with multiple instruments doubling and even tripling many of the parts to create a fuller, richer sound.{{sfn|Zak|2001|p=77}}{{refn|group=nb|For example, Spector would often duplicate a part played by an [[acoustic piano]] with an [[electric piano]] and a [[harpsichord]].{{sfn|Ribowsky|1989|pp=185-186}} Session guitarist [[Barney Kessel]] notes: \"Musically, it was terribly simple, but the way he recorded and miked it, they\u2019d diffuse it so that you couldn't pick out any one instrument. Techniques like distortion and echo were not new, but Phil came along and took these to make sounds that had not been used in the past. I thought it was ingenious.\"{{sfn|Ribowsky|1989|pp=185-186}} }} It evolved from his mid-1950s work with Leiber and Stoller during the period in which they sought a fuller sound through excessive instrumentation.{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=10}}{{refn|group=nb|Leiber and Stoller considered Spector's methods to be very distinct from what they were doing, stating: \"Phil was the first one to use multiple [[drum kit]]s, three pianos and so on. We went for much more clarity in terms of instrumental colors, and he deliberately blended everything into a kind of mulch. He definitely had a different point of view.\"{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=10}}}} His 1963 production of \"[[Be My Baby]]\", according to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, was a \"[[Rosetta Stone|Rosetta stone]] for studio pioneers such as [[the Beatles]] and [[Brian Wilson]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11028260/the_rs_500_greatest_songs_of_all_time/1|title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|publisher=RollingStone.com|accessdate=2007-06-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516110704/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11028260/the_rs_500_greatest_songs_of_all_time/1|archivedate=16 May 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Beatles and George Martin in studio 1966.JPG|thumb|right|Martin working with the Beatles, 1964]]\n\n* The Beatles' producer [[George Martin]] and [[the Beach Boys]]' producer-songwriter Brian Wilson are generally credited with helping to popularize the idea of the studio as an instrument used for in-studio composition, and music producers after the mid 1960s increasingly drew from their work.{{sfn|Edmondson|2013|p=890}}{{refn|group=nb|Academic [[Bill Martin (philosophy)|Bill Martin]] writes that the advancing technology of multitrack recording and [[mixing board]]s were more influential to [[experimental rock]] than [[electronic instruments]] such as the [[synthesizer]], allowing the Beatles and the Beach Boys to become the first crop of non-[[classically trained]] musicians to create extended and complex compositions.{{sfn|Martin|2015|p=75}}}} Although Martin was nominally the Beatles' producer, from 1964 he ceded control to the band, allowing them to use the studio as a workshop for their ideas and later as a sound laboratory.{{sfn|Millard|2012|pp=178\u201379}} Musicologist Olivier Julien writes that the Beatles' \"gradual integration of arranging and recording into one and the same process\" began as early as 1963, but developed in earnest during the sessions for ''[[Rubber Soul]]'' (1965) and ''[[Revolver (Beatles album)|Revolver]]'' (1966) and \"ultimately blossomed\" during the sessions for ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' (1967).{{sfn|Julien|2008|p=162}} Wilson, who was mentored by Spector,{{sfn|Cogan|Clark|2003|pp=32\u201333}} was another early auteur of popular music.{{sfn|Edmondson|2013|p=890}} Authors Jim Cogan and William Clark credit him as the first rock producer to use the studio as a discrete instrument.{{sfn|Cogan|Clark|2003|pp=32\u201333}}\n\n{{Listen\n|filename=Tomorrow Never Knows (Beatles song - sample).ogg\n|title=The Beatles \u2013 \"Tomorrow Never Knows\" (1966)\n|pos=right\n|description  = Author Mark Brend writes that, with ''Revolver'', the Beatles advanced on Meek's approach, and employed the studio as \"an environment for wide-ranging sonic research\" that included experimentation with [[tape loop]]s, reversed and speed-manipulated tape sounds, and backwards-recorded lead guitar parts.{{sfn|Brend|2005|pp=55\u201356}} \n}}\n\n: According to author David Howard, Martin's work on the Beatles' \"[[Tomorrow Never Knows]]\", from  ''Revolver'', and Spector's production  of \"[[River Deep \u2013 Mountain High]]\" from the same year were the two recordings that ensured that the studio \"was now its own instrument\".{{sfn|Howard|2004|pp=2\u20133}} Citing composer and producer [[Virgil Moorefield]]'s book ''The Producer as Composer'', author Jay Hodgson highlights ''Revolver'' as representing a \"dramatic turning point\" in recording history through its dedication to studio exploration over the \"performability\" of the songs, as this and subsequent Beatles albums reshaped listeners' preconceptions of a pop recording.{{sfn|Hodgson|2010|pp=viii\u2013ix}} According to Julien, the follow-up LP ''Sgt. Pepper'' represents the \"epitome of the transformation of the recording studio into a compositional tool\", marking the moment when \"popular music entered the era of phonographic composition.\"{{sfn|Julien|2008|pp=166\u2013167}} Composer and musicologist [[Michael Hannan (composer)|Michael Hannan]] attributes the album's impact to Martin and his engineers, in response to the Beatles' demands, making increasingly creative use of studio equipment and originating new processes.{{sfn|Hannan|2008|p=46}}\n\n: Like ''Revolver'', \"[[Good Vibrations]]\", which Wilson produced for the Beach Boys in 1966, was a prime proponent in revolutionizing rock from live concert performances into studio productions that could only exist on record.{{sfn|Ashby|2004|p=282}} For the first time, Wilson limited himself to recording short interchangeable fragments (or \"modules\") rather than a complete song. Through the method of [[tape splicing]], each fragment could then be assembled into a linear sequence \u2013 as Wilson explored on subsequent recordings from this period \u2013 allowing any number of larger structures and divergent moods to be produced at a later time.<ref name=\"ARP\">{{cite journal|last1=Heiser|first1=Marshall|title=SMiLE: Brian Wilson\u2019s Musical Mosaic|journal=The Journal on the Art of Record Production|date=November 2012|issue=7|url=http://arpjournal.com/smile-brian-wilson%E2%80%99s-musical-mosaic/}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Academic Marshall Heiser saw the resultant style of jumpcuts as a \"striking characteristic\", and that they \"must be acknowledged as compositional statements in themselves, giving the music a sonic signature every bit as noticeable as the performances themselves. There was no way this music could be 'real.' Wilson was therefore echoing the techniques of ''musique concr\u00e8te'' and seemed to be breaking the audio '[[fourth wall]]'\u2014if there can said to be such a thing.\"<ref name=\"ARP\">{{cite journal|last1=Heiser|first1=Marshall|title=SMiLE: Brian Wilson\u2019s Musical Mosaic|journal=The Journal on the Art of Record Production|date=November 2012|issue=7|url=http://arpjournal.com/smile-brian-wilson%E2%80%99s-musical-mosaic/}}</ref>}} Musicologist [[Charlie Gillett]] called \"Good Vibrations\" \"one of the first records to flaunt studio production as a quality in its own right, rather than as a means of presenting a performance\",{{sfn|Gillett|1984|p=329}} while rock critic [[Gene Sculatti]] called it the \"ultimate in-studio production trip\", adding that its influence was apparent in songs such as \"[[A Day in the Life]]\" from ''Sgt. Pepper''.<ref name=\"Scalluti1968\">{{cite magazine|last=Sculatti |first=Gene |authorlink=Gene Sculatti|url=http://www.teachrock.org/resources/article/villains-and-heroes-in-defense-of-the-beach-boys/ |title=Villains and Heroes: In Defense of the Beach Boys |magazine=Jazz & Pop |date=September 1968 |accessdate=10 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714191639/http://www.teachrock.org/resources/article/villains-and-heroes-in-defense-of-the-beach-boys/ |archivedate=14 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===1970s\u20132010s===\n[[File:Brian Eno live remix at Punkt 2012 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Brian Eno]] at a live remix in 2012]]\n\n* Adam Bell credits [[Brian Eno]] with popularizing the concept of the studio as instrument, particularly that it \"did not require previous experience, and in some ways, a lack of know-how might even be advantageous to creativity\", and that \"such an approach was typified\" by [[Kraftwerk]], whose members proclaimed \"we play the studio\".{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=49}} He goes on to say:\n\n: {{quote|While those of the ilk of Brian Wilson used the studio as an instrument by orchestrating everyone that worked within it, the turn to technology in the cases of [[Sly Stone]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], and Brian Eno signify a conceptual shift in which an alternative approach that might make using the studio as an instrument cheaper, easier, more convenient, or more creative, was increasingly sought after. Compared to the 1960s, using the studio as an instrument became less about working ''the system'' as it were, and working the ''systems''.{{sfn|Bell|2018|p=49}} }}\n\n* Jamaican producer [[Lee \"Scratch\" Perry]] is noted for his 70s [[reggae]] and [[Dub music|dub]] productions, recorded at his [[Black Ark Studios|Black Ark]] studio.{{sfn|Toop|2018|p=115}} [[David Toop]] commented that \"at its heights, Perry's genius has transformed the recording studio\" into \"virtual space, an imaginary chamber over which presided the electronic wizard, evangelist, gossip columnist and Dr. Frankenstein that he became.\"{{sfn|Toop|2018|pp=114\u2014115}}\n\n* From the late 1970s onward, [[hip hop production]] has been strongly linked to the lineage and technique of earlier artists who used the studio as an instrument. Jazz critic [[Francis Davis]] identified early hip-hop [[Disc jockey|DJs]], including [[Afrika Bambaataa]] and [[Grandmaster Flash]], as \"grassroots successors to Phil Spector, Brian Wilson, and George Martin, the 1960s producers who pioneered the use of the recording studio as an instrument in its own right.\"{{sfn|Davis|2004|p=259}}\n\n[[File:MBV 2008.jpg|thumb|[[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]] performing in 2008]]\n\n* Beginning in the 1980s, musicians associated with the genres [[dream pop]] and [[shoegazing]] made innovative use of [[effects pedal]]s and recording techniques to create ethereal, \"dreamy\" musical atmospheres.{{sfn|Edmondson|2013|p=1205}} The English-Irish shoegazing band [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]], helmed by guitarist-producer [[Kevin Shields]], are often celebrated for their studio albums ''[[Isn't Anything]]'' (1988) and ''[[Loveless (My Bloody Valentine album)|Loveless]]'' (1991). Writing for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', [[Paul Lester]] said Shields is \"widely accepted as shoegazing's genius\", with \"his astonishing wall of sound, use of the studio as instrument and dazzling reinvention of the guitar making him a sort of hydra-headed Spector-[[Jimi Hendrix|Hendrix]]-Eno figure\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lester|first1=Paul|author-link=Paul Lester|title=Sonic Cathedral spark shoegazing music revival|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article6066716.ece|website=[[The Times|Times Online]]|date=April 12, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919185133/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article6066716.ece|archive-date=September 19, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Record production}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[Acousmatic music]]\n* [[Art pop]]\n* [[Click track]]\n* [[Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center]]\n* [[Electroacoustic music]]\n* [[Experimental pop]]\n* [[Groupe de Recherches Musicales]]\n* [[Lo-fi music|Lo-fi/DIY music]]\n* [[Post-punk]]\n* [[Psychedelic music]]\n* [[Recording consciousness]]\n* [[Recording practices of the Beatles]]\n* ''[[Soundbreaking]]'' documentary series\n* [[Xenochrony]]\n* [[Studio di fonologia musicale di Radio Milano]]\n* [[Studio for Electronic Music (WDR)]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb|30em}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Ashby|editor-first=Arved Mark|title=The Pleasure of Modernist Music: Listening, Meaning, Intention, Ideology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pit6yL_Few4C|year=2004|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-1-58046-143-6}}\n* {{cite book|first=Matthew|last=Bannister|title=White Boys, White Noise: Masculinities and 1980s Indie Guitar Rock|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ckLKGTXRwQC&pg=PA38|year=2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-8803-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Bell|first=Adam Patrick|title=Dawn of the DAW: The Studio As Musical Instrument|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZD9FDwAAQBAJ|year=2018|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-029660-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Brend|first=Mark|title=Strange Sounds: Offbeat Instruments and Sonic Experiments in Pop|publisher=Backbeat Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2005|isbn=978-0-879308551|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cogan|first1=Jim|last2=Clark|first2=William|title=Temples of Sound: Inside the Great Recording Studios|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hO-KQ4o_B2MC|year=2003|publisher=Chronicle Books|isbn=978-0-8118-3394-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Francis |authorlink=Francis Davis |year=2004 |title=Jazz and Its Discontents: A Francis Davis Reader |publisher=Da Capo |isbn=0-306-81055-7 |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=QVr_AgAAQBAJ}} |ref={{SfnRef|Davis|2004}}}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Eno|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Eno|editor-last1=Cox|editor-first1=Christoph|editor-last2=Warner|editor-first2=Daniel|title=Audio Culture: Readings in Modern Music|chapter=The Studio as Compositional Tool|chapter-url=http://golancourses.net/2009ems1/pdf/sound_eno-the-studio-as-a-compositional-tool.pdf|year=2004|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-0-8264-1615-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Gillett|first=Charlie|authorlink=Charlie Gillett|title=The Sound of the City: The Rise of Rock and Roll|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzmhhXUwyt4C&pg=PA329|year=1984|publisher=Perseus Books Group|isbn=978-0-306-80683-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Greene|first=Doyle|title=Rock, Counterculture and the Avant-Garde, 1966\u20131970: How the Beatles, Frank Zappa and the Velvet Underground Defined an Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ELeaCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-2403-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hannan|first=Michael |year=2008|chapter= The sound design of ''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band''|title= Sgt. Pepper and the Beatles: It Was Forty Years Ago Today|editor-last=Julien |editor-first=Olivier|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-0-7546-6708-7|ref=harv|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=vZ-SB57WBo8C}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hodgson|first=Jay|year=2010|title=Understanding Records: A Field Guide to Recording Practice|publisher=Continuum|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-1-4411-5607-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Howard|first=David N.|year=2004|title=Sonic Alchemy: Visionary Music Producers and Their Maverick Recordings |publisher=Hal Leonard |location=Milwaukee, WI|isbn=0-634-05560-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Julien|first=Oliver |year=2008|chapter= 'A lucky man who made the grade': ''Sgt. Pepper'' and the rise of a phonographic tradition in twentieth-century popular music |title= Sgt. Pepper and the Beatles: It Was Forty Years Ago Today|editor-last=Julien |editor-first=Olivier|location=|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-0-7546-6708-7|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=vZ-SB57WBo8C}}|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Martin|first=Bill|title=Avant Rock: Experimental Music from the Beatles to Bjork|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CCLyCgAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=Open Court Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-8126-9939-5}}\n* {{cite book|last=Millard|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Beatlemania: Technology, Business, and Teen Culture in Cold War America|year=2012|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore, MD|isbn=978-1-4214-0525-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moorefield |first=Virgil |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Producer_as_Composer.html?id=PZ0R4_Oxr-4C&pg=PA18|title=The Producer as Composer: Shaping the Sounds of Popular Music|publisher=MIT Press |date=2010 |isbn=0-262-13457-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ribowsky|first=Mark|title=He's a Rebel|url=https://archive.org/details/hesrebel00ribo|url-access=registration|year=1989|publisher=Dutton|isbn=978-0-525-24727-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Toop|first=David|author-link=David Toop|title=Ocean of Sound: Ambient Sound and Radical Listening in the Age of Communication|year=2018|orig-year=First published 1995|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]]|isbn=978-1-78816-030-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zak|first=Albin|title=Poetics of Rock: Cutting Tracks, Making Records|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DJM6FgvlWw0C|year=2001|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92815-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|last=Eller|first=Dylan|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/03/28/revisiting-brian-enos-the-studio-as-a-compositional-tool/|title=Revisiting Brian Eno\u2019s \u2018The Studio as a Compositional Tool\u2019|date=March 28, 2016|website=[[TechCrunch]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schmidt Horning|first=Susan|year=2016 |orig-year=1st pub. 2012 by Ashgate|chapter=The Sounds of Space: Studio as Instrument in the Era of High Fidelity |title=The Art of Record Production: An Introductory Reader for a New Academic Field |editor1-last=Frith |editor1-first=Simon |editor1-link=Simon Frith |editor2-last=Zagorski-Thomas |editor2-first=Simon |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-4094-0562-7}}\n\n{{Music production}}\n[[Category:Recording studios| ]]\n[[Category:Musical instruments| Recording studio]]\n[[Category:Electronic music| ]]\n[[Category:Popular music]]\n[[Category:New media]]\n[[Category:20th century in music]]\n[[Category:21st century in music]]\n[[Category:Audio engineering]]\n", "name_user": "Bumm13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1950s\u20131960s:formatting fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recording_studio_as_an_instrument"}
{"title_page": "Alan Winde", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Alan Winde\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image               = Alan Winde.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Winde in 2018\n| office              = 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]\n| status              = \n| premier             = \n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Helen Zille]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]\n| premier1            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1         = 1 November 2018\n| term_end1           = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Dan Plato]]\n| successor1          = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office2             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]\n| premier2            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2         = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2           = 1 November 2018\n| alongside2          = \n| constituency2       = \n| predecessor2        = ''Position established''\n| successor2          = [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] \n| majority2           = \n| prior_term2         =\n| office3             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]\n| premier3            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2009\n| term_end3           = 26 May 2014\n| alongside3          = \n| constituency3       = \n| predecessor3        = Garth Strachan\n| successor3          = ''Position dissolved''\n| majority3           = \n| prior_term3         =\n| office4            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start4        = 15 June 1999\n| birthname          = Alan Richard Winde\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knysna]], [[Cape Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = [[South Africa]]n\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (1999\u20132000) <br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (Before 1999)\n| spouse             = Tracy Winde (m. 1993)\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = [[Knysna]]<br />[[Cape Town]]\n| education          = Knysna High School\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician<br />Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Alan Richard Winde''' (born 18 March 1965) is a South African politician and previous businessman.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', Western Cape, 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 30 September 2018.</ref> He is currently serving as the 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]] since his election in 2019, and a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since 1999. He previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]], the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]] and the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]. Winde is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).\n\nBorn in [[Knysna]], Winde attended Knysna High School. He has experience as a businessman and entrepreneur since he established several businesses. He also worked for and managed numerous companies. He started his political career as a municipal and district councillor in the early 1990s. Shortly afterwards in 1999, he was elected to the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He has held various leadership positions in the Democratic Alliance provincial parliament caucus. Winde was appointed [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]] in May 2009 and served until May 2014, when he assumed the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet], ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref><ref>Williams, Murray. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Democratic Alliance selected Winde to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-named-da-candidate-to-take-over-from-helen-zille-as-premier/ Alan Winde named DA candidate to take over from Helen Zille as premier], ''TimesLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref> In October 2018, Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Winde to the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]. He took office on 1 November 2018.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the Democratic Alliance retained their majority in the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]], but with a decrease in the number of seats.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-10-democratic-alliance-officially-wins-the-western-cape-vote/ It's official: The Democratic Alliance has won the Western Cape], ''TimesLIVE'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> Winde was elected Premier on 22 May 2019 and succeeded Helen Zille. He is the second Western Cape Premier from the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Roux |first1=Nckey |title=Winde formally elected as Premier on 22 May |url=https://www.georgeherald.com/News/Article/Elections-2019/premier-elect-inaugurated-on-22-may-201905131129 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=George Herald |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and business career==\n===Family and personal life===\nWinde was born on 18 March 1965 in the town of [[Knysna]]. He attended and matriculated from Knysna High School. He married Tracy Winde in 1993. They have two children named Lauren and Jason.<ref name = \"onesaforall\">[https://www.onesouthafricaforall.co.za/ Alan Winde], ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde's father, William Dave Winde, died on 1 August 2019.<ref>(In Afrikaans) [https://www.son.co.za/Nuus/Suid-Kaap/premier-se-pa-oorlede-20190801 Winde se pa oorlede], ''Son Digitaal'', 1 August 2019. Retrieved on 1 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===Business career===\nWinde has experience as an entrepreneur. He established and managed many small businesses. He was also a director of a tour company and a business broker with Aldes Business Brokers.<ref name=\"onesaforall\" />\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Minister Alan Winde (cropped).jpg|x200px|thumb|left|Winde as Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism in 2013]]\nWinde ran as an independent candidate and was elected to the South Cape District Council in 1996. He had previously served as a councillor for the Outeniqua Rural Council. Shortly after being elected a district councillor, the [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] recruited him to be a candidate for the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He was elected in the [[1999 South African general election|general election of 1999]].<ref name =\"bizzabo\">[https://events.bizzabo.com/u-start-conference-africa/agenda/speakers/89264 Alan Winde - Bizzabo], ''U-Start Conference Africa''. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe took office as a Member on 15 June 2009. During his first term, he served as Western Cape Provincial Finance Chairman and a Member of the Executive Committee. He returned to the Provincial Parliament following the 2004 general election. Briefly, before being re-elected in 2009, he served as Chief Whip of the Official Opposition, Party Spokesperson on Environment and Planning and Deputy Party Spokesperson on Economic Development and Tourism.<ref name=\"bizzabo\" />\n\nPremier Helen Zille appointed Winde to the position of Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism following his re-election in May 2009. Constitutional Court Judge [[Yvonne Mokgoro]] swore him in as Provincial Minister on 7 May 2009. He consequently succeeded Garth Strachan.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/appointment-western-cape-provincial-cabinet Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 7 May 2009. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the 2014 elections, Premier Helen Zille announced that Winde would now hold the title of Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities and only lead the Provincial Departments of Agriculture, Economic Development and Tourism. The Provincial Finance Department would be an independent department with its own Provincial Minister. Western Cape Deputy Judge President Jeanette Traverso swore him in on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Winde was selected by the DA's Federal Executive to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate for the 2019 provincial election.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-da-names-alan-winde-western-cape-premier-candidate WATCH: DA names Alan Winde as Western Cape Premier candidate], ''eNCA'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPremier Helen Zille announced in October 2018 that Winde would move to the Provincial Community Safety Department as incumbent Provincial Minister [[Dan Plato]] had announced his intention to resign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thaw |first1=Regan |title=Alan Winde to take over WC Community Safety portfolio |url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=19 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |archivedate=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alan Winde replacing Dan Plato as community safety MEC |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/alan-winde-replacing-dan-plato-as-community-safety-mec-17553379 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> Winde was succeeded by [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] on 1 November 2018. He subsequently assumed the post of Provincial Minister of Community Safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Economic Development on swearing in of MEC Beverley Sch\u00e4fer |url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/western-cape-economic-development-swearing-mec-beverley-sch%C3%A4fer-1-nov-2018-0000 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=South African Government |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nWinde has served as acting Premier of the Western Cape on various brief occasions.<ref>[https://twitter.com/alanwinde/status/1092696090162446337 Alan Winde on Twitter: \"I have just been sworn in as Acting Premier. I agreed with the Judge not to invade any neighboring country.\"]. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He represented the provincial government at the [[State of the Nation Address (South Africa)|February 2019 State of the Nation Address]], as [[Helen Zille]] was in [[Germany]].<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sona-2019-from-thuma-mina-to-new-dawn-fades-as-bosasa-casts-a-shadow-20190208 SONA 2019: From 'Thuma Mina' to 'New Dawn Fades' as Bosasa casts a shadow], News24, 8 February 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n== Premier of the Western Cape (2019\u2013present)==\n===Campaign===\n{{see also|2019 Western Cape provincial election}}\n[[File:Alan Winde For Premier Campaign Bus 2019 (cropped).jpg|270px|thumb|Alan Winde for Premier campaign bus, which was unveiled in April 2019.]]\nWinde emerged as the front-runner quite early on in the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=Who wants to be the Western Cape's next |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/who-wants-to-be-the-western-capes-next-premier-15527764 |accessdate=28 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, Democratic Alliance Federal Leader, [[Mmusi Maimane]], announced Winde as the party's Western Cape Premier candidate to succeed Premier [[Helen Zille]] after the 2019 elections. Winde defeated prominent candidates such as the Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape, [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]], and Member of Parliament [[David Maynier]]. After the announcement, Madikizela endorsed Winde and offered his full support to Winde's campaign.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', [[Western Cape]], 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Dentlinger, Lindsay. [https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/featured/da-wc-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-backs-alan-winde-as-premier-candidate/ar-BBNA1TB DA WC leader Bonginkosi Madikizela backs Alan Winde as premier candidate], ''MSN'', 20 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance launched their campaign to retain the Western Cape after the 2019 elections at the [[Cape Town Stadium]] on 29 September 2018. At the event, Mmusi Maimane highlighted the party's achievements while governing the province, such as the province's low unemployment rate and that the party had turned the previously struggling Provincial Education Department into one of the best functioning departments in South Africa.<ref>Isaacs, Lauren. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/30/da-determined-to-retain-western-cape-in-2019-elections DA determined to retain Western Cape in 2019 elections],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/unity-the-rallying-call-for-western-cape-da-as-it-launches-its-election-campaign-20180929 Unity the rallying call for Western Cape DA, as it launches its election campaign], ''News24'', 29 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter he was announced as the premier candidate, Winde embarked on a listening tour and travelled to various communities in the [[Western Cape]].<ref>[https://pr.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-DA-Western-Cape-Premier-Candidate-Winde-takes-Listening-Tour-to-George-8001073 #WindeForPremier: DA Western Cape Premier Candidate Winde takes Listening Tour to George], ''African News Agency'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nHe also campaigned for local DA candidates in by-elections. For instance, he went to the community of De Doorns to campaign for a DA candidate in a hotly-contested by-election. The DA candidate, Luwellyn Willemse, retained ward 3 of the [[Breede Valley Local Municipality|Breede Valley municipality]] by earning a total of 1,101 votes (52.16%).<ref>{{cite news |title=DA retains ward in Breede Valley municipal by-election |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2027939/da-retains-ward-in-breede-valley-municipal-by-election/ |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-Alan-Winde-to-address-supporters-at-De-Doorns-final-rally-ahead-of-by-election-7777913 #WindeForPremier: Alan Winde to address supporters at De Doorns final rally ahead of by-election], ''African News Agency''. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde launched the Democratic Alliance's 2019 provincial voter registration campaign on 4 January 2019. Winde and other Democratic Alliance members erected party registration posters in [[Mitchells Plain]], ahead of the Independent Electoral Commission's registration weekend on 26 and 27 January 2019.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-winde-launches-das-campaign-voter-registration-plan-criticised-18686993 WATCH: Winde launches DA's campaign, voter registration plan criticised], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 5 August 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance held its provincial Plan of Action Rally on 2 March 2019 at the [[Bellville Velodrome]] and launched their provincial party manifesto. Winde and various other DA politicians addressed thousands of party supporters. Winde assured that he would take on the national government for the Western Cape to receive its own, decentralised [[Rail transport in South Africa|rail]] and [[South African Police Service|police service]]. He pledged to increase the availability of [[Housing voucher|housing vouchers]] and vowed to spend [[Taxation in South Africa|tax money]] properly.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/da-comes-out-guns-blazing-to-retain-control-of-wc DA comes out guns blazing to retain control of WC], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref><ref>Payne, Sune. [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-03-04-da-punts-control-of-rail-and-policing-in-western-cape-as-party-launches-provincial-manifesto/ DA punts control of rail and policing in Western Cape as party launches provincial manifesto], ''The Daily Maverick'', 4 March 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref><ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/maimane-unemployment-will-continue-to-rise-the-longer-anc-stays-in-power Maimane: Unemployment will continue to rise the longer ANC stays in power],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde vowed on 11 March 2019 to build a police station in the gang-riddled community of [[Bonteheuwel]] due to the large number of murders that occur in the suburb.<ref>Mortlock, Monique.  \n[https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/11/winde-promises-to-a-police-station-in-bonteheuwel-if-da-wins-elections Winde promises to build police station in Bonteheuwel if DA wins elections], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde participated in the first [[eNCA]] Town Hall Debate, hosted at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]] on 14 March 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-emotions-run-high-encas-town-hall-debate WATCH: Emotions run high at eNCA's Town Hall Debate], ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref> The debate included many senior Western Cape politicians, such as former African National Congress Premier, [[Ebrahim Rasool]], Economic Freedom Fighters City of Cape Town councillor, [[Melikhaya Xego]], Good Party Leader, [[Patricia de Lille]], and Freedom Front Plus Western Cape Premier candidate, [[Peter Marais]].<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/senior-politicians-trade-barbs-campaign-at-enca-townhall-debate-in-the-capes-mitchells-plain-20190314 Senior politicians trade barbs, campaign at eNCA townhall debate in the Cape's Mitchells Plain], ''News24'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/live-video-cape-town-pre-election-town-hall-meetings WATCH: eNCA Town Hall Debate - Cape Town], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019.  Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and [[Mmusi Maimane]] revealed the Democratic Alliance's alternative energy plan for the Western Cape on 27 March 2019, in which the province acquires electricity directly from Independent Power Producers (IPPs).<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-maimane-winde-reveal-das-alternative-energy-plan-20115500 WATCH: Maimane, Winde reveal DA's alternative energy plan], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 27 March 2019. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance retained control of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, but with a decrease in the number of seats, on 8 May 2019.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/elections/2128368/live-da-secures-majority-again-in-western-cape-election-results/ LIVE: DA secures majority again in Western Cape election results], ''The Citizen'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> The party celebrated their election win in the province on 16 May 2019.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/campaigning-a-reality-check-das-winde-admits-as-he-thanks-the-western-cape-20190516 Campaigning a 'reality check', DA's Winde admits as he thanks the Western Cape], ''News24'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved on 18 May 2019.</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWinde was elected Premier of the Western Cape on 22 May 2019 during the first sitting of the Sixth Provincial Parliament. He received 24 out of the 34 valid votes. Six ballots were spoilt, and there were two abstentions. His main challenger for the post was [[Cameron Dugmore]] of the [[African National Congress]], who received only 10 out of the 34 valid votes.<ref>Lee, Samantha. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/breaking-winde-sworn-in-as-western-cape-premier-20190522 Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''News24'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>Mortlock, Monique. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/da-s-winde-elected-as-new-wc-premier DA's Winde elected as new WC premier], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2133822/winde-elected-western-cape-premier/ Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''The Citizen'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde announced the formation of his Provincial Cabinet on 23 May 2019. He retained four ministers in their existing portfolios, while he moved three to other portfolios and appointed three new members. He appointed former DA Member of Parliament and premier candidate contender, [[David Maynier]], to the post of Provincial Minister of Finance and Economic Opportunities, while he moved [[Albert Fritz]] and [[Ivan Meyer]] to the posts of Provincial Minister of Community Safety and Provincial Minister of Agriculture, respectively. Winde also said that all the newly-appointed cabinet members would undergo lifestyle audits.<ref name=\"provincial cabinet\">\n*Sicetsha, Andile. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/western-cape-premier-alan-winde-new-cabinet/ Western Cape Premier Alan Winde announces new Cabinet], ''The South African'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 9 September 2019.\n*Meyer, Dan. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new], ''TimesLIVE'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.\n*[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-names-western-cape-cabinet-20190523 Winde names new Western Cape cabinet], ''News24'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Nkanjeni, Unathi. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-24-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-western-cape-provincial-cabinet/ What you need to know about the Western Cape provincial cabinet], ''TimesLIVE'', 24 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Kiewit, Lester. [https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-23-windes-cabinet-to-undergo-lifestyle-audits Winde\u2019s cabinet to undergo lifestyle audits], ''Mail & Guardian'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde confirmed on 3 June 2019 that a provincial children's commissioner would be appointed before the end of 2019 or in early 2020. He added that the commissioner would have the authority to monitor, investigate, research, lobby and educate on issues, policy, services and legislation that affect children.<ref>Kahla, Cheryl. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/child-protection-week-western-cape-to-childrens-commissioner-2019/ Child Protection Week: Western Cape to appoint children\u2019s commissioner], ''The South African'', 3 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref><ref>Petersen, Tammy. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/child-murder-capital-to-introduce-first-childrens-commissioner-20190610 Child murder capital to introduce first Children\u2019s Commissioner], ''News24'', 10 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref> In March 2020, the provincial parliament recommended rights activist Christina Nomdo for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tembo |first1=Theolin |title=Legislature paves way to appoint Christina Nomdo as Western Cape Commissioner of Children |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/legislature-paves-way-to-appoint-christina-nomdo-as-western-cape-commissioner-of-children-45202798 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 March 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nNational Police Minister [[Bheki Cele]] announced on 11 July 2019, that the [[South African National Defence Force]] (SANDF) would be deployed in the gang-ridden areas of [[Cape Town]]. Winde welcomed the deployment of SANDF. His predecessor, [[Helen Zille]], had repeatedly asked for the deployment of SANDF during her tenure. The deployment came into effect on 18 July 2019 and was set to end on 16 September 2019. However, Winde wrote to President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] and Defence Minister [[Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula]] in mid-September 2019 to request that the SANDF deployment in [[Cape Town]] be extended.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sandfs-deployment-to-cape-flats-cabinet-to-assess-situation-after-premier-winde-calls-for-an-extension-20190910 SANDF's deployment to Cape Flats: Cabinet to 'assess situation' after Premier Winde calls for an extension], ''News24'', 10 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> Winde reasoned that an extension of the army is required to bring stability to the communities.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/still-a-massive-hill-to-climb-windes-reasons-for-wanting-army-to-stay-extra-6-months-20190911 'Still a massive hill to climb' - Winde's reasons for wanting army to stay extra 6 months], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The cabinet granted the request and it ended in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-fritz-welcome-sandfs-extended-stay-but-want-to-see-a-few-changes-20190916 Winde, Fritz welcome SANDF's extended stay, but want to see a few changes], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-sandfs-deployment-in-western-cape-extended-to-march-2020-20190916 SANDF's deployment in Western Cape extended to March 2020], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde delivered his maiden [[State of the Province Address (South Africa)|State of the Province Address]] on 18 July 2019, in which he highlighted the provincial government's achievements and outlined his agenda.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/07/18/job-creation-gangs-likely-to-feature-in-premier-winde-s-sopa Job creation, gangs likely to feature in Premier Winde's Sopa], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 17 August 2019.</ref> Also in the speech, Winde placed emphasis on the [[Crime in South Africa|provincial crime and misconduct statistics]] and claimed that the police \"had lost the war on crime\" because of [[South African Police Service#Criticism and controversies|mismanagement]].<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2156487/police-have-lost-the-war-on-crime-in-the-western-cape-says-winde/ Police have lost the war on crime in the Western Cape, says Winde], ''The Citizen'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-govt-mulling-court-action-over-control-of-saps-in-province-20190718 Western Cape govt mulling court action over control of SAPS in province], ''News24'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2019, he appointed Harry Malila as the new Director-General of the Western Cape Provincial Government. Malila succeeded long-serving Brent Gerber.<ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Harry Malila appointed as Western Cape director-general |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-harry-malila-appointed-as-western-cape-director-general-35615157 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=22 October 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020, Winde delivered his second State of the Province Address at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]]. It was the first time that the SOPA was held outside of the Provincial Parliament's chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gitahu |first1=Mwangi |title=Focus on Western Cape Sopa at Mitchells Plain centre |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/focus-on-western-cape-sopa-at-mitchells-plain-centre-43010777 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Winde urged residents to restrict the infection rate of the virus and said in a statement: \"This rate of transmission is concerning. As the premier of this province, it pains me to implement restrictions on our citizens, especially as they affect the economy and children. But I am willing to take these steps to keep as many of our citizens COVID-19 free.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=Coronavirus: Let's stop the spread, says Alan Winde as Western Cape's number of cases reach 30 |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-lets-stop-the-spread-says-alan-winde-as-western-capes-number-of-cases-reach-30-20200318 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Western Cape Government update on Coronavirus - 18 March |url=https://www.westerncape.gov.za/department-of-health/news/western-cape-government-update-coronavirus-18-march |website=westerncape.gov.za |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> As of March 2020, the Western Cape has the second-most cases in South Africa.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cape Town worst hit as Covid-19 cases near 500 in Western Cape |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-07-cape-town-worst-hit-as-covid-19-cases-near-500-in-western-cape/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Once a [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa#National_lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] in late-March was implemented, Winde advised residents to avoid travelling and rather stay at home.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nombembe |first1=Philani |title=Western Cape premier Alan Winde urges public to adhere to government's lockdown directive |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-28-western-cape-premier-alan-winde-urges-public-to-adhere-to-governments-lockdown-directive/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The Western Cape Health Department has also prepared sites across the province to be used as quarantine facilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC still preparing sites to be used as COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/31/wc-still-preparing-sites-to-be-used-as-covid-19-quarantine-areas |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=31 March 2020 |location=Johannesburg}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and record==\n===Immigration===\nWinde had been critical of controversial immigration regulations introduced by the national government, which he alleged had harmed tourism growth in the Western Cape. In response, he organised petitions against the regulations.<ref>[https://www.nwivisas.com/nwi-blog/south-africa/mec-alan-winde-plans-to-petition-visa-regulations/ MEC Alan Winde plans to petition visa regulations], ''nwvisas''. Retrieved on 7 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.vocfm.co.za/regulations-detrimental-to-economy-winde/ Regulations detrimental to economy: Winde], ''Voice of the Cape'', 3 September 2014. Retrieved on 3 July 2019.</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nProvincial government officials visited clothing factories in the Cape Town area on 11 June 2012. Winde investigated a local government leadership programme. The specific programme aimed to give the unemployed youth work experience.<ref>Adams, Nathan. [https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/11/Winde-visits-clothing-factories Winde visits clothing factories], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 June 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde approached the [[Development Bank of South Africa]] on 31 July 2012 to secure funding for the provincial government's work and skill programme. The programme has been active since 2009. Winde announced that if the provincial government could acquire additional funding, an extra 600 young people would be able to benefit from this project.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2012/07/31/WC-Skills-programme-needs-funding WC skills programme needs funding], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 July 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe visited small businesses in the Cape Town CBD on 15 January 2013. He called on the businesses to enter the province's Entrepreneurship Recognition Awards.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/01/15/Winde-promotes-Entrepreneurship-Awards Winde promotes Entrepreneurship Awards], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 15 January 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Western Cape Economic Development Department launched an artisan development programme on 20 August 2013 to train more artisans. Winde said that his department would be putting special focus on crucial industries in the province.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/08/20/Qualified-artisans-have-become-scarce 'Qualified artisans are scarce'], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 August 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Premier Helen Zille led a delegation to China in November 2015 in a bid to secure increased trade and investment opportunities. A report from 2013 estimated that the province's exports to China were valued at over [[South African rand|R]]2 billion (US$131.8 million).<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/11/13/Zille-Winde-lead-delegation-to-China Zille, Winde to lead delegation to China], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 13 November 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe said on 10 October 2018 that youth unemployment should be the main focus of the national job and employment summit, hosted by the [[Government of South Africa|national government]]. The Provincial Department of Economic Development has initiated many employment projects aiming to employ the unemployed youth.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/04/job-summit-can-t-be-allowed-to-become-another-talk-shop Youth unemployment must be key focus of job summit - Alan Winde], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 4 October 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde has been commended for creating a business-friendly environment in the Western Cape since the provincial economy has performed better than the national growth rate.<ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> The Western Cape currently has a lower unemployment rate compared to the national average. Democratic Alliance Federal Leader [[Mmusi Maimane]] called Winde the \"premier of jobs\", when he announced him as the party's candidate.<ref>Mpahlele, Mary Jane. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-premier-candidate-alan-winde-to-focus-on-job-creation-housing-17144485 DA Premier candidate Alan Winde to focus on job creation, housing], ''IOL'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He has received acknowledgement for his economic policies from senior opposition politicians. Deputy President of South Africa and senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] figure [[David Mabuza]] said in September 2019 that the provincial government's economic proposals should be implemented in other ANC-run provinces.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-11-da-premier-alan-winde-gets-surprise-endorsement-from-david-mabuza/ DA premier Alan Winde gets surprise endorsement from David Mabuza], ''TimesLIVE'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019</ref><ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/mabuza-praises-winde-as-a-good-selection-says-plans-are-afoot-to-settle-people-in-the-western-cape-20190911 Mabuza praises Winde as a 'good selection', says plans are afoot to settle people in the Western Cape], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political infighting and corruption===\nDemocratic Alliance party insiders have described Winde as someone who is not involved in party infighting and prioritised on completing his work.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. \n [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 7 April 2019. \"Winde is largely seen within the party as someone who is focused on his job and does not get involved in political infighting.\"</ref>\n\nDuring his premiership, Winde has strongly opposed corruption. He made it mandatory for his provincial ministers to undergo lifestyle audits. He announced in August 2019 that he would probe all the corruption allegations made against his provincial ministers. He made this announcement after the official opposition [[African National Congress]] had called for an investigation into alleged misconduct by the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Winde vows to probe all corruption allegation against MECs |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/30/winde-vows-to-probe-all-corruption-allegation-against-mecs | newspaper=EWN|accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nFollowing Winde's deployment to the Community Safety Department in November 2018, he announced that revised technology would be used to prevent and reduce crime. In the same month, he met with Hanover Park Peace Ambassador, Riedwaan Samuels, who was shot four times in the leg. Winde praised all the young peace ambassadors who were standing up against gang violence and fighting for their communities to be safer. He also met with Western Cape Police Commissioner, Khombinkosi Jula, and discussed that the addition of new police officers would help with the police under-resourcing in the Western Cape.<ref>Maliti, Soyiso. [https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/news/windes-plan-to-fight-crime-using-tech-17759673 Winde's plan to fight crime using tech], ''IOL'', 3 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Mlamla, Sisonke. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/pics-praise-for-hanover-park-peace-ambassador-who-was-shot-17791173 PICS: Praise for Hanover Park Peace Ambassador who was shot], ''IOL'', 6 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/11/09/wc-police-service-boosted-by-addition-of-1-000-new-recruits WC police service boosted by addition of 1,000 new recruits], ''EWN'', 9 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Winde called for the establishment of a provincial police force. In mid-December, [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] farmers requested that the Provincial Community Safety Department allocate more police officers to the area. In response, the Provincial Community Safety Department wrote a letter to the Western Cape Police Commissioner.<ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-wants-provincial-police-force-for-western-cape-20181213 Winde wants provincial police force for Western Cape], ''News24'', 13 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/12/18/philippi-urge-mec-alan-winde-to-urgently-allocate-them-more-police Philippi farmers urge MEC Winde to urgently allocate them more police], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government formally declared an inter-governmental dispute with National Minister of Police [[Bheki Cele]] on 29 April 2019 over police resources allocated to the province.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-04-28-western-cape-government-declares-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-policing/ Western Cape government declares dispute with Bheki Cele over policing], ''TimesLIVE'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/crime/2123896/western-cape-government-declares-formal-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-police-resourcing-da/ Western Cape government declares formal dispute with Bheki Cele over police resourcing \u2013 DA], ''TheCitizen'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref>\n\nSANDF was deployed to the areas of [[Cape Town]] affected by high levels of crime and gang violence in July 2019. Winde welcomed the decision by the [[Department of Defence (South Africa)|National Department of Defence]] to assist the police in its efforts to reduce the city's crime statistics.<ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/go-in-arrest-those-gangsters-w-cape-premier-on-military-move-20190711 Go in, arrest those gangsters: W Cape premier on military move], ''News24'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref><ref>Mabuza, Ernest. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-11-police-minister-bheki-cele-deploys-army-to-crime-ridden-western-cape/ Police minister Bheki Cele deploys army to crime-ridden Western Cape], ''BusinessDay'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref> The deployment was extended in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/winde-welcomes-sandf-extension-but-wants-criminal-justice-system-fixed-33080728 Winde welcomes SANDF extension but wants criminal justice system fixed], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Provincial Minister of Community Safety [[Albert Fritz]] announced on 19 September 2019 that the provincial government would annually be investing R1 billion (US$67.3 million) for three years into the training and deployment of 3,000 safety officers and 150 investigators. A total of 500 safety officers were deployed in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC provincial police service set to be deployed in February |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/05/wc-provincial-police-service-set-to-be-deployed-in-february |accessdate=14 December 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=500 new law enforcement officers deployed to crime hot spots in Cape Town |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/500-new-law-enforcement-officers-deployed-to-crime-hot-spots-in-cape-town-20200210 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The safety plan aims to halve the province's crime statistics within the next decade. Fritz added that the provincial government would also establish an integrated violence prevention programme. The provincial ministers would also be assessed by key performance indicators (KPIs) related to the safety plan.<ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/windes-r1bn-safety-plan-3-000-new-law-enforcement-officers-150-investigators-20190919 Winde's R1bn safety plan: 3 000 new law enforcement officers, 150 investigators], ''News24'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>Buhle, Lindwa. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/premier-winde-announces-western-cape-most-expensive-safety-plan/ Western Cape\u2019s crime-fighting plan: R1-billion, 3000 new officers and more], ''The South African'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.702.co.za/articles/361338/winde-to-appoint-3000-new-officers-in-three-year-wc-safety-plan Winde to appoint 3000 new officers in three-year WC safety plan], ''www.702.co.za'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Agriculture and tourism===\nOne of his duties, as Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities, was to oversee the Tourism Department of the Western Cape Government. He was responsible for projects such as Project Khulisa, a project introduced by the provincial government to increase tourism growth and grow the South African economy. The project resulted in the Western Cape tourism sector growing extensively.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/09/01/WC-Govt-launch-economic-growth-plan WC govt launches economic growth plan], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 1 September 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced that it was investing more than R23 million (US$1.5 million) on increasing the province's agricultural exports and set a target of creating 100,000 jobs in the sector. Winde said that additional support would be given to emerging farmers.<ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/30/WC-govt-invests-over-R23m-on-increasing-agricultural-exports WC govt invests over R23m on increasing agricultural exports], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/31/WC-govt-to-create-more-than-100-thousand-jobs-in-agricultural-sector WC to create over 100,000 jobs in agricultural sector], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cape Town water crisis|drought]] that ravaged the Western Cape province from 2017 to 2018, he argued for farmers to keep hold of their private agricultural water supply, even if their local municipalities had a shortage of water.<ref>Head, Tom. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-alan-winde-western-cape-premier/ Breaking: Alan Winde revealed as the DA\u2019s choice for Western Cape premier], ''The South African'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nDuring a campaign visit to the West Coast region of the Western Cape province on 8 January 2019, Winde urged communities to protect infrastructure. He made this announcement after he witnessed fire-damaged municipal buildings in the town of [[Saldanha Bay]]. The buildings were set on fire during violent protests that occurred in 2018.<ref>Brandt, Kevin. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/01/08/da-wc-premier-candidate-winde-embarks-door-to-door-campaign Winde urges communities to protect infrastructure during door-to-door campaign], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 8 January 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nWinde called for the Western Cape to draw its electricity from natural resources and be independent of [[Eskom|Eskom's]] electricity supply in March 2019.<ref>Mokone, Thabo. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-03-02-da-wants-western-cape-off-eskom-grid/ DA wants Western Cape off Eskom grid], ''TimesLIVE'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref> He said that it is his ambition for the City of Cape Town to become the first city in South Africa to procure electricity from independent suppliers.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/20/alan-winde-says-eskom-crisis-will-cripple-sa-s-economy DA's Winde hopes CT can be the first to get power from independent suppliers], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[Eskom]] announced another round of [[2007\u20132019 South African energy crisis|power outages]]. Winde described the announcement as the \"last straw\" and called on Minister of Energy [[Gwede Mantashe]] to consider a proposal in which municipalities obtain electricity directly from IPPs.<ref>Mabuza, Ernst. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-10-17-alan-winde-asks-gwede-mantashe-to-allow-municipalities-to-procure-clean-energy/ Alan Winde asks Gwede Mantashe to allow municipalities to procure clean energy], ''TimesLIVE'', 17 October 2019. Retrieved on 17 October 2019.</ref> Mantashe, later on, agreed to discuss the matter.<ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-11-19-gwede-mantashe-opens-a-gap-will-discuss-independent-power-for-western-cape/ Gwede Mantashe opens a gap - will 'discuss' independent power for Western Cape], ''SowetanLIVE'', 19 November 2019. Retrieved on 6 December 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, President Ramaphosa announced in his State of the Nation Address that municipalities with an adequate financial standing would be allowed to purchase electricity from IPPs. Winde welcomed the decision and called for it to be expedited.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brandt |first1=Kevin |title=WC Premier Winde looking to quickly implement Ramaphosa's IPP announcement |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/02/14/wc-premier-winde-looking-to-quickly-implement-ramaphosa-s-ipp-announcement-1 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alan Winde}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/alan-winde/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/profile/mr-alan-winde Provincial Minister of Community Safety]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/97 Premier of the Western Cape: Overview]\n* [https://cfo.co.za/article/alan-winde Profile: Alan Winde] at CFO South Africa\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/alan-winde Alan Winde, Mr] at [[Government of South Africa]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Helen Zille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Plato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fritz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=''Position established''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Garth Strachan}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Position dissolved''}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{WCPremiers}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winde, Alan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from Knysna]]\n[[Category:South African businesspeople]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Premiers of the Western Cape]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Alan Winde\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image               = Alan Winde.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Winde in 2018\n| office              = 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]\n| status              = \n| premier             = \n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Helen Zille]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]\n| premier1            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1         = 1 November 2018\n| term_end1           = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Dan Plato]]\n| successor1          = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office2             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]\n| premier2            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2         = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2           = 1 November 2018\n| alongside2          = \n| constituency2       = \n| predecessor2        = ''Position established''\n| successor2          = [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] \n| majority2           = \n| prior_term2         =\n| office3             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]\n| premier3            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2009\n| term_end3           = 26 May 2014\n| alongside3          = \n| constituency3       = \n| predecessor3        = Garth Strachan\n| successor3          = ''Position dissolved''\n| majority3           = \n| prior_term3         =\n| office4            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start4        = 15 June 1999\n| birthname          = Alan Richard Winde\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knysna]], [[Cape Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = [[South Africa]]n\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (1999\u20132000) <br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (Before 1999)\n| spouse             = Tracy Winde (m. 1993)\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = [[Knysna]]<br />[[Cape Town]]\n| education          = Knysna High School\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician<br />Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Alan Richard Winde''' (born 18 March 1965) is a South African politician and previous businessman.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', Western Cape, 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 30 September 2018.</ref> He is currently serving as the 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]] since his election in 2019, and a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since 1999. He previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]], the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]] and the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]. Winde is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).\n\nBorn in [[Knysna]], Winde attended Knysna High School. He has experience as a businessman and entrepreneur since he established several businesses. He also worked for and managed numerous companies. He started his political career as a municipal and district councillor in the early 1990s. Shortly afterwards in 1999, he was elected to the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He has held various leadership positions in the Democratic Alliance provincial parliament caucus. Winde was appointed [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]] in May 2009 and served until May 2014, when he assumed the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet], ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref><ref>Williams, Murray. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Democratic Alliance selected Winde to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-named-da-candidate-to-take-over-from-helen-zille-as-premier/ Alan Winde named DA candidate to take over from Helen Zille as premier], ''TimesLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref> In October 2018, Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Winde to the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]. He took office on 1 November 2018.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the Democratic Alliance retained their majority in the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]], but with a decrease in the number of seats.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-10-democratic-alliance-officially-wins-the-western-cape-vote/ It's official: The Democratic Alliance has won the Western Cape], ''TimesLIVE'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> Winde was elected Premier on 22 May 2019 and succeeded Helen Zille. He is the second Western Cape Premier from the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Roux |first1=Nckey |title=Winde formally elected as Premier on 22 May |url=https://www.georgeherald.com/News/Article/Elections-2019/premier-elect-inaugurated-on-22-may-201905131129 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=George Herald |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and business career==\n===Family and personal life===\nWinde was born on 18 March 1965 in the town of [[Knysna]]. He attended and matriculated from Knysna High School. He married Tracy Winde in 1993. They have two children named Lauren and Jason.<ref name = \"onesaforall\">[https://www.onesouthafricaforall.co.za/ Alan Winde], ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde's father, William Dave Winde, died on 1 August 2019.<ref>(In Afrikaans) [https://www.son.co.za/Nuus/Suid-Kaap/premier-se-pa-oorlede-20190801 Winde se pa oorlede], ''Son Digitaal'', 1 August 2019. Retrieved on 1 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===Business career===\nWinde has experience as an entrepreneur. He established and managed many small businesses. He was also a director of a tour company and a business broker with Aldes Business Brokers.<ref name=\"onesaforall\" />\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Minister Alan Winde (cropped).jpg|x200px|thumb|left|Winde as Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism in 2013]]\nWinde ran as an independent candidate and was elected to the South Cape District Council in 1996. He had previously served as a councillor for the Outeniqua Rural Council. Shortly after being elected a district councillor, the [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] recruited him to be a candidate for the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He was elected in the [[1999 South African general election|general election of 1999]].<ref name =\"bizzabo\">[https://events.bizzabo.com/u-start-conference-africa/agenda/speakers/89264 Alan Winde - Bizzabo], ''U-Start Conference Africa''. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe took office as a Member on 15 June 2009. During his first term, he served as Western Cape Provincial Finance Chairman and a Member of the Executive Committee. He returned to the Provincial Parliament following the 2004 general election. Briefly, before being re-elected in 2009, he served as Chief Whip of the Official Opposition, Party Spokesperson on Environment and Planning and Deputy Party Spokesperson on Economic Development and Tourism.<ref name=\"bizzabo\" />\n\nPremier Helen Zille appointed Winde to the position of Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism following his re-election in May 2009. Constitutional Court Judge [[Yvonne Mokgoro]] swore him in as Provincial Minister on 7 May 2009. He consequently succeeded Garth Strachan.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/appointment-western-cape-provincial-cabinet Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 7 May 2009. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the 2014 elections, Premier Helen Zille announced that Winde would now hold the title of Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities and only lead the Provincial Departments of Agriculture, Economic Development and Tourism. The Provincial Finance Department would be an independent department with its own Provincial Minister. Western Cape Deputy Judge President Jeanette Traverso swore him in on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Winde was selected by the DA's Federal Executive to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate for the 2019 provincial election.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-da-names-alan-winde-western-cape-premier-candidate WATCH: DA names Alan Winde as Western Cape Premier candidate], ''eNCA'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPremier Helen Zille announced in October 2018 that Winde would move to the Provincial Community Safety Department as incumbent Provincial Minister [[Dan Plato]] had announced his intention to resign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thaw |first1=Regan |title=Alan Winde to take over WC Community Safety portfolio |url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=19 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |archivedate=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alan Winde replacing Dan Plato as community safety MEC |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/alan-winde-replacing-dan-plato-as-community-safety-mec-17553379 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> Winde was succeeded by [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] on 1 November 2018. He subsequently assumed the post of Provincial Minister of Community Safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Economic Development on swearing in of MEC Beverley Sch\u00e4fer |url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/western-cape-economic-development-swearing-mec-beverley-sch%C3%A4fer-1-nov-2018-0000 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=South African Government |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nWinde has served as acting Premier of the Western Cape on various brief occasions.<ref>[https://twitter.com/alanwinde/status/1092696090162446337 Alan Winde on Twitter: \"I have just been sworn in as Acting Premier. I agreed with the Judge not to invade any neighboring country.\"]. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He represented the provincial government at the [[State of the Nation Address (South Africa)|February 2019 State of the Nation Address]], as [[Helen Zille]] was in [[Germany]].<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sona-2019-from-thuma-mina-to-new-dawn-fades-as-bosasa-casts-a-shadow-20190208 SONA 2019: From 'Thuma Mina' to 'New Dawn Fades' as Bosasa casts a shadow], News24, 8 February 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n== Premier of the Western Cape (2019\u2013present)==\n===Campaign===\n{{see also|2019 Western Cape provincial election}}\n[[File:Alan Winde For Premier Campaign Bus 2019 (cropped).jpg|270px|thumb|Alan Winde for Premier campaign bus, which was unveiled in April 2019.]]\nWinde emerged as the front-runner quite early on in the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=Who wants to be the Western Cape's next |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/who-wants-to-be-the-western-capes-next-premier-15527764 |accessdate=28 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, Democratic Alliance Federal Leader, [[Mmusi Maimane]], announced Winde as the party's Western Cape Premier candidate to succeed Premier [[Helen Zille]] after the 2019 elections. Winde defeated prominent candidates such as the Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape, [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]], and Member of Parliament [[David Maynier]]. After the announcement, Madikizela endorsed Winde and offered his full support to Winde's campaign.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', [[Western Cape]], 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Dentlinger, Lindsay. [https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/featured/da-wc-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-backs-alan-winde-as-premier-candidate/ar-BBNA1TB DA WC leader Bonginkosi Madikizela backs Alan Winde as premier candidate], ''MSN'', 20 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance launched their campaign to retain the Western Cape after the 2019 elections at the [[Cape Town Stadium]] on 29 September 2018. At the event, Mmusi Maimane highlighted the party's achievements while governing the province, such as the province's low unemployment rate and that the party had turned the previously struggling Provincial Education Department into one of the best functioning departments in South Africa.<ref>Isaacs, Lauren. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/30/da-determined-to-retain-western-cape-in-2019-elections DA determined to retain Western Cape in 2019 elections],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/unity-the-rallying-call-for-western-cape-da-as-it-launches-its-election-campaign-20180929 Unity the rallying call for Western Cape DA, as it launches its election campaign], ''News24'', 29 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter he was announced as the premier candidate, Winde embarked on a listening tour and travelled to various communities in the [[Western Cape]].<ref>[https://pr.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-DA-Western-Cape-Premier-Candidate-Winde-takes-Listening-Tour-to-George-8001073 #WindeForPremier: DA Western Cape Premier Candidate Winde takes Listening Tour to George], ''African News Agency'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nHe also campaigned for local DA candidates in by-elections. For instance, he went to the community of De Doorns to campaign for a DA candidate in a hotly-contested by-election. The DA candidate, Luwellyn Willemse, retained ward 3 of the [[Breede Valley Local Municipality|Breede Valley municipality]] by earning a total of 1,101 votes (52.16%).<ref>{{cite news |title=DA retains ward in Breede Valley municipal by-election |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2027939/da-retains-ward-in-breede-valley-municipal-by-election/ |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-Alan-Winde-to-address-supporters-at-De-Doorns-final-rally-ahead-of-by-election-7777913 #WindeForPremier: Alan Winde to address supporters at De Doorns final rally ahead of by-election], ''African News Agency''. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde launched the Democratic Alliance's 2019 provincial voter registration campaign on 4 January 2019. Winde and other Democratic Alliance members erected party registration posters in [[Mitchells Plain]], ahead of the Independent Electoral Commission's registration weekend on 26 and 27 January 2019.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-winde-launches-das-campaign-voter-registration-plan-criticised-18686993 WATCH: Winde launches DA's campaign, voter registration plan criticised], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 5 August 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance held its provincial Plan of Action Rally on 2 March 2019 at the [[Bellville Velodrome]] and launched their provincial party manifesto. Winde and various other DA politicians addressed thousands of party supporters. Winde assured that he would take on the national government for the Western Cape to receive its own, decentralised [[Rail transport in South Africa|rail]] and [[South African Police Service|police service]]. He pledged to increase the availability of [[Housing voucher|housing vouchers]] and vowed to spend [[Taxation in South Africa|tax money]] properly.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/da-comes-out-guns-blazing-to-retain-control-of-wc DA comes out guns blazing to retain control of WC], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref><ref>Payne, Sune. [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-03-04-da-punts-control-of-rail-and-policing-in-western-cape-as-party-launches-provincial-manifesto/ DA punts control of rail and policing in Western Cape as party launches provincial manifesto], ''The Daily Maverick'', 4 March 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref><ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/maimane-unemployment-will-continue-to-rise-the-longer-anc-stays-in-power Maimane: Unemployment will continue to rise the longer ANC stays in power],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde vowed on 11 March 2019 to build a police station in the gang-riddled community of [[Bonteheuwel]] due to the large number of murders that occur in the suburb.<ref>Mortlock, Monique.  \n[https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/11/winde-promises-to-a-police-station-in-bonteheuwel-if-da-wins-elections Winde promises to build police station in Bonteheuwel if DA wins elections], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde participated in the first [[eNCA]] Town Hall Debate, hosted at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]] on 14 March 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-emotions-run-high-encas-town-hall-debate WATCH: Emotions run high at eNCA's Town Hall Debate], ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref> The debate included many senior Western Cape politicians, such as former African National Congress Premier, [[Ebrahim Rasool]], Economic Freedom Fighters City of Cape Town councillor, [[Melikhaya Xego]], Good Party Leader, [[Patricia de Lille]], and Freedom Front Plus Western Cape Premier candidate, [[Peter Marais]].<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/senior-politicians-trade-barbs-campaign-at-enca-townhall-debate-in-the-capes-mitchells-plain-20190314 Senior politicians trade barbs, campaign at eNCA townhall debate in the Cape's Mitchells Plain], ''News24'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/live-video-cape-town-pre-election-town-hall-meetings WATCH: eNCA Town Hall Debate - Cape Town], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019.  Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and [[Mmusi Maimane]] revealed the Democratic Alliance's alternative energy plan for the Western Cape on 27 March 2019, in which the province acquires electricity directly from Independent Power Producers (IPPs).<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-maimane-winde-reveal-das-alternative-energy-plan-20115500 WATCH: Maimane, Winde reveal DA's alternative energy plan], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 27 March 2019. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance retained control of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, but with a decrease in the number of seats, on 8 May 2019.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/elections/2128368/live-da-secures-majority-again-in-western-cape-election-results/ LIVE: DA secures majority again in Western Cape election results], ''The Citizen'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> The party celebrated their election win in the province on 16 May 2019.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/campaigning-a-reality-check-das-winde-admits-as-he-thanks-the-western-cape-20190516 Campaigning a 'reality check', DA's Winde admits as he thanks the Western Cape], ''News24'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved on 18 May 2019.</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWinde was elected Premier of the Western Cape on 22 May 2019 during the first sitting of the Sixth Provincial Parliament. He received 24 out of the 34 valid votes. Six ballots were spoilt, and there were two abstentions. His main challenger for the post was [[Cameron Dugmore]] of the [[African National Congress]], who received only 10 out of the 34 valid votes.<ref>Lee, Samantha. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/breaking-winde-sworn-in-as-western-cape-premier-20190522 Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''News24'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>Mortlock, Monique. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/da-s-winde-elected-as-new-wc-premier DA's Winde elected as new WC premier], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2133822/winde-elected-western-cape-premier/ Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''The Citizen'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde announced the formation of his Provincial Cabinet on 23 May 2019. He retained four ministers in their existing portfolios, while he moved three to other portfolios and appointed three new members. He appointed former DA Member of Parliament and premier candidate contender, [[David Maynier]], to the post of Provincial Minister of Finance and Economic Opportunities, while he moved [[Albert Fritz]] and [[Ivan Meyer]] to the posts of Provincial Minister of Community Safety and Provincial Minister of Agriculture, respectively. Winde also said that all the newly-appointed cabinet members would undergo lifestyle audits.<ref name=\"provincial cabinet\">\n*Sicetsha, Andile. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/western-cape-premier-alan-winde-new-cabinet/ Western Cape Premier Alan Winde announces new Cabinet], ''The South African'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 9 September 2019.\n*Meyer, Dan. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new], ''TimesLIVE'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.\n*[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-names-western-cape-cabinet-20190523 Winde names new Western Cape cabinet], ''News24'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Nkanjeni, Unathi. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-24-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-western-cape-provincial-cabinet/ What you need to know about the Western Cape provincial cabinet], ''TimesLIVE'', 24 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Kiewit, Lester. [https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-23-windes-cabinet-to-undergo-lifestyle-audits Winde\u2019s cabinet to undergo lifestyle audits], ''Mail & Guardian'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde confirmed on 3 June 2019 that a provincial children's commissioner would be appointed before the end of 2019 or in early 2020. He added that the commissioner would have the authority to monitor, investigate, research, lobby and educate on issues, policy, services and legislation that affect children.<ref>Kahla, Cheryl. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/child-protection-week-western-cape-to-childrens-commissioner-2019/ Child Protection Week: Western Cape to appoint children\u2019s commissioner], ''The South African'', 3 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref><ref>Petersen, Tammy. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/child-murder-capital-to-introduce-first-childrens-commissioner-20190610 Child murder capital to introduce first Children\u2019s Commissioner], ''News24'', 10 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref> In March 2020, the provincial parliament recommended rights activist Christina Nomdo for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tembo |first1=Theolin |title=Legislature paves way to appoint Christina Nomdo as Western Cape Commissioner of Children |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/legislature-paves-way-to-appoint-christina-nomdo-as-western-cape-commissioner-of-children-45202798 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 March 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nNational Police Minister [[Bheki Cele]] announced on 11 July 2019, that the [[South African National Defence Force]] (SANDF) would be deployed in the gang-ridden areas of [[Cape Town]]. Winde welcomed the deployment of SANDF. His predecessor, [[Helen Zille]], had repeatedly asked for the deployment of SANDF during her tenure. The deployment came into effect on 18 July 2019 and was set to end on 16 September 2019. However, Winde wrote to President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] and Defence Minister [[Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula]] in mid-September 2019 to request that the SANDF deployment in [[Cape Town]] be extended.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sandfs-deployment-to-cape-flats-cabinet-to-assess-situation-after-premier-winde-calls-for-an-extension-20190910 SANDF's deployment to Cape Flats: Cabinet to 'assess situation' after Premier Winde calls for an extension], ''News24'', 10 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> Winde reasoned that an extension of the army is required to bring stability to the communities.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/still-a-massive-hill-to-climb-windes-reasons-for-wanting-army-to-stay-extra-6-months-20190911 'Still a massive hill to climb' - Winde's reasons for wanting army to stay extra 6 months], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The cabinet granted the request and is now set to end in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-fritz-welcome-sandfs-extended-stay-but-want-to-see-a-few-changes-20190916 Winde, Fritz welcome SANDF's extended stay, but want to see a few changes], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-sandfs-deployment-in-western-cape-extended-to-march-2020-20190916 SANDF's deployment in Western Cape extended to March 2020], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde delivered his maiden [[State of the Province Address (South Africa)|State of the Province Address]] on 18 July 2019, in which he highlighted the provincial government's achievements and outlined his agenda.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/07/18/job-creation-gangs-likely-to-feature-in-premier-winde-s-sopa Job creation, gangs likely to feature in Premier Winde's Sopa], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 17 August 2019.</ref> Also in the speech, Winde placed emphasis on the [[Crime in South Africa|provincial crime and misconduct statistics]] and claimed that the police \"had lost the war on crime\" because of [[South African Police Service#Criticism and controversies|mismanagement]].<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2156487/police-have-lost-the-war-on-crime-in-the-western-cape-says-winde/ Police have lost the war on crime in the Western Cape, says Winde], ''The Citizen'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-govt-mulling-court-action-over-control-of-saps-in-province-20190718 Western Cape govt mulling court action over control of SAPS in province], ''News24'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2019, he appointed Harry Malila as the new Director-General of the Western Cape Provincial Government. Malila succeeded long-serving Brent Gerber.<ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Harry Malila appointed as Western Cape director-general |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-harry-malila-appointed-as-western-cape-director-general-35615157 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=22 October 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020, Winde delivered his second State of the Province Address at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]]. It was the first time that the SOPA was held outside of the Provincial Parliament's chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gitahu |first1=Mwangi |title=Focus on Western Cape Sopa at Mitchells Plain centre |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/focus-on-western-cape-sopa-at-mitchells-plain-centre-43010777 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Winde urged residents to restrict the infection rate of the virus and said in a statement: \"This rate of transmission is concerning. As the premier of this province, it pains me to implement restrictions on our citizens, especially as they affect the economy and children. But I am willing to take these steps to keep as many of our citizens COVID-19 free.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=Coronavirus: Let's stop the spread, says Alan Winde as Western Cape's number of cases reach 30 |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-lets-stop-the-spread-says-alan-winde-as-western-capes-number-of-cases-reach-30-20200318 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Western Cape Government update on Coronavirus - 18 March |url=https://www.westerncape.gov.za/department-of-health/news/western-cape-government-update-coronavirus-18-march |website=westerncape.gov.za |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> As of March 2020, the Western Cape has the second-most cases in South Africa.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cape Town worst hit as Covid-19 cases near 500 in Western Cape |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-07-cape-town-worst-hit-as-covid-19-cases-near-500-in-western-cape/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Once a [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa#National_lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] in late-March was implemented, Winde advised residents to avoid travelling and rather stay at home.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nombembe |first1=Philani |title=Western Cape premier Alan Winde urges public to adhere to government's lockdown directive |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-28-western-cape-premier-alan-winde-urges-public-to-adhere-to-governments-lockdown-directive/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The Western Cape Health Department has also prepared sites across the province to be used as quarantine facilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC still preparing sites to be used as COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/31/wc-still-preparing-sites-to-be-used-as-covid-19-quarantine-areas |accessdate=9 April 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=31 March 2020 |location=Johannesburg}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and record==\n===Immigration===\nWinde had been critical of controversial immigration regulations introduced by the national government, which he alleged had harmed tourism growth in the Western Cape. In response, he organised petitions against the regulations.<ref>[https://www.nwivisas.com/nwi-blog/south-africa/mec-alan-winde-plans-to-petition-visa-regulations/ MEC Alan Winde plans to petition visa regulations], ''nwvisas''. Retrieved on 7 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.vocfm.co.za/regulations-detrimental-to-economy-winde/ Regulations detrimental to economy: Winde], ''Voice of the Cape'', 3 September 2014. Retrieved on 3 July 2019.</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nProvincial government officials visited clothing factories in the Cape Town area on 11 June 2012. Winde investigated a local government leadership programme. The specific programme aimed to give the unemployed youth work experience.<ref>Adams, Nathan. [https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/11/Winde-visits-clothing-factories Winde visits clothing factories], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 June 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde approached the [[Development Bank of South Africa]] on 31 July 2012 to secure funding for the provincial government's work and skill programme. The programme has been active since 2009. Winde announced that if the provincial government could acquire additional funding, an extra 600 young people would be able to benefit from this project.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2012/07/31/WC-Skills-programme-needs-funding WC skills programme needs funding], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 July 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe visited small businesses in the Cape Town CBD on 15 January 2013. He called on the businesses to enter the province's Entrepreneurship Recognition Awards.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/01/15/Winde-promotes-Entrepreneurship-Awards Winde promotes Entrepreneurship Awards], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 15 January 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Western Cape Economic Development Department launched an artisan development programme on 20 August 2013 to train more artisans. Winde said that his department would be putting special focus on crucial industries in the province.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/08/20/Qualified-artisans-have-become-scarce 'Qualified artisans are scarce'], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 August 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Premier Helen Zille led a delegation to China in November 2015 in a bid to secure increased trade and investment opportunities. A report from 2013 estimated that the province's exports to China were valued at over [[South African rand|R]]2 billion (US$131.8 million).<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/11/13/Zille-Winde-lead-delegation-to-China Zille, Winde to lead delegation to China], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 13 November 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe said on 10 October 2018 that youth unemployment should be the main focus of the national job and employment summit, hosted by the [[Government of South Africa|national government]]. The Provincial Department of Economic Development has initiated many employment projects aiming to employ the unemployed youth.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/04/job-summit-can-t-be-allowed-to-become-another-talk-shop Youth unemployment must be key focus of job summit - Alan Winde], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 4 October 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde has been commended for creating a business-friendly environment in the Western Cape since the provincial economy has performed better than the national growth rate.<ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> The Western Cape currently has a lower unemployment rate compared to the national average. Democratic Alliance Federal Leader [[Mmusi Maimane]] called Winde the \"premier of jobs\", when he announced him as the party's candidate.<ref>Mpahlele, Mary Jane. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-premier-candidate-alan-winde-to-focus-on-job-creation-housing-17144485 DA Premier candidate Alan Winde to focus on job creation, housing], ''IOL'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He has received acknowledgement for his economic policies from senior opposition politicians. Deputy President of South Africa and senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] figure [[David Mabuza]] said in September 2019 that the provincial government's economic proposals should be implemented in other ANC-run provinces.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-11-da-premier-alan-winde-gets-surprise-endorsement-from-david-mabuza/ DA premier Alan Winde gets surprise endorsement from David Mabuza], ''TimesLIVE'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019</ref><ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/mabuza-praises-winde-as-a-good-selection-says-plans-are-afoot-to-settle-people-in-the-western-cape-20190911 Mabuza praises Winde as a 'good selection', says plans are afoot to settle people in the Western Cape], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political infighting and corruption===\nDemocratic Alliance party insiders have described Winde as someone who is not involved in party infighting and prioritised on completing his work.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. \n [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 7 April 2019. \"Winde is largely seen within the party as someone who is focused on his job and does not get involved in political infighting.\"</ref>\n\nDuring his premiership, Winde has strongly opposed corruption. He made it mandatory for his provincial ministers to undergo lifestyle audits. He announced in August 2019 that he would probe all the corruption allegations made against his provincial ministers. He made this announcement after the official opposition [[African National Congress]] had called for an investigation into alleged misconduct by the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Winde vows to probe all corruption allegation against MECs |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/30/winde-vows-to-probe-all-corruption-allegation-against-mecs | newspaper=EWN|accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nFollowing Winde's deployment to the Community Safety Department in November 2018, he announced that revised technology would be used to prevent and reduce crime. In the same month, he met with Hanover Park Peace Ambassador, Riedwaan Samuels, who was shot four times in the leg. Winde praised all the young peace ambassadors who were standing up against gang violence and fighting for their communities to be safer. He also met with Western Cape Police Commissioner, Khombinkosi Jula, and discussed that the addition of new police officers would help with the police under-resourcing in the Western Cape.<ref>Maliti, Soyiso. [https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/news/windes-plan-to-fight-crime-using-tech-17759673 Winde's plan to fight crime using tech], ''IOL'', 3 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Mlamla, Sisonke. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/pics-praise-for-hanover-park-peace-ambassador-who-was-shot-17791173 PICS: Praise for Hanover Park Peace Ambassador who was shot], ''IOL'', 6 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/11/09/wc-police-service-boosted-by-addition-of-1-000-new-recruits WC police service boosted by addition of 1,000 new recruits], ''EWN'', 9 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Winde called for the establishment of a provincial police force. In mid-December, [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] farmers requested that the Provincial Community Safety Department allocate more police officers to the area. In response, the Provincial Community Safety Department wrote a letter to the Western Cape Police Commissioner.<ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-wants-provincial-police-force-for-western-cape-20181213 Winde wants provincial police force for Western Cape], ''News24'', 13 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/12/18/philippi-urge-mec-alan-winde-to-urgently-allocate-them-more-police Philippi farmers urge MEC Winde to urgently allocate them more police], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government formally declared an inter-governmental dispute with National Minister of Police [[Bheki Cele]] on 29 April 2019 over police resources allocated to the province.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-04-28-western-cape-government-declares-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-policing/ Western Cape government declares dispute with Bheki Cele over policing], ''TimesLIVE'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/crime/2123896/western-cape-government-declares-formal-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-police-resourcing-da/ Western Cape government declares formal dispute with Bheki Cele over police resourcing \u2013 DA], ''TheCitizen'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref>\n\nSANDF was deployed to the areas of [[Cape Town]] affected by high levels of crime and gang violence in July 2019. Winde welcomed the decision by the [[Department of Defence (South Africa)|National Department of Defence]] to assist the police in its efforts to reduce the city's crime statistics.<ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/go-in-arrest-those-gangsters-w-cape-premier-on-military-move-20190711 Go in, arrest those gangsters: W Cape premier on military move], ''News24'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref><ref>Mabuza, Ernest. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-11-police-minister-bheki-cele-deploys-army-to-crime-ridden-western-cape/ Police minister Bheki Cele deploys army to crime-ridden Western Cape], ''BusinessDay'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref> The deployment was extended in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/winde-welcomes-sandf-extension-but-wants-criminal-justice-system-fixed-33080728 Winde welcomes SANDF extension but wants criminal justice system fixed], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Provincial Minister of Community Safety [[Albert Fritz]] announced on 19 September 2019 that the provincial government would annually be investing R1 billion (US$67.3 million) for three years into the training and deployment of 3,000 safety officers and 150 investigators. A total of 500 safety officers were deployed in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC provincial police service set to be deployed in February |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/05/wc-provincial-police-service-set-to-be-deployed-in-february |accessdate=14 December 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=500 new law enforcement officers deployed to crime hot spots in Cape Town |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/500-new-law-enforcement-officers-deployed-to-crime-hot-spots-in-cape-town-20200210 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The safety plan aims to halve the province's crime statistics within the next decade. Fritz added that the provincial government would also establish an integrated violence prevention programme. The provincial ministers would also be assessed by key performance indicators (KPIs) related to the safety plan.<ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/windes-r1bn-safety-plan-3-000-new-law-enforcement-officers-150-investigators-20190919 Winde's R1bn safety plan: 3 000 new law enforcement officers, 150 investigators], ''News24'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>Buhle, Lindwa. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/premier-winde-announces-western-cape-most-expensive-safety-plan/ Western Cape\u2019s crime-fighting plan: R1-billion, 3000 new officers and more], ''The South African'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.702.co.za/articles/361338/winde-to-appoint-3000-new-officers-in-three-year-wc-safety-plan Winde to appoint 3000 new officers in three-year WC safety plan], ''www.702.co.za'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Agriculture and tourism===\nOne of his duties, as Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities, was to oversee the Tourism Department of the Western Cape Government. He was responsible for projects such as Project Khulisa, a project introduced by the provincial government to increase tourism growth and grow the South African economy. The project resulted in the Western Cape tourism sector growing extensively.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/09/01/WC-Govt-launch-economic-growth-plan WC govt launches economic growth plan], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 1 September 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced that it was investing more than R23 million (US$1.5 million) on increasing the province's agricultural exports and set a target of creating 100,000 jobs in the sector. Winde said that additional support would be given to emerging farmers.<ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/30/WC-govt-invests-over-R23m-on-increasing-agricultural-exports WC govt invests over R23m on increasing agricultural exports], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/31/WC-govt-to-create-more-than-100-thousand-jobs-in-agricultural-sector WC to create over 100,000 jobs in agricultural sector], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cape Town water crisis|drought]] that ravaged the Western Cape province from 2017 to 2018, he argued for farmers to keep hold of their private agricultural water supply, even if their local municipalities had a shortage of water.<ref>Head, Tom. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-alan-winde-western-cape-premier/ Breaking: Alan Winde revealed as the DA\u2019s choice for Western Cape premier], ''The South African'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nDuring a campaign visit to the West Coast region of the Western Cape province on 8 January 2019, Winde urged communities to protect infrastructure. He made this announcement after he witnessed fire-damaged municipal buildings in the town of [[Saldanha Bay]]. The buildings were set on fire during violent protests that occurred in 2018.<ref>Brandt, Kevin. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/01/08/da-wc-premier-candidate-winde-embarks-door-to-door-campaign Winde urges communities to protect infrastructure during door-to-door campaign], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 8 January 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nWinde called for the Western Cape to draw its electricity from natural resources and be independent of [[Eskom|Eskom's]] electricity supply in March 2019.<ref>Mokone, Thabo. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-03-02-da-wants-western-cape-off-eskom-grid/ DA wants Western Cape off Eskom grid], ''TimesLIVE'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref> He said that it is his ambition for the City of Cape Town to become the first city in South Africa to procure electricity from independent suppliers.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/20/alan-winde-says-eskom-crisis-will-cripple-sa-s-economy DA's Winde hopes CT can be the first to get power from independent suppliers], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[Eskom]] announced another round of [[2007\u20132019 South African energy crisis|power outages]]. Winde described the announcement as the \"last straw\" and called on Minister of Energy [[Gwede Mantashe]] to consider a proposal in which municipalities obtain electricity directly from IPPs.<ref>Mabuza, Ernst. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-10-17-alan-winde-asks-gwede-mantashe-to-allow-municipalities-to-procure-clean-energy/ Alan Winde asks Gwede Mantashe to allow municipalities to procure clean energy], ''TimesLIVE'', 17 October 2019. Retrieved on 17 October 2019.</ref> Mantashe, later on, agreed to discuss the matter.<ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-11-19-gwede-mantashe-opens-a-gap-will-discuss-independent-power-for-western-cape/ Gwede Mantashe opens a gap - will 'discuss' independent power for Western Cape], ''SowetanLIVE'', 19 November 2019. Retrieved on 6 December 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, President Ramaphosa announced in his State of the Nation Address that municipalities with an adequate financial standing would be allowed to purchase electricity from IPPs. Winde welcomed the decision and called for it to be expedited.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brandt |first1=Kevin |title=WC Premier Winde looking to quickly implement Ramaphosa's IPP announcement |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/02/14/wc-premier-winde-looking-to-quickly-implement-ramaphosa-s-ipp-announcement-1 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alan Winde}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/alan-winde/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/profile/mr-alan-winde Provincial Minister of Community Safety]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/97 Premier of the Western Cape: Overview]\n* [https://cfo.co.za/article/alan-winde Profile: Alan Winde] at CFO South Africa\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/alan-winde Alan Winde, Mr] at [[Government of South Africa]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Helen Zille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Plato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fritz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=''Position established''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Garth Strachan}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Position dissolved''}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{WCPremiers}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winde, Alan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from Knysna]]\n[[Category:South African businesspeople]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Premiers of the Western Cape]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTenure:It has ended", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Winde"}
