{"title_page": "Pedro Mairal", "text_new": "'''Pedro Mairal''' (born 1970) is an [[Argentinian]] novelist, poet and writer. He has published more than a dozen books, among them the novel ''La Uruguaya'' which won the [[Premio Juan Tigre]] in 2017. His work has been translated into French, German, English and Dutch. In 2007, he was named as one of the [[Bogota39]], a selection of the best young writers in [[Latin America]].<ref>[http://www.formsofworldliterature.com/pedro-mairal/ Bio]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mairal, Pedro}}\n[[Category:Argentine writers]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Pedro Mairal''' (born 1970) is an [[Argentinian]] novelist, poet and writer. He has published more than a dozen books, among them the novel ''La Uruguaya'' which won the [[Premio Juan Tigre]] in 2017. His work has been translated into French, German, English and Dutch. In 2007, he was named as one of the [[Bogota39]], a selection of the best young writers in [[Latin America]].<ref>[http://www.formsofworldliterature.com/pedro-mairal/ Bio]</ref>  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mairal, Pedro}}\n[[category:Argentine writers]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Argentina-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedro_Mairal"}
{"title_page": "Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{| class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width: 22em; margin-bottom: 559px;\" tabindex=\"0\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\" |<span class=\"fn\">Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici</span>\n|}\n'''Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici''' ([[Car\u00fapano]], [[Sucre (state)|estado Sucre]], Venezuela, February 18, 1873 \u2013 [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, August 23, 1954) was a writer, [[playwright]] and [[Venezuelan]] [[diplomat]].\n\n== Biography ==\nCo-founder of the magazine ''Cosm\u00f3polis'' with [[Luis Urbaneja Archepohl]] and his friend and writer [[Pedro Emilio Coll]].He published several works for the magazine ''[[El Cojo Ilustrado]]'' and was the founder of two newspapers of Car\u00fapano, ''El Noticiero'' and ''El Bien P\u00fablico''.  He was director of the ''magazine Venezuela'' between 1905 and 1909 in [[Paris|Par\u00eds]]; this magazine circulated only clandestinely in Venezuela.\n\nRepresented Venezuela in the Government of [[Juan Vicente G\u00f3mez]] as Extraordinary Envoy and [[Plenipotentiary|Minister Plenipotentiary]] in Italy, Spain, England, Argentina, Chile and Uruguay. In 1890 was [[Consul (representative)|General Consul]] in Rome.\n\n== Theater ==\n\n* The Man Who Returned (drama, 1949) \n* The House (Dramatic comedy, 1949)\n* The Sad Venus (Comedy, 1950)\n* Angelica (Dramatic comedy, 1950)\n* The Golden Cage (Dramatic comedy, 1950)\n* Red Love, The Drama of the Crowds, (1951)\n\n== Works ==\n\n* ''Ideas and Impressions'' (Par\u00eds, 1897)\n* ''Voluptuous Sadness'' (Novel, Caracas, 1899)\n* ''The Triumph of the Ideal ''(Novela, Par\u00eds, 1901)\n* ''A Stratopra'' (Novel, Caracas 1901)\n* ''Dionysos'' (Novel, 1904){{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez|1996|p=95}}\n* ''Apollonian Book'' (Chronicles and Essays, Caracas, 1909)\n* ''Vacant Thrones'' (Reviews, Buenos Aires, 1914)\n* ''The Condor'' (Novel, Buenos Aires, 1925)\n* ''Under the Autumn Sun'' (Buenos Aires, 1947)\n* ''Evocation (The novel of an unhappy love)'' (Novel, 1949){{Sfn|Contreras|2010|p=104}}\n\n== Referencias ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite journal|journal=Voz y escritura. Revista de estudios literarios.|number=18|year=2010|last=Contreras|first=\u00c1lvaro|title=La experiencia decadente. Sobre Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici|pages=99\u2013120|url=http://www.saber.ula.ve/bitstream/123456789/32416/1/articulo5.pdf|issn=1315-8392|location=M\u00e9rida|publisher=Editorial Venezolana|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411085445/http://www.saber.ula.ve/bitstream/123456789/32416/1/articulo5.pdf|archivedate=11 April 2016|ref=harv|language=es}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=The Cambridge History of Latin American Literature|volume=2|editor1-first= Roberto|editor1-last= Gonz\u00e1lez Echevarr\u00eda|editor2-first= Enrique|editor2-last= Pupo-Walker|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1996|isbn=0-521-34070-5|title=Modernist prose|first=An\u00edbal|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|pages=69\u2013113|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dominici, Pedro C\u00e9sar}}\n[[Category:People from Car\u00fapano]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan short story writers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Chile]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Spain]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan writers]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Venezuelan Academy of Language]]\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{| class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width: 22em; margin-bottom: 559px;\" tabindex=\"0\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\" |<span class=\"fn\">Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici</span>\n|}\n'''Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici''' ([[Car\u00fapano]], [[Sucre (state)|estado Sucre]], Venezuela, February 18, 1873 \u2013 [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, August 23, 1954) was a writer, [[Playwright|playwright]] and [[Venezuelan]] [[diplomat]].\n\n== Biography ==\nCo-founder of the magazine ''Cosm\u00f3polis'' with [[Luis Urbaneja Archepohl]] and his friend and writer [[Pedro Emilio Coll]].He published several works for the magazine ''[[El Cojo Ilustrado]]'' and was the founder of two newspapers of Car\u00fapano, ''El Noticiero'' and ''El Bien P\u00fablico''.  He was director of the ''magazine Venezuela'' between 1905 and 1909 in [[Paris|Par\u00eds]]; this magazine circulated only clandestinely in Venezuela.\n\nRepresented Venezuela in the Government of [[Juan Vicente G\u00f3mez]] as Extraordinary Envoy and [[Plenipotentiary|Minister Plenipotentiary]] in Italy, Spain, England, Argentina, Chile and Uruguay. In 1890 was [[Consul (representative)|General Consul]] in Rome.\n\n== Theater ==\n\n* The Man Who Returned (drama, 1949) \n* The House (Dramatic comedy, 1949)\n* The Sad Venus (Comedy, 1950)\n* Angelica (Dramatic comedy, 1950)\n* The Golden Cage (Dramatic comedy, 1950)\n* Red Love, The Drama of the Crowds, (1951)\n\n== Works ==\n\n* ''Ideas and Impressions'' (Par\u00eds, 1897)\n* ''Voluptuous Sadness'' (Novel, Caracas, 1899)\n* ''The Triumph of the Ideal ''(Novela, Par\u00eds, 1901)\n* ''A Stratopra'' (Novel, Caracas 1901)\n* ''Dionysos'' (Novel, 1904){{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez|1996|p=95}}\n* ''Apollonian Book'' (Chronicles and Essays, Caracas, 1909)\n* ''Vacant Thrones'' (Reviews, Buenos Aires, 1914)\n* ''The Condor'' (Novel, Buenos Aires, 1925)\n* ''Under the Autumn Sun'' (Buenos Aires, 1947)\n* ''Evocation (The novel of an unhappy love)'' (Novel, 1949){{Sfn|Contreras|2010|p=104}}\n\n== Referencias ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite journal|journal=Voz y escritura. Revista de estudios literarios.|number=18|year=2010|last=Contreras|first=\u00c1lvaro|title=La experiencia decadente. Sobre Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici|pages=99-120|url=http://www.saber.ula.ve/bitstream/123456789/32416/1/articulo5.pdf|issn=1315-8392|location=M\u00e9rida|publisher=Editorial Venezolana|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411085445/http://www.saber.ula.ve/bitstream/123456789/32416/1/articulo5.pdf|archivedate=11 April 2016|ref=harv|language=es}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=The Cambridge History of Latin American Literature|volume=2|editor1-first= Roberto|editor1-last= Gonz\u00e1lez Echevarr\u00eda|editor2-first= Enrique|editor2-last= Pupo-Walker|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1996|isbn=0-521-34070-5|title=Modernist prose|first=An\u00edbal|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|pages=69-113|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Pedro C\u00e9sar Dominici}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dominici, Pedro C\u00e9sar}}\n[[Category:People from Car\u00fapano]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan short story writers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Chile]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Spain]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Venezuela to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan writers]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Venezuelan Academy of Language]]\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedro_C%C3%A9sar_Dominici"}
{"title_page": "The Infinite Way", "text_new": "'''The Infinite Way''' is a spiritual movement and activity created by 20th century [[United States|American]] healer, mystic and lecturer [[Joel S. Goldsmith]] (1892&ndash;1964). According to Goldsmith, the Message of the Infinite Way  is a spiritual teaching consisting of principles which anyone may follow and practice, irrespective of their religious affiliation. The Infinite Way reveals the nature of [[God]] to be one infinite power, intelligence, and love; the nature of the individual being to be one with God's qualities and character, expressed in infinite forms and variety; and the nature of the discords of this world to be a misconception of God's expression of Himself in His universe.\"<ref>Goldsmith, J.S. (1992) ''The Art of Spiritual Healing.'' HarperCollins. p 40.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nGoldsmith started teaching the lessons of the Infinite Way in 1940 and in 1947 published the book, ''The Infinite Way''.<ref>Beverely, J.A. (2009) ''Nelson's Illustrated Guide to Religions.'' Thomas Nelson Inc. p 108.</ref> He began teaching and lecturing extensively that year, first in [[New England]], then on the [[West Coast of the United States]] and finally in Hawaii. In 1950, Goldsmith began recording his lectures world-wide.<ref>Melton, J.G. (2003) ''Encyclopedia of American Religions.'' Gale. p 743-44.</ref> \n\n== Framework ==\n\"'The Infinite Way' is not a religion... but an experience in spiritual living. There is no organization, no structure, no rules, no church buildings, no congregation, no dues, and no bureaucracy. 'The Infinite Way' is composed solely of the inspired works of Joel Goldsmith based on his revelations and experiences: the more than fifty-one books he authored, and the more than twelve hundred hours of his lectures and classes.\"<ref>Covell, O.D. (2005) ''Taking the Path to Spiritual Awakening.'' AuthorHouse. p IX.</ref>\n\nDuring his life Joel Goldsmith asked for no remuneration for his healing work but he did take it if offered. He also did not participate in overt advertisement of his books and tapes, knowing instead that people would find them as they needed them.<ref>Sinkler, L. (1973) ''The Spiritual Journey of Joel S. Goldsmith, Modern Mystic.'' Harper & Row.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christian Science]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://joelgoldsmith.com/|JoelGoldsmith.com}}, official office and website for study, resources, and access to the purchase of all copywrited Joel Goldsmith materials, audio tapes (1300+), tape transcripts, books,  pamphlets, etc; electronic search tool feature, accessing all Joel Goldsmith writings and recordings, etc; .[http://www.joelgoldsmith.com/faq.html]\n*https://goldsmithglobal.org<nowiki/>  site offering online tape groups, related study, meditations, and resources\n*https://www.acropolisbooks.com/, official publisher of the complete library of all Joel Goldsmith written materials, (print and e-books, pamphlets, etc with brief explanation of each book or pamphlet).  Large free library of Infinite Way information and study materials, free electronic concordance-style search tool, accessing all Joel Goldsmith writings and recordings.\n*https://iwstudentcontactcenter.com/, Infinite Way resource site, with a searchable database of Infinite Way teachers, practitioners, and students.\n* \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Infinite Way}}\n[[Category:New Thought movement]]\n[[Category:Spirituality]]\n[[Category:Panentheism]]\n[[Category:New religious movements]]\n", "text_old": "'''The Infinite Way''' is a spiritual movement and activity created by 20th century [[United States|American]] healer, mystic and lecturer [[Joel S. Goldsmith]] (1892&ndash;1964). According to Goldsmith, the Message of the Infinite Way  is a spiritual teaching consisting of principles which anyone may follow and practice, irrespective of their religious affiliation. The Infinite Way reveals the nature of [[God]] to be one infinite power, intelligence, and love; the nature of the individual being to be one with God's qualities and character, expressed in infinite forms and variety; and the nature of the discords of this world to be a misconception of God's expression of Himself in His universe.\"<ref>Goldsmith, J.S. (1992) ''The Art of Spiritual Healing.'' HarperCollins. p 40.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nGoldsmith started teaching the lessons of the Infinite Way in 1940 and in 1947 published the book, ''The Infinite Way''.<ref>Beverely, J.A. (2009) ''Nelson's Illustrated Guide to Religions.'' Thomas Nelson Inc. p 108.</ref> He began teaching and lecturing extensively that year, first in [[New England]], then on the [[West Coast of the United States]] and finally in Hawaii. In 1950, Goldsmith began recording his lectures world-wide.<ref>Melton, J.G. (2003) ''Encyclopedia of American Religions.'' Gale. p 743-44.</ref> \n\n== Framework ==\n\"'The Infinite Way' is not a religion... but an experience in spiritual living. There is no organization, no structure, no rules, no church buildings, no congregation, no dues, and no bureaucracy. 'The Infinite Way' is composed solely of the inspired works of Joel Goldsmith based on his revelations and experiences: the more than fifty-one books he authored, and the more than twelve hundred hours of his lectures and classes.\"<ref>Covell, O.D. (2005) ''Taking the Path to Spiritual Awakening.'' AuthorHouse. p IX.</ref>\n\nDuring his life Joel Goldsmith asked for no remuneration for his healing work but he did take it if offered. He also did not participate in overt advertisement of his books and tapes, knowing instead that people would find them as they needed them.<ref>Sinkler, L. (1973) ''The Spiritual Journey of Joel S. Goldsmith, Modern Mystic.'' Harper & Row.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christian Science]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://joelgoldsmith.com/|JoelGoldsmith.com}}, official office and website for study, resources, and access to the purchase of all copywrited Joel Goldsmith materials, audio tapes (1700+), tape transcripts, books,  pamphlets, etc; free concordance-style search tool, accessing all Joel Goldsmith writings and recordings, etc; .[http://www.joelgoldsmith.com/faq.html]\n*https://goldsmithglobal.org<nowiki/>  site offering online tape groups, related study, meditations, and resources\n*https://www.acropolisbooks.com/, official publisher of the complete library of all Joel Goldsmith written materials, (print and e-books, pamphlets, etc).  Large free library of Infinite Way information and study materials, free concordance-style search tool, accessing all Joel Goldsmith writings and recordings.\n*https://iwstudentcontactcenter.com/, Infinite Way resource site, with a searchable database of Infinite Way teachers, practitioners, and students.\n* \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Infinite Way}}\n[[Category:New Thought movement]]\n[[Category:Spirituality]]\n[[Category:Panentheism]]\n[[Category:New religious movements]]\n", "name_user": "Michaelkrupp", "label": "safe", "comment": "number of tapes offered changed from 1700+ to 1300+ plus more robust description of Acropolis Books", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Infinite_Way"}
